ack \u2013 [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] | conference = no | startyear = 2018 | endyear = }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry | championship = | season = [[2018-19 Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team|2018\u201319]] | name = Chris Mack | overall = 20\u201314 | conference = 10\u20138 | confstanding = T\u20136th | postseason = [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Round of 64]] | ranking = no| ranking2 =no}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry | championship = | season = [[2019-20 Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team|2019\u201320]] | name = Chris Mack | overall = 24\u20137 | conference = 15\u20135 | confstanding = T\u20132nd | postseason = [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Cancelled]] | ranking = no| ranking2 =no}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n |name          =[[Chris Mack (basketball)|Chris Mack]]\n |overall       = 44\u201321\n |confrecord    = 25\u201313\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End | overall  = 1,869*\u2013926 | poll = two | polltype= | polltype2 = }}\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> Vacated, Louisville forfeited 123 wins during 2011\u20132014, its NCAA tournament appearances, and its 2013 National Championship title.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/02/20/louisville-basketball-will-vacate-2013-national-championship-as-ncaa-upholds-ruling/</ref> <br />\nKIAC \u2013 [[Kentucky Intercollegiate Athletic Conference]]<br />\nSIAA \u2013 [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]]<br />\nNAIB \u2013 [[National Association for Intercollegiate Basketball]]<br />\nNAIA \u2013 [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] was NAIB until 1952 when they picked up other sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naiahoops.com/page/history.php |title=History & Archives |publisher=NAIA Hoops |accessdate=March 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121185725/http://www.naiahoops.com/page/history.php |archivedate=November 21, 2011 }}</ref><br />\nNIT \u2013 [[National Invitation Tournament]]<br />\nNCAA \u2013 [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]\n\n==Rivalries==\n===Kentucky Wildcats===\nThe [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]]\u2013Louisville rivalry has been ranked the 2nd best rivalry in college basketball by Bleacher Report and 3rd best rivalry in all of college sports by [[List of members of the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Basketball Hall of Fame]] contributor [[Dick Vitale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/dickvitale/story/_/id/7561633/dick-vitale-picks-best-rivalries-college-sports|title=Dick Vitale picks the best rivalries in college sports|work=ESPN.com}}</ref> Kentucky and Louisville first played against each other in 1913 but stopped playing each other in the 1920s, playing only twelve times between 1913 and 1983.   The rivalry was generally dormant with only occasional matchups until the teams met in the [[1983 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1983 NCAA Tournament]].  Since then, the two teams have met each year in late December or early January.\n\nMuch like the [[Iron Bowl]], the Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry is all the more intense because the two schools have consistently been among the nation's elite men's basketball teams for most of the last 50 years.  Both schools are also two of the most victorious programs in [[NCAA]] men's basketball history; Kentucky is #1 on the list of all-time [[List of teams with the most victories in NCAA Division I men's college basketball|winningest program]]s in [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] Men's Basketball and Louisville #26 (#10 including vacated victories).  Kentucky has eight national championships while Louisville has two (official)(3 including the vacated 2013 championship) national championships.\n\n===Cincinnati Bearcats===\n{{main|Cincinnati\u2013Louisville rivalry#Men's Basketball}}\n\nWhile predominantly a football rivalry, the proximity and long-standing conference affiliation of Cincinnati and Louisville made this into a key rivalry, particularly in the days of the [[Metro Conference|Metro]] and [[Big East Conference|Big East]] conferences.  This rivalry went on hiatus in 2014 when Louisville left the [[American Athletic Conference]] for the ACC.\n\n==Notable Cardinals==\n{{See also|List of University of Louisville people}}\n\n===Retired numbers===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\"  style=\"float:right; width:250px;\"\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center; {{CollegePrimaryStyle|Louisville Cardinals|color=white}};\"| '''Retired numbers'''\n|-\n!Number\n!Player\n!Years\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| 8 || [[Charlie Tyra]] || 1954\u201357\n|-\n| 31 || [[Wes Unseld]] || 1966\u201368\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| 35 || [[Darrell Griffith]] || 1977\u201380\n|-\n| 42 || [[Pervis Ellison]] || 1986\u201389\n|}\n\nLouisville basketball has honored four former players by retiring their numbers. These are the last players to wear these numbers for a Louisville men's squad:\n\n* '''Charlie Tyra #8''' \u2013 A consensus All-American during the 1956 and 1957 seasons, Charlie Tyra led the University of Louisville to its first NIT title in 1956 and was named the tournament's MVP for his performance. Tyra was named Helms Athletic Foundation All-American in his junior and senior years. One of only five Cardinals to record over 1,000 rebounds in his career, Tyra ranks as the all-time rebounder in U of L history with 1,617. During the 1955\u201356 season, Tyra pulled down 645 rebounds, a mark that has been bettered by only three other players in NCAA history. He set the Louisville record for most rebounds in a game when he pulled down 38 against Canisius during the 1955\u201356 season. In his four seasons with Louisville, he helped his teams to a combined record of 88\u201323 and three straight NIT appearances. Tyra ranks third in career free throws made (448), second in career rebounding average (17.0), fourth in career scoring average (18.2), eighth in career scorers (1,728 points) and eighth in field goals made (640). Tyra is one of only four players in UofL history to score 40 points or more in a game (achieved against Notre Dame when he hit 12 of 16 field goals and all 16 of his free throw attempts). Tyra died on December 29, 2006, at the age of 71. He was drafted #2 by in the [[Detroit Pistons]] in the [[1957 NBA draft]].\n* '''Wes Unseld #31''' \u2013 When Wes Unseld ended his career with the University of Louisville following the 1967\u201368 season, he left as the Cardinals' all-time leading scorer for a three-year player. Today, Unseld ranks 10th on the all-time scoring list, but his career point total of 1,686 is still tops for a three-year player. A consensus All-American during his junior and senior years, Unseld is one of only five other Cardinal players to pull down over 1,000 rebounds in his career. His 1,551 career rebounds ranks second behind Tyra's 1,617. Unseld began his senior season with a 45-point effort against Georgetown College, a UofL record that still stands today. Unseld, chosen as second player overall in the NBA draft by Baltimore, was honored on the All-Missouri Valley Conference team all three years at UofL and the Cardinals were 60\u201322 during his three seasons. During his junior year, Unseld led the Cardinals to a final No. 2 ranking in both wire service polls. Unseld's 20.6 scoring average still ranks as the top scoring average in Louisville history. His 18.9 rebounding average also ranks as the top average for a Cardinal. While playing on the Cardinals' freshmen team, Unseld averaged 35.8 points and 23.6 rebounds, and hit 68.6 percent from the field. \n* '''Darrell Griffith #35''' \u2013 The 1980 Player of the Year and consensus first team All-American led Louisville to four consecutive NCAA tournament appearances, winning the 1980 Championship as he had promised when he committed to his hometown Cardinals. Griffith's career 2333 points and single-season 825 points rank first in Louisville history. He scored in double figures in 41 straight games and 111 of his 126 games with the Cardinals. His play earned him the nickname \"Dr. Dunkenstein\".<ref>John Papanek. \"[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1124021/index.htm A Rookie Gives The Jazz Pizzazz]\". ''Sports Illustrated''. December 8, 1980. Retrieved on February 1, 2010.</ref>  He was drafted #2 by the [[Utah Jazz]] in the [[1980 NBA draft]].\n* '''Pervis Ellison #42''' \u2013 Ellison won the 1986 NCAA Tournament MOP award after leading the Cardinals to their second NCAA Tournament Championship. A consensus first team All-American in 1989, he is the only Louisville player to score 2000 points and grab 1000 rebounds in a career. His 374 career rejections rank first at Louisville and ranked Ellison third all time in the NCAA when he left in 1989. He was drafted #1 by the [[Sacramento Kings]] in the [[1989 NBA draft]].\n\n===Cardinals in the Hall of Fame===\nLouisville has three representatives in the [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]]: Cardinal All-American and former Washington Bullets All-Star [[Wes Unseld]], who was inducted in 1988, former coach [[Denny Crum]], who was inducted in 1994, and coach [[Rick Pitino]], who was inducted in 2013. [[Darrell Griffith]], a national player of the year and consensus All-American at the University of Louisville, is part of the 2014 induction class for the National Collegiate Basketball Hall of Fame.\n\n===National Player of the Year awards===\n* 1980 \u2013 Darrell Griffith ([[John R. Wooden Award]])\n\n===All-Americans===\nTwenty one Louisville players have earned 25 [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All American]] selections. 7 players received 8 consensus All-American selections.<ref>{{cite web|title=Division I Consensus All-American Selections|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/m_basketball_RB/2010/Awards.pdf|work=Division I Consensus All-American Selections|publisher=NCAA|accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Louisville All-Americans|url=http://www.guide.provations.com/louisville/cardinalbb2010#pg130|work=Louisville All-Americans|publisher=University of Louisville Athletic Department|accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Consensus selections====\n* [[1957 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1957]]\u2013 [[Charlie Tyra]]\n* [[1967 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1967]]\u2013 [[Wes Unseld]]\n* [[1968 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1968]]\u2013 [[Wes Unseld]]\n* [[1972 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1972]]\u2013 [[Jim Price (basketball)|Jim Price]]\n* [[1980 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1980]]\u2013 [[Darrell Griffith]]\n* [[1989 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1989]]\u2013 [[Pervis Ellison]]\n* [[1994 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1994]]\u2013 [[Clifford Rozier]]\n* [[2014 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2014]]\u2013 [[Russ Smith (basketball)|Russ Smith]]\n\n====Other selections====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[1956 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1956]]\u2013 [[Charlie Tyra]]\n* [[1959 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1959]]\u2013 [[Don Goldstein]]\n* [[1961 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1961]]\u2013 John Turner\n* [[1966 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1966]]\u2013 [[Wes Unseld]]\n* [[1969 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1969]]\u2013 [[Butch Beard]]\n* [[1975 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1975]]\u2013 [[Junior Bridgeman]] & [[Allen Murphy]]\n* [[1976 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1976]]\u2013 [[Phil Bond]]\n* [[1977 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1977]]\u2013 [[Wesley Cox]]\n{{col-2}}\n* [[1978 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1978]]\u2013 [[Rick Wilson (basketball)|Rick Wilson]]\n* [[1979 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1979]]\u2013 [[Darrell Griffith]]\n* [[1984 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1984]]\u2013 [[Lancaster Gordon]]\n* [[1997 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1997]]\u2013 [[DeJuan Wheat]]\n* [[2003 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2003]]\u2013 [[Reece Gaines]]\n* [[2005 NCAA Men's Ba