sk]], Soviet Union\n|}\n\n===IAAF world records===\n[[File:2012 Olympics - Womens 5000m Dibaba leading.jpg|thumb|Current women's world record holder [[Tirunesh Dibaba]] (right) leading former world record holder [[Meseret Defar]] (centre) at the 2012 Olympic 5000&nbsp;m final]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Time\n!Athlete\n!Date\n!Location\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''12:05:00'''\n|Alannahg99\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2020 - 04-20\n|England \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''15:13.22'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Anne Audain]]|NZL}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1982-03-17\n|[[Auckland]], New Zealand<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''15:08.26'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Mary Decker|Mary Decker-Slaney]]|USA}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1982-07-05\n|[[Eugene, Oregon]], United States<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:58.89'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Ingrid Kristiansen]]|NOR}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1984-06-28\n|[[Oslo]], Norway<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:48.07'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Zola Budd]]|GBR}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1985-08-26\n|London, United Kingdom<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:37.33'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Ingrid Kristiansen]]|NOR}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1986-08-05\n|[[Stockholm]], Sweden<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:36.45'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Fernanda Ribeiro]]|POR}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1995-07-22\n|[[Hechtel-Eksel|Hechtel]], Belgium<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:31.27'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Dong Yanmei]]|CHN}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1997-10-21\n|Shanghai, [[China]]<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:28.09'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Jiang Bo (athlete)|Jiang Bo]]|CHN}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1997-10-23\n|Shanghai, [[China]]<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:24.68'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Elvan Abeylegesse]]|TUR}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2004-06-11\n|[[Bergen]], Norway<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:24.53'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Meseret Defar]]|ETH|1996}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2006-06-03\n|New York, United States<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:16.63'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Meseret Defar]]|ETH|1996}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007-06-15\n|[[Oslo]], Norway<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14:11.15'''\n|{{flagathlete|[[Tirunesh Dibaba]]|ETH|1996}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008-06-06\n|[[Oslo]], Norway<ref name=iaaf2/>\n|}\n\n{{flagathlete|[[Zola Budd]]|RSA|1928}} ran 15:01.83 in 1984, but this time was not ratified as a world record.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Athletics record progressions}}\n\n[[Category:World athletics record progressions]]\n[[Category:5000 metres|World record]]\n[[Category:Articles which contain graphical timelines]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:5609:5300:f845:d63f:1415:1aeb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/5000_metres_world_record_progression"}
{"title_page": "Jessica Meir", "text_new": "{{Short description|astronaut, physiologist}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox astronaut\n| name          = Jessica Meir\n| image         = Jessica Meir official portrait in an EMU.jpg\n| caption       = Jessica Meir in 2019\n\n| type          = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| status        = Active\n| nationality   = American and Swedish dual citizenship\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1977|7|1}}\n| birth_place   = [[Caribou, Maine]], U.S.\n| occupation    = astronaut, [[physiologist]]\n| selection     = [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|2013 NASA Group]]\n| evas          = 3\n| eva_time      = 21h 44m\n| alma_mater    = [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]]<br/>{{nowrap|[[International Space University]]}}<br/>[[Brown University]]\n| space_time    =  204d 15h 19m 00s\n| mission       = [[Soyuz MS-15]] ([[Expedition 61]]/[[Expedition 62|62]])\n| insignia      = [[File:Soyuz-MS-15-Mission-Patch.png|50px]] [[File:ISS Expedition 61 Patch.svg |45px]] [[File:ISS Expedition 62 Patch.png|45px]]\n| module            = \n  {{Infobox scientist | embed=yes\n  | fields            = {{ublist|[[Marine biology]]|[[comparative physiology]]}}\n  | workplaces        = {{ublist|[[Harvard Medical School]]|[[NASA]]}}\n  | thesis_title      = Blood oxygen transport and depletion: The key of consummate divers\n  | thesis_url        = https://search.proquest.com/docview/304852089\n  | thesis_year       = 2009\n  | doctoral_advisor  = Paul Ponganis\n  | academic_advisors = Bill Milsom (post doc)\n  | doctoral_students = \n  | notable_students  = \n  | known_for         = \n  | influences        = \n  | influenced        = \n  | awards            = \n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Jessica Ulrika Meir''' ([[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]: {{IPAc-en|m|\u026a\u0259r|}}; {{respell|m|eer|}}; born July 1, 1977) is a [[NASA]] astronaut, marine biologist, and  physiologist. She was previously Assistant Professor of Anesthesia at [[Harvard Medical School]], [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], [[Boston]], following [[postdoctoral research]] in [[comparative physiology]] at the [[University of British Columbia]].<ref name=\"Abstract\">{{cite journal |title=Point: Counterpoint \"High Altitude is / is not for the Birds!\" |last1=Scott |first1=Graham R. |last2=Meir |first2=Jessica Ulrika |last3=Hawkes |first3=Lucy A. |last4=Frappell |first4=Peter B. |last5=Milsom |first5=William K. |last6=Llanos |first6=Anibal J. |last7=Ebensperger |first7=German |last8=Herrera |first8=Emilio A. |last9=Reyes |first9=Roberto Victor |last10=Moraga |first10=Fernando A. |last11=Parer |first11=Julian T. |last12=Giussani |first12=Dino A. |date=July 1, 2011 |publisher=[[American Physiological Society]] |doi=10.1152/japplphysiol.00821.2011 |pmid=21737822 |journal=[[Journal of Applied Physiology]] |volume=111 |issue=5 |pages=1514\u20131515}}</ref><ref name=\"Astronaut\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013astroclass.html |title=2013 Astronaut Class |url-status=live |last1=Roberts |first1=Jason |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=June 19, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621011402/http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013astroclass.html |archivedate=June 21, 2013}}</ref> She has studied the diving physiology and behavior of [[emperor penguin]]s in [[Antarctica]],<ref name=\"Science Daily\">{{cite news |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/05/110512083139.htm |title=Penguins continue diving long after muscles run out of oxygen |date=May 12, 2011 |last=Knight |first=Kathryn |work=[[Science Daily]] |accessdate=November 17, 2011}}</ref> and the physiology of [[Bar-headed goose|bar-headed geese]], which are able to migrate over the [[Himalayas]].<ref name=\"ISNS\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usnews.com/science/articles/2011/04/15/skys-no-limit-in-high-flying-goose-chase |title=Sky's No Limit in High-Flying Goose Chase |last=Arnold |first=Carrie |date=April 15, 2011 |magazine=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref> In September 2002, Meir served as an [[aquanaut]] on the [[NEEMO|NASA Extreme Environment Mission Operations]] 4 ([[NEEMO#NEEMO 4: September 23\u201327, 2002|NEEMO 4]]) crew.<ref name=\"four\">{{cite web |url=http://lsda.jsc.nasa.gov/scripts/mission/miss.cfm?mis_index=213 |title=Life Sciences Data Archive: Experiment |access-date=November 16, 2011 |website=NASA |date=April 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322172426/http://lsda.jsc.nasa.gov/scripts/mission/miss.cfm?mis_index=213 |archive-date=March 22, 2012|df=}}</ref> In 2013 she was selected by NASA to [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|Astronaut Group 21]]. Meir launched on September 25, 2019, to the [[International Space Station|ISS]] onboard [[Soyuz MS-15]], where she served as a flight Engineer during [[Expedition 61]] and [[Expedition 62|62]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Astronaut from Maine prepares for takeoff |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2019/09/08/maine-astronaut-jessica-meir-prepares-for-her-launch/ |newspaper=[[Portland Press Herald]] |accessdate=September 24, 2019 |last1=Graham |first1=Gillian |date=September 8, 2019}}</ref> On October 18, 2019, Meir and [[Christina Koch]] were the first women to participate in an all-female [[spacewalk]]. The Soyuz capsule carrying Jessica Meir and fellow astronauts Andrew Morgan and Oleg Skripochka touched down on Friday April 17, 2020 near the town of Dzhezkazgan, Kazakhstan, at 11.16am local time.<ref>{{cite news |title=ASTRONAUTS RETURN TO EARTH AFTER WATCHING CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK FROM INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/nasa-landing-astronauts-launch-space-international-station-a9470281.html}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nJessica Meir was born in [[Caribou, Maine|Caribou]], [[Maine]], to a [[Swedes|Swedish]] mother who was a nurse and an Israeli father of [[History of the Jews in Iraq|Iraqi-Jewish]] descent, who worked as a physician. Her mother is from [[V\u00e4ster\u00e5s]], Sweden; her father was born in [[Iraq]] and moved to [[Israel]] as a child. He later moved to [[Sweden]] where he met Meir's mother who grew up in a Christian family. The couple moved to Maine, US where Meir was born.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.jpost.com/Israeli-women/Swedish-Israeli-NASA-astronaut-Jessica-Meir-gets-ready-for-space-589217 |title=Swedish-Israeli NASA astronaut Jessica Meir gets ready for space |last=Dolsten |first=Josefin |date=May 9, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url-status=live |access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlthough her mother did not convert, Meir grew up attending synagogue in [[Presque Isle, Maine]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She was inspired to venture into space after watching the [[Space Shuttle]] missions on television. Meir knew no one who worked for NASA or for the space program. She attributes her abiding dream of personally participating in space exploration to the love of nature she learned from her mother, and from her father's predilection for wandering and adventure. \"And it might have had something to do with the fact that the stars shone so brightly in rural Maine\", Meir added.<ref name=\"TimesofIsrael\">{{cite news |first=Renee |last=Ghert-Zand |date=June 1, 2018 |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/no-risk-no-reward-says-fearless-jewish-astronaut-jessica-meir/ |title=No Risk, No Reward Says Fearless Jewish Astronaut Jessica Meir |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 13, Meir attended a youth space camp at [[Purdue University]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2019/04/17/news/aroostook/astronaut-from-aroostook-county-will-soon-go-on-her-1st-spaceflight/ |title=Astronaut from Aroostook County will soon go on her 1st spaceflight |newspaper=[[Bangor Daily News]] |access-date=May 9, 2019 |last1=Burns |first1=Christopher |date=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html |title=Meet Jessica Meir |website=NASA Quest |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030504145149/http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html |archive-date=May 4, 2003 |access-date=October 20, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"wp-2015apr28\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/kidspost/journey-to-mars-jessica-meir/2015/04/28/29d206a0-b11b-11e4-886b-c22184f27c35_story.html |title=Journey to Mars: Meet NASA astronaut candidate Jessica Meir |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |date=April 28, 2015 |first=Sarah |last=Kaplan}}</ref> During her undergraduate biology studies at [[Brown University]], she also spent a semester in a study abroad program in Stockholm and ran a student experiment on a NASA [[reduced gravity aircraft]] \"vomit comet\" in her senior year.<ref name=\"TimesofIsrael\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Meir graduated from Brown in 1999 with a Bachelor of Arts Degree in Biology, with Honors, magna cum laude.<ref name=\"thesis\" /> In 2000, Meir graduated with a Master of Space Studies from the [[International Space University]] in [[Strasbourg, France]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.isunet.edu/news/success-stories/jessica-meir-mss00/226 |title=Three I's of ISU Influential to 2013 NASA Astronaut Candidate Jessica Meir |work=[[International Space University]] |year=2013 |access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref> \n\n===Comparative physiology research===\nMeir earned a Ph.D. in [[marine biology]] in 2009 from the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] for research on the [[diving physiology]] of [[emperor penguin]]s and [[northern elephant seal]]s.<ref name=\"thesis\">{{cite thesis |last=Meir |first=Jessica Ulrika |date=2009 |title=Blood oxygen transport and depletion: The key of consummate divers |degree=Ph.D. |isbn=978-1-109-31853-1 |institution=[[University of California, San Diego]] |oclc=449187875 |id={{ProQuest|304852089}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=What triggers the aerobic dive limit? Patterns of muscle oxygen depletion during dives of emperor penguins |journal=[[The Journal of Experimental Biology]] |date=June 1, 2011 |volume=214 |issue=11 |pages=1802\u20131812 |doi=10.1242/jeb.052233 |url=http://jeb.biologists.org/content/214/11/1802.abstract |pmid=21562166 |pmc=3092726 |last1=Williams |first1=CL |last2=Meir |first2=JU |last3=Ponganis |first3=PJ}}</ref><ref name=\"Students\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/article/secrets-worlds-extreme-divers |title=Secrets of the world's extreme divers |last=Kwok |first=Roberta |date=April 24, 2011 |work=[[Science News for Students]] |accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref>  Meir performed field work at ''Penguin Ranch''  on [[McMurdo Sound]] in [[Antarctica]] to study the diving abilities of the emperor penguin while [[scuba diving]] alongside them under the ice.<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Ponganis |url=https://www.nsf.gov/discoveries/disc_summ.jsp?cntn_id=111170 |title=A Season at the Penguin Ranch in Antarctica|work=[[National Science Foundation]] |date=May 19, 2008 |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Students\"/>  She also studied elephant seals while they were diving in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off [[Northern California]].<ref name=\"Students\"/>\n\nMeir did post-doctoral research at the University of British Columbia, raising [[Bar-headed Goose|bar-headed geese]] so their tolerance of high altitude and low oxygen levels during flight over the [[Himalayas]] could be studied in a controlled environment.<ref name=\"ISNS\"/><ref name=\"Students\"/> For the 2012 academic year she continued her research as an assistant professor of [[anesthesia]] at the Harvard Medical School/Massachusetts General Hospital and then took a leave of absence to enter the astronaut corps.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2013/09/destination-space/ |first1=Alvin |last1=Powell |title=Destination Space |website=[[The Harvard Gazette]] |date=September 6, 2013 |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== NASA career ==\nAfter getting her master's degree, Meir worked from 2000\u20132003 for [[Lockheed Martin]] Space Operations as an experiment support scientist for the Human Research Facility at the [[NASA]] [[Johnson Space Center]] (JSC) in [[Houston, Texas]].<ref name=nasabio /><ref name=\"Antarctica\">{{cite web|url=http://womeninantarctica.com/portraits/jessica.html|title=Jessica Meir, Emperor Penguin Researcher in Antarctica\n|last=Price|first=Mary Lynn|website=Women Working in Antarctica|accessdate=November 19, 2011}}</ref> Meir coordinated and supported human space life science experiments that were performed by [[astronaut]]s on [[Space Shuttle]] and [[International Space Station]] (ISS) missions. These experiments included physiological studies (bone loss, muscle control/atrophy, lung function, etc.) to determine if any bodily processes were altered in the spaceflight environment. Meir guided these experiments through the necessary review cycles, developed procedures that the astronauts would use on-orbit, trained crew members, and provided ground support in the Mission Control Center while the astronauts were performing the experiments on the shuttle or ISS.<ref name=\"NASA Quest Bio\">{{cite web|url=http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html|title=:: NASA Quest > Space :: Meet Jessica Meir|access-date=November 19, 2011|last=Meir|first=Jessica|publisher=[[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030504145149/http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html|archive-date=May 4, 2003|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2002, Meir served as an [[aquanaut]] on the joint NASA-[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]] [[NEEMO#NEEMO 4: September 23\u201327, 2002|NEEMO 4]] expedition (NASA Extreme Environment Mission Operations), an exploration research mission held in [[Aquarius (laboratory)|Aquarius]], an [[Underwater habitat|undersea research laboratory]] four miles off shore from [[Key Largo]]. Meir and her crewmates spent five days [[saturation diving]] from the Aquarius habitat as a [[Human analog missions|space analogue]] for working and training under extreme environmental conditions. The mission was delayed due to [[Hurricane Isadore]], forcing National Undersea Research Center managers to shorten it to an underwater duration of five days. Then, three days into their underwater mission, the crew members were told that [[Hurricane Lili|Tropical Storm Lili]] was headed in their direction and to prepare for an early departure from Aquarius. Fortunately, Lili degenerated to the point where it was no longer a threat, so the crew was able to remain the full five days.<ref name=\"four\"/><ref name=\"history\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/NEEMO/history.html|title=NEEMO History|accessdate=November 16, 2011|work=NASA|date=March 21, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061008171834/http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/NEEMO/history.html|archivedate=October 8, 2006}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of NEEMO 4, Meir was leaning toward pursuing a [[PhD]] in a field related to [[evolutionary biology]] and/or life in [[extreme environment]]s ([[astrobiology]]). She was also fascinated by [[marine biology]] (which suited the [[NEEMO]] mission well), and hoped to coordinate a specific topic of study to combine these main interests.<ref name=\"NASA Quest Bio\"/> She received her PhD in marine biology from [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]], studying diving physiology, in 2009.<ref name=\"nasabio\" />\n\nIn 2009, Meir was a semi-finalist for selection to [[NASA Astronaut Group 20]].<ref name=\"Spacefacts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/candidates/nasa20/english/meir_jessica.htm |title=Biographies of Astronaut and Cosmonaut Candidates: Jessica Meir |date=March 27, 2010 |work=Spacefacts |access-date=November 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227090109/http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/candidates/nasa20/english/meir_jessica.htm |archive-date=February 27, 2014 |first1=Joachim Wilhelm Josef |last1=Becker |first2=Heinz Hermann |last2=Janssen}}</ref> For the next selection group in June 2013, Meir was chosen as one of eight astronaut candidates for training in [[NASA Astronaut Group 21]].<ref name=\"Astronaut\"/> She completed training in July 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-s-newest-astronauts-complete-training |title=NASA's Newest Astronauts Complete Training |date=July 9, 2015 |work=NASA}}</ref>\n\nDuring her time in the astronaut office, Meir has served as the [[Flight controller#Spacecraft communicator (CAPCOM)|capsule communicator]] for various missions. She was the lead capsule communicator for [[Expedition 47]], the [[Bigelow Expandable Activity Module|BEAM]] mission, and a [[H-II Transfer Vehicle|HTV]] (Japanese Space Agency cargo vehicle) mission.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nMeir is a member of the science advisory board of Adventurers and Scientists for Conservation.<ref name=\"Globe and Mail\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/technology/science/extreme-trekkers-citizen-scientists/article2036774/|title=Extreme trekkers, citizen scientists |last=D'Aliesio |first=Renata |date=May 26, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Jessica Meir\u2013first all female spacewalk in history-2019-10-18.jpg|alt=Jessica Meir waving at the camera during her EVA on October 18|thumb|Jessica Meir during her EVA on October 18]]\n\n===Expedition 61/62===\nMeir launched to the [[International Space Station]] on board [[Soyuz MS-15]] on September 25, 2019, as a flight engineer for [[Expedition 61|Expeditions 61]] and [[Expedition 62|62]]. She was scheduled to perform three spacewalks during this mission to help install new [[Lithium-ion battery|lithium-ion batteries]] on the Port-6 truss structure of the ISS, although this schedule was later changed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/category/expedition-60/ |title=Expedition 60 \u2013 Space Station |work=NASA |access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> On October 18, 2019, Meir performed her first spacewalk alongside her colleague [[Christina Koch]], replacing a faulty Battery Charging Discharging Unit. The unit had unexpectedly failed to activate, preventing the station's newly installed lithium-ion batteries from providing additional power.<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-to-televise-first-all-female-spacewalk-host-media-teleconference |title=NASA to Televise First All-Female Spacewalk, Host Media Teleconference |date=October 18, 2019 |work=NASA |url-status=live |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The three other scheduled spacewalks scheduled to install the new batteries had to be postponed in order to perform this spacewalk.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite press release |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/in-space-news-conference-to-review-first-all-woman-spacewalk |title=In-Space News Conference to Review First All-Woman Spacewalk |date=October 19, 2019 |work=NASA |url-status=live |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe spacewalk lasted for seven hours and 17 minutes, and was the first all-female spacewalk in history. During the spacewalk US president [[Donald Trump]] called and spoke to the astronauts in recognition of the historical significance of this event.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iji5hTQ3CUo|title=NASA Astronauts Spacewalk Outside the International Space Station on Oct. 18 |date=October 18, 2019 |work= NASA |via=YouTube |url-status=live |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nu.nl/buitenland/6004873/voor-het-eerst-maakt-vrouwelijk-duo-ruimtewandeling-bij-iss.html |title=Voor het eerst maakt vrouwelijk duo ruimtewandeling bij ISS |language=Dutch |newspaper=[[NU.nl]] |date=October 18, 2019 |trans-title=For the first time a female duo is taking a space walk at ISS}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/10/18/nasa-tv-is-live-now-broadcasting-first-all-woman-spacewalk/ |title=NASA TV is Live Now Broadcasting First All-Woman Spacewalk |last=Garcia |first=Mark |date=October 18, 2019 |website=NASA Blogs |access-date=October 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/stationreport/2019/10/18/iss-daily-summary-report-10182019/ |title=ISS Daily Summary Report \u2013 10/18/2019 |last=Keeter |first=Bill |date=October 18, 2019 |website=NASA |url-status=live |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nMeir returned to Earth on April 17, 2020.<ref name=\"nasa20190417\">{{cite press release |title=NASA Announces First Flight, Record-Setting Mission |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-announces-first-flight-record-setting-mission |work=NASA |date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Although she is American, due to also holding Swedish citizenship by virtue of her mother's country of birth, she is technically the first Swedish female citizenship-holder in space and the second Swedish citizenship-holder in space overall after ESA astronaut [[Christer Fuglesang]]. She speaks Swedish and spent several months in a Swedish university.<ref>{{cite news |last1=N\u00e4slund |first1=Anne-Sofie |title=Jessica blir f\u00f6rsta svenska kvinnan i rymden: \"Trodde det var k\u00f6rt\" |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/qs/jessica-40-blir-forsta-svenska-kvinnan-i-rymden-jag-trodde-det-var-kort/ |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |newspaper=[[Expressen]] |date=May 11, 2018|trans-title=Jessica becomes the first Swedish woman in space: \"Thought it was over\"}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMeir played [[flute]], [[piccolo]], and [[saxophone]] as a youth, and enjoys reading classical literature. She spent a semester studying at [[Stockholm University]] in [[Sweden]] during her undergraduate years.<ref name=\"NASA Quest Bio\"/> She speaks [[Swedish language|Swedish]] and [[Russian language|Russian]] (required for astronaut training).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://astronauts.nasa.gov/content/broch00.htm|title=Astronaut Selection|website=NASA|access-date=October 18, 2019|date=January 4, 2016}}</ref> Meir enjoys recreational cycling, hiking, running, skiing, soccer and scuba diving, and holds a private pilot's license.<ref name=nasabio />\n\n== Awards  ==\nMeir has received numerous awards including:<ref name=nasabio>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/jessica-u-meir/biography|title=Jessica U. Meir (PH.D.) NASA Astronaut|last=Whiting|first=Melanie|date=September 25, 2019|access-date=October 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* Philanthropic Educational Organization (PEO) Scholar Award (2008);\n* Achievement Rewards for College Scientists (ARCS) Fellowship (2006); \n* Lockheed Martin Space Operations (LMSO) Special Recognition Award (2002); \n* NASA JSC Space and Life Sciences Directorate Special Professional Achievement Award (2002); \n* Lockheed Martin Technology Services \"Lightning Award\" (2002).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote|Jessica Meir}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/meir-ju.pdf NASA biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190323110600/http://www.zoology.ubc.ca/person/meir Postdoctoral research]\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013_meir.html Astronaut candidate bio]\n* [http://penguinranch.blogspot.com/ Penguin Ranch blog]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VPUetsnURVk Youtube: Meir in Antarctica]\n* [http://science360.gov/obj/video/6e368bab-5612-4fc3-9a1c-a55b80bcab42 Video of Meir with bar-headed geese]\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/discoveries/disc_summ.jsp?cntn_id=118659 National Science Foundation (NSF) Discoveries - Into Thin Air]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111016003625/http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html Meet Jessica Meir, NASA Quest]\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/NEEMO/history.html NEEMO History, NASA]\n* [http://earthguide.ucsd.edu/elephantseals/ Elephant Seals - Earthguide]\n* [http://www.livescience.com/14091-modern-mother-goose-attempts-unravel-flight-bar-headed-goose.html Modern \"Mother Goose\" Attempts to Unravel the Flight of the Bar-Headed Goose, LiveScience]\n* [http://www.brownalumnimagazine.com/articles/2016-11-08/gravitational-pull Gravitational Pull, Brown Alumni Magazine Nov/Dec 2016]\n\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 21}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meir, Jessica Ulrika}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American aviators]]\n[[Category:American explorers]]\n[[Category:American marine biologists]]\n[[Category:American people of Israeli descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Iraqi-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:Mizrahi Jews]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American underwater divers]]\n[[Category:Aquanauts]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Antarctica]]\n[[Category:Female explorers]]\n[[Category:Harvard Medical School faculty]]\n[[Category:International Space University alumni]]\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:People from Caribou, Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Somerville, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Scripps Institution of Oceanography alumni]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Women physiologists]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:Swedish astronauts]]\n[[Category:Jewish astronauts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|astronaut, physiologist}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox astronaut\n| name          = Jessica Meir\n| image         = Jessica Meir official portrait in an EMU.jpg\n| caption       = Jessica Meir in 2019\n\n| type          = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| status        = Active\n| nationality   = American and Swedish dual citizenship\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1977|7|1}}\n| birth_place   = [[Caribou, Maine]], U.S.\n| occupation    = astronaut, [[physiologist]]\n| selection     = [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|2013 NASA Group]]\n| evas          = 3\n| eva_time      = 21h 44m\n| alma_mater    = [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]]<br/>{{nowrap|[[International Space University]]}}<br/>[[Brown University]]\n| space_time    =  204d 15h 19m 00s\n| mission       = [[Soyuz MS-15]] ([[Expedition 61]]/[[Expedition 62|62]])\n| insignia      = [[File:Soyuz-MS-15-Mission-Patch.png|50px]] [[File:ISS Expedition 61 Patch.svg |45px]] [[File:ISS Expedition 62 Patch.png|45px]]\n| module            = \n  {{Infobox scientist | embed=yes\n  | fields            = {{ublist|[[Marine biology]]|[[comparative physiology]]}}\n  | workplaces        = {{ublist|[[Harvard Medical School]]|[[NASA]]}}\n  | thesis_title      = Blood oxygen transport and depletion: The key of consummate divers\n  | thesis_url        = https://search.proquest.com/docview/304852089\n  | thesis_year       = 2009\n  | doctoral_advisor  = Paul Ponganis\n  | academic_advisors = Bill Milsom (post doc)\n  | doctoral_students = \n  | notable_students  = \n  | known_for         = \n  | influences        = \n  | influenced        = \n  | awards            = \n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Jessica Ulrika Meir''' ([[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]: {{IPAc-en|m|\u026a\u0259r|}}; {{respell|m|eer|}}; born July 1, 1977) is a [[NASA]] astronaut, marine biologist, and  physiologist. She was previously Assistant Professor of Anesthesia at [[Harvard Medical School]], [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], [[Boston]], following [[postdoctoral research]] in [[comparative physiology]] at the [[University of British Columbia]].<ref name=\"Abstract\">{{cite journal |title=Point: Counterpoint \"High Altitude is / is not for the Birds!\" |last1=Scott |first1=Graham R. |last2=Meir |first2=Jessica Ulrika |last3=Hawkes |first3=Lucy A. |last4=Frappell |first4=Peter B. |last5=Milsom |first5=William K. |last6=Llanos |first6=Anibal J. |last7=Ebensperger |first7=German |last8=Herrera |first8=Emilio A. |last9=Reyes |first9=Roberto Victor |last10=Moraga |first10=Fernando A. |last11=Parer |first11=Julian T. |last12=Giussani |first12=Dino A. |date=July 1, 2011 |publisher=[[American Physiological Society]] |doi=10.1152/japplphysiol.00821.2011 |pmid=21737822 |journal=[[Journal of Applied Physiology]] |volume=111 |issue=5 |pages=1514\u20131515}}</ref><ref name=\"Astronaut\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013astroclass.html |title=2013 Astronaut Class |url-status=live |last1=Roberts |first1=Jason |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=June 19, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621011402/http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013astroclass.html |archivedate=June 21, 2013}}</ref> She has studied the diving physiology and behavior of [[emperor penguin]]s in [[Antarctica]],<ref name=\"Science Daily\">{{cite news |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/05/110512083139.htm |title=Penguins continue diving long after muscles run out of oxygen |date=May 12, 2011 |last=Knight |first=Kathryn |work=[[Science Daily]] |accessdate=November 17, 2011}}</ref> and the physiology of [[Bar-headed goose|bar-headed geese]], which are able to migrate over the [[Himalayas]].<ref name=\"ISNS\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usnews.com/science/articles/2011/04/15/skys-no-limit-in-high-flying-goose-chase |title=Sky's No Limit in High-Flying Goose Chase |last=Arnold |first=Carrie |date=April 15, 2011 |magazine=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref> In September 2002, Meir served as an [[aquanaut]] on the [[NEEMO|NASA Extreme Environment Mission Operations]] 4 ([[NEEMO#NEEMO 4: September 23\u201327, 2002|NEEMO 4]]) crew.<ref name=\"four\">{{cite web |url=http://lsda.jsc.nasa.gov/scripts/mission/miss.cfm?mis_index=213 |title=Life Sciences Data Archive: Experiment |access-date=November 16, 2011 |website=NASA |date=April 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322172426/http://lsda.jsc.nasa.gov/scripts/mission/miss.cfm?mis_index=213 |archive-date=March 22, 2012|df=}}</ref> In 2013 she was selected by NASA to [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|Astronaut Group 21]]. Meir launched on September 25, 2019, to the [[International Space Station|ISS]] onboard [[Soyuz MS-15]], where she served as a flight Engineer during [[Expedition 61]] and [[Expedition 62|62]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Astronaut from Maine prepares for takeoff |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2019/09/08/maine-astronaut-jessica-meir-prepares-for-her-launch/ |newspaper=[[Portland Press Herald]] |accessdate=September 24, 2019 |last1=Graham |first1=Gillian |date=September 8, 2019}}</ref> On October 18, 2019, Meir and [[Christina Koch]] were the first women to participate in an all-female [[spacewalk]]. The Soyuz capsule carrying Jessica Meir and fellow astronauts Andrew Morgan and Oleg Skripochka touched down on Friday April 17, 2020 near the town of Dzhezkazgan, Kazakhstan, at 11.16am local time.<ref>{{cite news |title=ASTRONAUTS RETURN TO EARTH AFTER WATCHING CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK FROM INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/nasa-landing-astronauts-launch-space-international-station-a9470281.html}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nJessica Meir was born in [[Caribou, Maine|Caribou]], [[Maine]], to a [[Swedes|Swedish]] mother who was a nurse and an Israeli father of [[History of the Jews in Iraq|Iraqi-Jewish]] descent, who worked as a physician. Her mother is from [[V\u00e4ster\u00e5s]], Sweden; her father was born in [[Iraq]] and moved to [[Israel]] as a child. He later moved to [[Sweden]] where he met Meir's mother who grew up in a Christian family. The couple moved to Maine, US where Meir was born.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.jpost.com/Israeli-women/Swedish-Israeli-NASA-astronaut-Jessica-Meir-gets-ready-for-space-589217 |title=Swedish-Israeli NASA astronaut Jessica Meir gets ready for space |last=Dolsten |first=Josefin |date=May 9, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url-status=live |access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlthough her mother did not convert, Meir grew up attending synagogue in [[Presque Isle, Maine]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She was inspired to venture into space after watching the [[Space Shuttle]] missions on television. Meir knew no one who worked for NASA or for the space program. She attributes her abiding dream of personally participating in space exploration to the love of nature she learned from her mother, and from her father's predilection for wandering and adventure. \"And it might have had something to do with the fact that the stars shone so brightly in rural Maine\", Meir added.<ref name=\"TimesofIsrael\">{{cite news |first=Renee |last=Ghert-Zand |date=June 1, 2018 |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/no-risk-no-reward-says-fearless-jewish-astronaut-jessica-meir/ |title=No Risk, No Reward Says Fearless Jewish Astronaut Jessica Meir |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 13, Meir attended a youth space camp at [[Purdue University]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2019/04/17/news/aroostook/astronaut-from-aroostook-county-will-soon-go-on-her-1st-spaceflight/ |title=Astronaut from Aroostook County will soon go on her 1st spaceflight |newspaper=[[Bangor Daily News]] |access-date=May 9, 2019 |last1=Burns |first1=Christopher |date=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html |title=Meet Jessica Meir |website=NASA Quest |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030504145149/http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html |archive-date=May 4, 2003 |access-date=October 20, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"wp-2015apr28\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/kidspost/journey-to-mars-jessica-meir/2015/04/28/29d206a0-b11b-11e4-886b-c22184f27c35_story.html |title=Journey to Mars: Meet NASA astronaut candidate Jessica Meir |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |date=April 28, 2015 |first=Sarah |last=Kaplan}}</ref> During her undergraduate biology studies at [[Brown University]], she also spent a semester in a study abroad program in Stockholm and ran a student experiment on a NASA [[reduced gravity aircraft]] \"vomit comet\" in her senior year.<ref name=\"TimesofIsrael\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Meir graduated from Brown in 1999 with a Bachelor of Arts Degree in Biology, with Honors, magna cum laude.<ref name=\"thesis\" /> In 2000, Meir graduated with a Master of Space Studies from the [[International Space University]] in [[Strasbourg, France]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.isunet.edu/news/success-stories/jessica-meir-mss00/226 |title=Three I's of ISU Influential to 2013 NASA Astronaut Candidate Jessica Meir |work=[[International Space University]] |year=2013 |access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref> \n\n===Comparative physiology research===\nMeir earned a Ph.D. in [[marine biology]] in 2009 from the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] for research on the [[diving physiology]] of [[emperor penguin]]s and [[northern elephant seal]]s.<ref name=\"thesis\">{{cite thesis |last=Meir |first=Jessica Ulrika |date=2009 |title=Blood oxygen transport and depletion: The key of consummate divers |degree=Ph.D. |isbn=978-1-109-31853-1 |institution=[[University of California, San Diego]] |oclc=449187875 |id={{ProQuest|304852089}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=What triggers the aerobic dive limit? Patterns of muscle oxygen depletion during dives of emperor penguins |journal=[[The Journal of Experimental Biology]] |date=June 1, 2011 |volume=214 |issue=11 |pages=1802\u20131812 |doi=10.1242/jeb.052233 |url=http://jeb.biologists.org/content/214/11/1802.abstract |pmid=21562166 |pmc=3092726 |last1=Williams |first1=CL |last2=Meir |first2=JU |last3=Ponganis |first3=PJ}}</ref><ref name=\"Students\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/article/secrets-worlds-extreme-divers |title=Secrets of the world's extreme divers |last=Kwok |first=Roberta |date=April 24, 2011 |work=[[Science News for Students]] |accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref>  Meir performed field work at ''Penguin Ranch''  on [[McMurdo Sound]] in [[Antarctica]] to study the diving abilities of the emperor penguin while [[scuba diving]] alongside them under the ice.<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Ponganis |url=https://www.nsf.gov/discoveries/disc_summ.jsp?cntn_id=111170 |title=A Season at the Penguin Ranch in Antarctica|work=[[National Science Foundation]] |date=May 19, 2008 |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Students\"/>  She also studied elephant seals while they were diving in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off [[Northern California]].<ref name=\"Students\"/>\n\nMeir did post-doctoral research at the University of British Columbia, raising [[Bar-headed Goose|bar-headed geese]] so their tolerance of high altitude and low oxygen levels during flight over the [[Himalayas]] could be studied in a controlled environment.<ref name=\"ISNS\"/><ref name=\"Students\"/> For the 2012 academic year she continued her research as an assistant professor of [[anesthesia]] at the Harvard Medical School/Massachusetts General Hospital and then took a leave of absence to enter the astronaut corps.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2013/09/destination-space/ |first1=Alvin |last1=Powell |title=Destination Space |website=[[The Harvard Gazette]] |date=September 6, 2013 |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== NASA career ==\nAfter getting her master's degree, Meir worked from 2000\u20132003 for [[Lockheed Martin]] Space Operations as an experiment support scientist for the Human Research Facility at the [[NASA]] [[Johnson Space Center]] (JSC) in [[Houston, Texas]].<ref name=nasabio /><ref name=\"Antarctica\">{{cite web|url=http://womeninantarctica.com/portraits/jessica.html|title=Jessica Meir, Emperor Penguin Researcher in Antarctica\n|last=Price|first=Mary Lynn|website=Women Working in Antarctica|accessdate=November 19, 2011}}</ref> Meir coordinated and supported human space life science experiments that were performed by [[astronaut]]s on [[Space Shuttle]] and [[International Space Station]] (ISS) missions. These experiments included physiological studies (bone loss, muscle control/atrophy, lung function, etc.) to determine if any bodily processes were altered in the spaceflight environment. Meir guided these experiments through the necessary review cycles, developed procedures that the astronauts would use on-orbit, trained crew members, and provided ground support in the Mission Control Center while the astronauts were performing the experiments on the shuttle or ISS.<ref name=\"NASA Quest Bio\">{{cite web|url=http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html|title=:: NASA Quest > Space :: Meet Jessica Meir|access-date=November 19, 2011|last=Meir|first=Jessica|publisher=[[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030504145149/http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html|archive-date=May 4, 2003|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2002, Meir served as an [[aquanaut]] on the joint NASA-[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]] [[NEEMO#NEEMO 4: September 23\u201327, 2002|NEEMO 4]] expedition (NASA Extreme Environment Mission Operations), an exploration research mission held in [[Aquarius (laboratory)|Aquarius]], an [[Underwater habitat|undersea research laboratory]] four miles off shore from [[Key Largo]]. Meir and her crewmates spent five days [[saturation diving]] from the Aquarius habitat as a [[Human analog missions|space analogue]] for working and training under extreme environmental conditions. The mission was delayed due to [[Hurricane Isadore]], forcing National Undersea Research Center managers to shorten it to an underwater duration of five days. Then, three days into their underwater mission, the crew members were told that [[Hurricane Lili|Tropical Storm Lili]] was headed in their direction and to prepare for an early departure from Aquarius. Fortunately, Lili degenerated to the point where it was no longer a threat, so the crew was able to remain the full five days.<ref name=\"four\"/><ref name=\"history\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/NEEMO/history.html|title=NEEMO History|accessdate=November 16, 2011|work=NASA|date=March 21, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061008171834/http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/NEEMO/history.html|archivedate=October 8, 2006}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of NEEMO 4, Meir was leaning toward pursuing a [[PhD]] in a field related to [[evolutionary biology]] and/or life in [[extreme environment]]s ([[astrobiology]]). She was also fascinated by [[marine biology]] (which suited the [[NEEMO]] mission well), and hoped to coordinate a specific topic of study to combine these main interests.<ref name=\"NASA Quest Bio\"/> She received her PhD in marine biology from [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]], studying diving physiology, in 2009.<ref name=\"nasabio\" />\n\nIn 2009, Meir was a semi-finalist for selection to [[NASA Astronaut Group 20]].<ref name=\"Spacefacts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/candidates/nasa20/english/meir_jessica.htm |title=Biographies of Astronaut and Cosmonaut Candidates: Jessica Meir |date=March 27, 2010 |work=Spacefacts |access-date=November 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227090109/http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/candidates/nasa20/english/meir_jessica.htm |archive-date=February 27, 2014 |first1=Joachim Wilhelm Josef |last1=Becker |first2=Heinz Hermann |last2=Janssen}}</ref> For the next selection group in June 2013, Meir was chosen as one of eight astronaut candidates for training in [[NASA Astronaut Group 21]].<ref name=\"Astronaut\"/> She completed training in July 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-s-newest-astronauts-complete-training |title=NASA's Newest Astronauts Complete Training |date=July 9, 2015 |work=NASA}}</ref>\n\nDuring her time in the astronaut office, Meir has served as the [[Flight controller#Spacecraft communicator (CAPCOM)|capsule communicator]] for various missions. She was the lead capsule communicator for [[Expedition 47]], the [[Bigelow Expandable Activity Module|BEAM]] mission, and a [[H-II Transfer Vehicle|HTV]] (Japanese Space Agency cargo vehicle) mission.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nMeir is a member of the science advisory board of Adventurers and Scientists for Conservation.<ref name=\"Globe and Mail\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/technology/science/extreme-trekkers-citizen-scientists/article2036774/|title=Extreme trekkers, citizen scientists |last=D'Aliesio |first=Renata |date=May 26, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Jessica Meir\u2013first all female spacewalk in history-2019-10-18.jpg|alt=Jessica Meir waving at the camera during her EVA on October 18|thumb|Jessica Meir during her EVA on October 18]]\n\n===Expedition 61/62===\nMeir launched to the [[International Space Station]] on board [[Soyuz MS-15]] on September 25, 2019, as a flight engineer for [[Expedition 61|Expeditions 61]] and [[Expedition 62|62]]. She was scheduled to perform three spacewalks during this mission to help install new [[Lithium-ion battery|lithium-ion batteries]] on the Port-6 truss structure of the ISS, although this schedule was later changed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/category/expedition-60/ |title=Expedition 60 \u2013 Space Station |work=NASA |access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> On October 18, 2019, Meir performed her first spacewalk alongside her colleague [[Christina Koch]], replacing a faulty Battery Charging Discharging Unit. The unit had unexpectedly failed to activate, preventing the station's newly installed lithium-ion batteries from providing additional power.<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-to-televise-first-all-female-spacewalk-host-media-teleconference |title=NASA to Televise First All-Female Spacewalk, Host Media Teleconference |date=October 18, 2019 |work=NASA |url-status=live |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>The three other scheduled spacewalks scheduled to install the new batteries had to be postponed in order to perform this spacewalk.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite press release |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/in-space-news-conference-to-review-first-all-woman-spacewalk |title=In-Space News Conference to Review First All-Woman Spacewalk |date=October 19, 2019 |work=NASA |url-status=live |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe spacewalk lasted for seven hours and 17 minutes, and was the first all-female spacewalk in history. During the spacewalk US president [[Donald Trump]] called and spoke to the astronauts in recognition of the historical significance of this event.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iji5hTQ3CUo|title=NASA Astronauts Spacewalk Outside the International Space Station on Oct. 18 |date=October 18, 2019 |work= NASA |via=YouTube |url-status=live |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nu.nl/buitenland/6004873/voor-het-eerst-maakt-vrouwelijk-duo-ruimtewandeling-bij-iss.html |title=Voor het eerst maakt vrouwelijk duo ruimtewandeling bij ISS |language=Dutch |newspaper=[[NU.nl]] |date=October 18, 2019 |trans-title=For the first time a female duo is taking a space walk at ISS}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/10/18/nasa-tv-is-live-now-broadcasting-first-all-woman-spacewalk/ |title=NASA TV is Live Now Broadcasting First All-Woman Spacewalk |last=Garcia |first=Mark |date=October 18, 2019 |website=NASA Blogs |access-date=October 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/stationreport/2019/10/18/iss-daily-summary-report-10182019/ |title=ISS Daily Summary Report \u2013 10/18/2019 |last=Keeter |first=Bill |date=October 18, 2019 |website=NASA |url-status=live |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nMeir returned to Earth on April 17, 2020.<ref name=\"nasa20190417\">{{cite press release |title=NASA Announces First Flight, Record-Setting Mission |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-announces-first-flight-record-setting-mission |work=NASA |date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Although she is American, due to also holding Swedish citizenship by virtue of her mother's country of birth, she is technically the first Swedish female citizenship-holder in space and the second Swedish citizenship-holder in space overall after ESA astronaut [[Christer Fuglesang]]. She speaks Swedish and spent several months in a Swedish university.<ref>{{cite news |last1=N\u00e4slund |first1=Anne-Sofie |title=Jessica blir f\u00f6rsta svenska kvinnan i rymden: \"Trodde det var k\u00f6rt\" |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/qs/jessica-40-blir-forsta-svenska-kvinnan-i-rymden-jag-trodde-det-var-kort/ |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |newspaper=[[Expressen]] |date=May 11, 2018|trans-title=Jessica becomes the first Swedish woman in space: \"Thought it was over\"}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMeir played [[flute]], [[piccolo]], and [[saxophone]] as a youth, and enjoys reading classical literature. She spent a semester studying at [[Stockholm University]] in [[Sweden]] during her undergraduate years.<ref name=\"NASA Quest Bio\"/> She speaks [[Swedish language|Swedish]] and [[Russian language|Russian]] (required for astronaut training).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://astronauts.nasa.gov/content/broch00.htm|title=Astronaut Selection|website=NASA|access-date=October 18, 2019|date=January 4, 2016}}</ref> Meir enjoys recreational cycling, hiking, running, skiing, soccer and scuba diving, and holds a private pilot's license.<ref name=nasabio />\n\n== Awards  ==\nMeir has received numerous awards including:<ref name=nasabio>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/jessica-u-meir/biography|title=Jessica U. Meir (PH.D.) NASA Astronaut|last=Whiting|first=Melanie|date=September 25, 2019|access-date=October 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* Philanthropic Educational Organization (PEO) Scholar Award (2008);\n* Achievement Rewards for College Scientists (ARCS) Fellowship (2006); \n* Lockheed Martin Space Operations (LMSO) Special Recognition Award (2002); \n* NASA JSC Space and Life Sciences Directorate Special Professional Achievement Award (2002); \n* Lockheed Martin Technology Services \"Lightning Award\" (2002).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote|Jessica Meir}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/meir-ju.pdf NASA biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190323110600/http://www.zoology.ubc.ca/person/meir Postdoctoral research]\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013_meir.html Astronaut candidate bio]\n* [http://penguinranch.blogspot.com/ Penguin Ranch blog]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VPUetsnURVk Youtube: Meir in Antarctica]\n* [http://science360.gov/obj/video/6e368bab-5612-4fc3-9a1c-a55b80bcab42 Video of Meir with bar-headed geese]\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/discoveries/disc_summ.jsp?cntn_id=118659 National Science Foundation (NSF) Discoveries - Into Thin Air]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111016003625/http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/people/bios/space/meir.html Meet Jessica Meir, NASA Quest]\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/NEEMO/history.html NEEMO History, NASA]\n* [http://earthguide.ucsd.edu/elephantseals/ Elephant Seals - Earthguide]\n* [http://www.livescience.com/14091-modern-mother-goose-attempts-unravel-flight-bar-headed-goose.html Modern \"Mother Goose\" Attempts to Unravel the Flight of the Bar-Headed Goose, LiveScience]\n* 