{"title_page": "1970 British Annapurna South Face expedition", "text_new": "{{short description|First ascent of Himalayan mountain face using rock climbing techniques}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Annapurna Base Camp Range 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Annapurna South Face from Base Camp (2013)]]\nThe '''1970 British Annapurna South Face expedition''' was a Himalayan climb that was the first to take a deliberately difficult route up the face of an [[Eight-thousander|8,000-metre mountain]]. On 27 May 1970 [[Don Whillans]] and [[Dougal Haston]] reached the summit of [[Annapurna I]] which at {{convert|26545|ft}} is the highest peak in the [[Annapurna Massif]] in [[Nepal]]. [[Chris Bonington]] led the expedition which approached up a glacier from the [[Annapurna Sanctuary]] and then used rock climbing techniques to put [[fixed rope]]s up the steep South Face. Although the plan had been to use supplementary oxygen, in the event it was not possible to carry any cylinders high enough for the lead climbers to use on their summit bid.\n\nLow down on the mountain, on 30 May as the expedition was about to leave, [[Ian Clough]] was killed by a falling [[serac]]. Several members of the expedition rose to fame in Britain, and as a whole the expedition received international recognition in mountaineering circles on account of its innovative and extremely difficult nature.\n\n== Background ==\n=== Annapurna ===\n{{see also|Mount Everest reconnaissance from Nepal}}\nThe [[Annapurna Massif|Annapurna massif]] is in the [[Eastern Himalaya]]a region of Nepal where for over one hundred years the ruling [[Rana dynasty]]  had not allowed explorers or mountaineers to enter the country.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=238\u2013241}}{{sfnp|Ward|Clark|1992}} In 1950 Nepal at last gave permission for the [[1950 French Annapurna expedition]], to attempt [[Dhaulagiri]] or [[Annapurna I Main|Annapurna I]], the two highest peaks in the Annapurna region. The expedition, led by [[Maurice Herzog]], mounted a successful summit attempt via the North Face. For most Himalayan mountains the easiest route to the summit is along a ridge route but for Annapurna the North Face is not too steep (though it is very exposed to avalanches) and the route subsequently turned out to be the easiest.{{sfnp|Herzog|1954|pp=48,54,57,102\u2013103}}{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=242\u2013253,387}} Although it was the first climbed of the eight-thousanders, Annapurna is not often climbed and there is a high death rate among those attempting it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adam |first1=Voiland |title=The Eight-Thousanders |url=https://www.earthobservatory.nasa.gov/features/8000MeterPeaks |website=www.earthobservatory.nasa.gov |publisher=NASA |date=16 December 2013 |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503184334/https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/Features/8000MeterPeaks/ |archive-date=3 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Start of rock climbing in Himalaya ===\nAfter years of stagnation between the wars, British rock climbing underwent a renaissance, particularly with working-class climbing clubs starting up in the north of England and Scotland. The [[Rock and Ice Club]] in [[Manchester]], the Creagh Dhu Mountaineering Club in [[Glasgow]] and several university climbing clubs were amongst those that engendered a highly competitive climbing environment. At [[Clogwyn Du'r Arddu]] in Wales numerous routes of a very high standard were achieved using strictly [[free climbing]] techniques. [[Hamish MacInnes]] and [[Dougal Haston]], although not members, climbed with Creagh Dhu and MacInnes had mentored [[Chris Bonington]]'s youthful climbing as early as 1953.{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|pp=189\u2013260}}\n\nIn 1960, Bonington, as a member of a joint British\u2013Indian\u2013Nepalese army team led by [[J. O. M. Roberts|Jimmy Roberts]], reached the summit of the {{convert|26039|ft|adj=on}} [[Annapurna II]], {{convert|20|mi}} east of the range's main summit, Annapurna I. The route did not involve rock climbing.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=347,387}}\n\n[[Mount Everest]] was ascended in 1963 by an American team along [[Timeline of Mount Everest expeditions#1963|a deliberately difficult route along its West Ridge]].{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|p=387}}  Two years later, when planning with the American [[John Harlin]] for Harlin's ''direttissima'' attempt on the [[Eigerwand|North Face of the Eiger]], Harlin introduced Bonington to the American [[Big wall climbing|big wall]] technique of directly ascending a [[fixed rope]] using [[Jumar]]s.{{sfnp|Harlin|2008|pp=109\u2013111}} Harlin fell to his death and Haston's success on the route were reported on by Bonington and [[Mick Burke (mountaineer)|Mick Burke]] who were on the North Face as climbing journalist and cameraman.{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|p=246}} The publicity led to the televising of a climb of the [[Old Man of Hoy]] in Scotland, this time featuring Bonington and Haston.{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|p=231}} From this start, commercial sponsorship became a possibility for rock climbing and more elaborate and ambitious expeditions could be planned. With all fourteen [[Eight-thousander|8000-metre peaks]] climbed by 1964, Himalayan expeditions using rock climbing routes became an opportunity Bonington wanted to seize.{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|pp=189\u2013260}}\n\nEncouraged by Roberts, Bonington conceived of the idea of climbing [[Annapurna]] by its South Face which he realised was going to require not just rock climbing but also [[Expedition style|siege climbing tactics]] because the ascent would take many weeks. No one had tried rock climbing at high altitude before. The face itself was almost twice as high as the {{convert|6000|ft}} [[Eigerwand]] and even above the rock band there was another {{convert|3000|ft}} to the summit.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971b|p=18\u201333}}{{sfnp|Bonington|2017|p=155}}{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|pp=189\u2013260}}  The topography near the summit could be assessed from photographs Bonington had taken on the Annapurna II expedition of ten years earlier.{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=411}}\n\n===Planning===\n{{external media|topic=Clip from TV programme|Annapurna|title=Annapurna South Face|headerimage=|caption=\n|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uQE_65nk_p4 Annapurna: The Hardest Way Up]{{sfnp|Edwards|1971}}}}\nWith financial support for the expedition from the [[Mount Everest Foundation]], Bonington assembled a team from amongst his friends: [[Nick Estcourt]], [[Martin Boysen]], [[Ian Clough]], Mike Thompson, Burke and Haston. Advised to include an American to boost sales of the book he was planning, Bonington appointed [[Tom Frost]] who had considerable [[big wall]] experience in [[Yosemite]] as well as \u2013 secretly at the time \u2013 [[Nanda Devi]] on a [[Nanda Devi#CIA mission|CIA mission]] to install a nuclear-powered listening device for monitoring [[China and weapons of mass destruction|Chinese missiles]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=2\u201313,238\u2013239}} Frost was known to and respected by Haston and [[Don Whillans]]. Whillans was to be deputy leader for, although by then he was an overweight heavy drinker and smoker who disliked Bonington, he had more Himalayan experience than any other British mountaineer still active.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=389\u2013390}} Indeed, only he, Bonington and Clough had been to Himalaya at all.{{sfnp|Bonington|1986|p=16}} Also included as climbers were [[Kelvin Kent (mountaineer)|Kelvin Kent]], base camp manager, and David Lambert, the doctor. A four-man television team from [[ITN]] and [[Thames Television]] was to be accompanying them.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=2\u201313,238\u2013239}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=414}}\n\n===Departure===\nThey took {{convert|18000|ft}} of rope for fixing (they did not use their climbing rope), 40 cylinders of Oxygen and six breathing sets.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=246,257}} The baggage was sent from London by sea with Whillans and Lambert flying to [[Bombay]]{{refn|group=note|[[Mumbai]] is the present name.}} to see to its unloading and transport to [[Pokhara]] by lorry. However, the ship was then delayed by about three weeks so Bonington arranged for Whillans and Lambert to travel to [[Kathmandu]] to reconnoitre the approach route instead of waiting at Bombay, and Clough would go to Bombay to deal with the baggage.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=29\u201331,39}} They took oxygen cylinders intending to use supplementary oxygen above about {{convert|22500|ft}} but it was very little used for climbing and not at all above Camp VI. It was used, however, for people who had become ill.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=257\u2013259}}\n\n==Expedition==\n===March-in and Base Camp===\n[[File:1970 Annapurna south face expedition approach route.svg|thumb|Approach route from [[Pokhara]] to Annapurna Base Camp]]\nIn March 1970 the expedition flew to Kathmandu and then on to [[Pokhara]] from where the trek to the southern vicinity of Annapurna was along an easy route. Unlike twenty years earlier when [[Maurice Herzog|Herzog]] had no satisfactory map and had to pioneer a route, by 1970 the track was well known even to [[hippie]] wanderers.{{refn|group=note|The eight-day trek route from Pokhara went up beside the [[Seti Gandaki River|Seti Khola]] river and then the Modi Khola (a tributary of the [[Gandaki river]]). Bonington notes passing through [[Naudanda]], [[Lumle]], Chondracot (now Chandrakot), Ghandrung (now [[Ghandruk]]), Chomro (now Chhomrong), Thomo and Hinko Cave.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=47\u201350,54,79}}}} Another change was that the Sherpas were no longer unsophisticated peasants \u2013 they were smart in appearance, spoke good English and had a Western attitude. [[Pasang Kami]], the sirdar, treated the sahibs as equals and this was reciprocated. The other Sherpas were Pemba Tharkay, Ang Pema, Mingma Tsering, Nima Tsering and Kancha. As it turned out, a group from the British Army Mountaineering Association, led by [[Henry Day (colonel)|Henry Day]], was setting off at the same time for an ascent on Herzog's north face route and they had greatly helped Bonington by flying out {{convert|1500|lb}} of baggage to supply him until his main baggage arrived.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=390\u2013391}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=29,39,43,238}}{{sfnp|Day|1971|p=89}}\n\nOn 16 March Whillans, Thompson and two Sherpas went ahead of the main parties to reconnoitre the route and to find a suitable place for the base camp.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=38\u201339}} A temporary location was found to be at the entrance to the [[Annapurna Sanctuary]] at the location of a previous base camp: that of the 1957 expedition to [[Machapuchare]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=18,51}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=416}}\nThe slower-moving baggage train of 140 porters set off from Pokhara on 22 March and Clough with his 240 porters was able to leave Bombay with the delayed baggage on 24 March.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=42,53,81}}\n\nBonington and Whillans met up on 27 March and Whillans said he thought he and his Sherpas had seen a [[yeti]] and had photographed the footprints. More significantly, he had been able to identify a climbing route up the mountain's south face.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=56\u201362,68, ill 10}} After the whole party has gathered at the temporary base camp on 29 March an advance party including Whillans, Haston and Burke established a final base camp at {{convert|14000|ft}} three miles from the foot of the face.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|p=391}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=42}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=417}} Estcourt used a theodolite to make accurate altitude measurements of various points on the face because foreshortening makes estimation inaccurate. The porters returned to Pokhara from where many of them would help move up to Base Camp the main baggage being carried from Bombay by the party led by Clough, Thompson and Kent. Meanwhile, the lead climbers and Sherpas were left to ferry the advance baggage up to the final Base Camp.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=62\u201366}} The monsoon was due at bbout the end of May.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=166,195}}\n\n===Climbing route===\n[[File:1970 Annapurna south face expedition climbing route.png|thumb|Climbing route up South Face]]\nBetween Camp III at {{convert|20100|ft}} and the top of the Rock Band at {{convert|24750|ft}} the average slope is 55\u00b0.{{refn|group=note|Bonington compares this with 44\u00b0 on the [[Aiguille de la Brenva|Brenva face]] of [[Mont Blanc]] and 61\u00b0 on the Walker Spur of the [[Grandes Jorasses]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=237}}}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=236\u2013237}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | Locations of camps on mountain\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Camp\n! colspan=\"2\" | Altitude\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Occupied{{refn|group=note|Dates of occupation{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=233}} unless noted otherwise.}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Description\n|-\n!  feet{{refn|group=note|Altitudes{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=237}} unless noted otherwise.}} !! metres{{refn|group=note|Altitudes in metres calculated from referenced figures in feet.}}\n|-\n| Temporary Base || 12,000{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|loc=plate 12}} || {{convert|12000|ft|disp=number}} || 28&nbsp;March<br />{{refn|group=note|Date of occupation by main party;  for advance party \u2013 21 March.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=51}}}} || sited at Base Camp of 1957 Machapuchare expedition{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=18,60}}\n|-\n| Base || 14,000 || {{convert|14000|ft|disp=number}} || 31 March{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=66}} || side of Annapurna glacier{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=60}}\n|-\n| Camp I || 16,000 || {{convert|16000|ft|disp=number}} || 2 April || on [[Nunatak|\"rognon\"]] (island of rock in glacier){{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=64}}\n|-\n| Camp II || 17,500 || {{convert|17500|ft|disp=number}} || 6 April || under rock overhang{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=76}}\n|-\n| Camp III || 20,100 || {{convert|20100|ft|disp=number}} || 13 April || large, flat area at Col{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=85}}\n|-\n| Camp IV || 21,300 || {{convert|21300|ft|disp=number}} || 23 April || sloping 30\u00b0  on Ice Ridge{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=109,111}}\n|-\n| dump || 21,650{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=154,236}} || {{convert|21650|ft|disp=number}} || 11 May || col at top of Ice Ridge{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=139\u2013140,154,236}}\n|-\n| temporary<br /> Camp&nbsp;V || 22,500<br />{{refn|group=note|8,500 feet above Base Camp at 14,000 feet.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=147,237}}}} || {{convert|22500|ft|disp=number}} || 6 May{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=141}} || foot of Ice Wall, vulnerable to snow sliding from above{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=141}}\n|-\n| Camp V || 22,750 || {{convert|22750|ft|disp=number}} || 9 May || [[bergschrund]] at foot of Rock Band{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=149,152}}\n|-\n| Camp VI || 24,000 || {{convert|24000|ft|disp=number}} || 19 May || tiny platform carved in snow at top of Flat Iron{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=194}}\n|-\n| Summit || 26,545 || {{convert|26545|ft|disp=number}} || 27 May ||\n|}\n\n===To Camp III and abortive start up Ice Ridge===\nWhillans and Haston had found a difficult route across the glacier and up to a [[Nunatak|rognon]] \u2013 an island of rock on a glacier \u2013 where Camp I was planned to be and then reached the flattish top of the rognon where Camp I would be just far enough away from the face \u2013 about a mile away \u2013 to avoid avalanche danger. Bonington and Burke relocated the lower part of the route hoping to make it suitable for porters.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=64\u201372}}\n\nThe ridge they were to use at the start of the climb was straightforwardly approached across the glacier but steep cliff barred the way onto the ridge itself so they skirted these on the right to reach a site for Camp II, lower than hoped for but with nowhere suitable immediately higher. For a short distance the route was seriously threatened by an ice overhang which they called the \"Sword of Damocles\" but they decided to reduce the risk by moving under it as quickly as possible.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=73\u201377}}\n\nWhen he arrived with the main baggage Clough was supposed to stop at Hinko Cave overnight on 7 April but, due to confusing instructions, with his entourage of 240 porters he continued on in a snowstorm to temporary base camp some miles further on. Some porters had refused to go beyond Hinko Cave and the rest, overloaded and without adequate clothes and shoes in the bad weather, variously got into states of anger and collapse. However, now the main gear had arrived, it was possible to sort out shelter under cover for the night and provide medical help when necessary.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=79\u201381}} On this same day Whillans and Haston had reached the Ice Ridge at a col where Camp III was to be established. They had to climb through deep snow in bad weather. In ten days the expedition had got from the Sanctuary to half height on the face, although with the difficult climbing all to be done further ahead. They [[abseil]]ed down to Camp II from where, next day, they started placing fixed ropes towards the col.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=81\u201383}}\n\nOn 11 March Boysen and Estcourt established Camp III on the col, where there were to be two Whillans Box tents at a spacious location, free from risk of avalanches or falling rocks.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=85,98}} The version used on Annapurna, designed by Whillans, was [[cuboid]] in shape, {{convert|6.5|x|4.0|x|4|ft}}, made of socketed aluminium tubes covered in nylon top and bottom and cotton-[[terylene]] at the sides. It was strengthened with nylon webbing straps and at one end was a nylon-zipped entrance. An inner nylon tent was available but not always used. It weighed {{convert|30|lb}}{{refn|group=note|In comparison the nylon tents of a hooped design, Bonington calls them RAFMA tents, weighed only {{convert|10|lb}}.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=251}}}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=66\u201367,249\u2013250}}\n\nOn 12 April, after Bonington had organised the logistics of getting Base Camp fully set up and equipped, he and Frost set from there so that on 14 April they could start to prospect a route up the Ice Ridge above Camp III. After investigating a snow shelf leading to a gully on the west of the ridge, Bonington decided avalanches posed too great a threat so he joined Frost who was ascending along the actual crest of the ridge. However, this turned out to be much more difficult than they had expected with snow too soft and loose for firm [[piton]] placements and there would be a need to set [[fixed rope]]s all the way up the ridge. Also, they had not formed a plan for placing fixed ropes \u2013 should the lead climber fix his rope or should he climb normally leaving the second climber to pay out a rope from his rucksack, fixing it as he climbed? To begin with the latter method seemed more successful but progress was dreadfully slow with Bonington never having previously encountered such appalling snow.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=86\u201391}} Later in the expedition the technique changed and they climbed using their {{convert|9|mm|adj=on}} fixed rope which they then secured with pitons and [[karabiner]]s, not using their {{convert|11|mm|adj=on}} climbing rope at all.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=247}}\n\nThat night at Camp III they discussed their religious beliefs \u2013 Bonington was a sceptic and Frost a [[Morman]]. Bonington wrote to his wife \"He is a convinced and fervent Mormon, never rams it down your throat, yet his faith has given him a code of conduct that puts him way out in front of most of us\". Next day it was straightforward to re-climb their fixed rope but again onward climbing was extremely difficult. On the previous day and this one Whillans and Haston had been ferrying supplies from Camp II up to Camp III and following their second climb they starting exploring the shelf which Bonington had investigated previously beside the ridge. Here they made such good progress that the pair on the ridge needed little persuasion to abandon  entirely their efforts on the lowest part of the ridge.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=91\u201395}}\n\nNext day all four climbers set off along the shelf with Haston breaking trail and never surrendering the lead. The avalanche risk was considerable even though they kept their distance from the ridge and matters got worse as they reached the gully threatened by avalanches from ice cliffs thousands of feet above and by [[Snow cornice|cornices]] on the ridge itself. They decided to avoid the gully by climbing a minor [[ar\u00eate]] which led from the foot of the gully up to a high point on the main ridge but they had to leave a [[deadman anchor]] when deteriorating weather forced them to retreat to camp. Next day Bonington and Frost got within {{convert|50|ft}} of the crest of the Ice Ridge but again bad weather forced a retreat.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=95\u201399}}\n\nBy 18 April only {{convert|1000|ft}} had been gained since the Col had been reached eleven days earlier and from Base Camp and on 19 April Haston again ascended the minor ar\u00eate where the way to the main ridge was blocked by huge cornices but he found he could slip through gaps in the rotten snow between the wall of the ridge and one of the cornices. However, after reaching the crest of main ridge and fixing a rope he was forced back by the weather. At last, two days later, he was able to reach the Ice Ridge and find an ideal place for Camp IV.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=102\u2013109}}\n\nThe expedition was unexpectedly enhanced when four trekkers \u2013 the Sherpas called them the \"London Sherpas\" \u2013 turned up at Base Camp completely unexpectedly.{{refn|group=note|The trekkers had left [[Essex]] in England in 1969 in a [[Land Rover]], planning to climb in the [[Hindu Kush]]. Delayed in Austria they had spent the winter in Afghanistan and then had driven to Kathmandu, flown to Pokhara, trekked over to the foothills of [[Dhaulagiri]] and crossed to Chomro via the Deroli Pass intending to reach the [[Annapurna Sanctuary]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=109}} The Deroli Pass, now more usually referred to as the [[Deurali Pass]], is on the [[Annapurna Circuit]] trail, near [[Ghorepani]] and [[Poon Hill]].}} In return for \"board and lodging\" the two men helped carry loads even as high as Camp IV and the women helped at Base Camp where Bonington thought their presence engendered a more a civilised and relaxed air. Other trekkers also turned up to get a grandstand view of the climb and to help carrying loads.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=109\u2013110}}\n\n===Camp IV to Camp V on the Rock Band===\nBoysen, Estcourt, Haston and Whillans worked together establishing Camp IV but the situation at Camp III became critical after several attempts to supply it from Camp II had failed because of deep snow and avalanches. Eventually an overnight carry was successful and in general it seemed the snow conditions improved the higher one got up the mountain.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=110\u2013114}}\n\nBoysen and Estcourt tackled the upper part of the Ice Ridge above Camp IV which was very narrow with cornices to the left but solid rock on the right. At one point Boysen's progress was blocked except for a {{convert|20|ft|adj=on}} tunnel which he could clamber through, without his rucksack, as if potholing. The tunnel led not further up the ridge but out onto an ice cliff with a {{convert|2000|ft|adj=on}} drop to the glacier. However, he managed to climb onto and up the cliff despite the drag of his climbing rope passing along a highly contorted route behind him. When he reached safety he had let out {{convert|150|ft}} of rope in ascending only {{convert|50|ft}}. It was the most difficult ice climb Boysen had ever done. There was no direct way for Estcourt to ascend to Boysen's stance so he had to repeat the circuitous climb. Boysen's next lead again went on to a traverse, which was later called the \"Terrible Traverse\", which he was not able to complete before descending to Camp IV for the night. They had spent all day climbing {{convert|300|ft}}.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=115\u2013119,125}} Next day it again proved impossible to keep to the crest of the ridge but a descent on the right to solid rock gave access to an ice-covered rock wall leading upwards. This climb had to be without the rope being secured with pitons because the rope would have jammed along its contorted route. They regained the ridge again only some {{convert|50|ft}} higher than they had reached the previous day. The following day they extended their route slightly further. After that they had to go down to recover from exhaustion but the fixed ropes they had left allowed everyone following to take a direct line though one that was neither safe nor easy.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=119\u2013121,125}}\n\nBonington and Clough took over the work of extending the route, reaching Camp IV on 27 April. Sometimes they advanced only {{convert|10|ft}} in an hour.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=123\u2013128}} At Whillans' suggestion, they arranged for Sherpas to carry all the climbers'supplies up to Camp III so that when climbers went down to rest they only needed to go to Camp III rather than Base Camp.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=128}} After a few very difficult days, and without being able to regain the crest of the Ice Ridge at a higher point, Clough went down to be replaced by Haston. On 3 May Whillans, Frost and Burke carried a box tent up to Camp IV while Bonington and Haston with very difficult ice climbing reached a col at {{convert|21650|ft}} where the Ice Ridge terminates to be replaced by a snow slope leading up to the Ice Wall.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=124\u2013141}} Next day they carried a load of ropes to the col and Haston ran out {{convert|500|ft}} of rope towards the Ice Wall. At {{convert|22350|ft}} the slope suddenly changes from 45\u00b0 to vertical and this point was planned to become Camp V{{refn|group=note|The site turned out to be very poor so the camp here was only temporary.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=149}}}} where a {{convert|18|lb|adj=on}} hooped tent was set up, capable of sleeping three. Supplying as high as here was a logistical problem because it took at least five days for anything to arrive from base camp.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=141,251}}\n\nSupported by Frost and Burke, Whillans and Haston established Camp V but that night spindrift  inundated the site and the tent so they decided to find a better camp location. Next day they explored the Ice Wall finding a \"gangway\" leading to the top of the Ice Wall and the foot of the Rock Band. At this point the overhang of the [[bergschrund]], although threatening, provided excellent shelter so they proposed moving Camp V to this point. On 9 May Frost and Burke established the camp at the new, higher location.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=141\u2013153}} The climb from Camp IV to V was very long and difficult so two intermediate dumps{{refn|group=note|The lower of the dumps was at the top of the Ice Ridge and the other was at the original site for Camp V at the bottom of the Ice Wall.}} for supplies were used with carrying being done in shorter sections from above and below.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=149\u2013150,154,178}}\n\n===Above Camp V===\n[[File:Tom Frost - South Face of Annapurna - 1970.jpg|thumb|Photograph by Frost: Boysen descending to Camp IV after carrying supplies up to Camp V.]]\nFrost and Burke started on the Rock Band which sloped at about 50\u00b0{{refn|group=note|Bonington likens this to the Second Ice Field on the [[Nordwand|North face of the Eiger]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=160}}}} Instead of taking the most direct line up a groove leading straight upwards, they cut over to the left aiming for the \"Flat Iron\", named after the similar-looking feature on the Eiger, with Burke doing the lead climbing. The good weather helped with the climbing but because of the thaw they were bombarded  from above by falling rocks. The climbers Further down the mountain were having to rest through illness or exhaustion so shortages of rope, oxygen, tents, food and fuel built up towards Camp V. On 12 May Burke and Frost made more progress but only through taking serious risks with inadequate piton placements but when they turned back for the day a storm hit them and their tent was almost buried. Fortunately by that time fresh supplies had arrived from lower camps.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=154\u2013172}}\n\nBonington's general plan had been to pair off the leading climbers and to share the work of the pairs equitably by having periods of rest, carrying supplies to higher camps and extending the route. The Sherpas were carrying higher up the mountain than expected and other trekkers with climbing experience had turned up by chance and helped out. However at the higher camps things were not going so well and so on 13 May Bonington decided that when Frost and Burke came down to be rested they would be replaced by Whillans and Haston. In fact it was the turn of Estcourt and Boysen to force the route upwards but they had been working hard doing carrying while Whillans and Haston were rested. Over the radio between various camps some of the adversely affected climbers complained but were accepting it after Bonington agreed for Whillans and Haston to do a single carry before rotating into the lead. Whillans then started criticising Burke and Frost for making very slow progress on the Rock Band and so, to curtail the increasing bitterness, the radio call was ended leaving each pair to plan the detail of their newly assigned roles.{{refn|group=note|Bonington did not think Whillans' criticisms were at all fair. Indeed Burke and Frost has worked hard and made good progress.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=182}}}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=173\u2013180}}\n\nOn their last day in the lead Burke and Frost, possibly goaded by the criticism, managed to fix ropes up all the way to the Flat Iron. Burke had been on the face for 28 days, and Frost only slightly less \u2013 Bonington thought Burke's climb had been on the most exacting rock of the entire expedition. When Frost met Bonington down at Camp II he firmly told him he thought the stab in the back of Estcourt and Boysen had wrecked the morale of the expedition \u2013 all the same he maintained his close relationship with Bonington.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=180\u2013184}}\n\nOn 17 May Boysen, Whillans and Haston carried equipment to the top of the Flat Iron to a suitable site for Camp VI but on the way Boysen had to return to camp to recover. Whillans and Haston found a site for Camp VI but that night at Camp V the ridge tent was crushed with an avalanche of snow so Estcourt and Haston went down to the upper dump to collect the one intended for Camp VII and to get more food. Climbing back to Camp VI on 19 May, Haston's rucksack, containing his personal gear and food for Camp VI, fell down the mountain. So, that night, Whillans was alone at Camp VII with no food after the others had descended. Estcourt was alone at Camp V and so Bonington went up there to help him support the lead team. The climb from there to Camp VI was even more tiring and Bonington scarcely managed the {{convert|200|ft|adj=on}} [[jumar]] climb near the top. However, he managed and even took the time on his way down to relocate the dangling rope and place further [[piton]]s on this [[Pitch (ascent/descent)|pitch]] of the climb. As for oxygen, there were only three bottles at Camp V and another three at the upper dump. There was hardly any food or rope at Camp VI.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=154,185\u2013195}}{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=205\u2013209}}\n\nOn 20 May Haston returned to Camp VI where Whillans had been without food for over twenty-four hours. Bonington carried up there more food and a radio but had to dump the rope slightly below the camp. Camp VI was a terrible place \u2013 the tent was too large to fit on the ledge so Whillans and Haston had to sleep lying across the width of the tent. Also, the wind was severe and it was only held by two tent pegs, a rope over the top, and the weight of the climbers.{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=209\u2013209}} The same day Estcourt carried the oxygen bottles up to Camp V from the upper dump and the lead climbers climbed {{convert|400|ft}} up from Camp VI but they were then out of food and rope and had no tent to pitch for Camp VII which they intended to place at the top of the Rock Band. They heard news that the army team on the other side of the mountain had reached the summit using a similar route to that of the [[1950 French Annapurna expedition|French expedition in 1950]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=196\u2013200}}\n\nOn 22 May Bonington and Estcourt headed up with supplies and oxygen cylinders towards Camp VI but Estcourt had to retreat back and Bonington, who was using supplementary oxygen, had to abandon the tent and oxygen ''en route''. Haston and Whillans had reached the top of the \"mini rock band\" at the top of the Rock Band but, with no rope left, they had needed to climb without protection, leaving only about {{convert|1500|ft}} to the summit, they estimated.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=200\u2013202}} They had reached the {{convert|25000|ft|adj=on}} snowfield above the Rock Band but without a tent or food. Next day Bonington carried tent, cin\u00e9 camera and food up from V to VI but he had needed to abandon his personal gear so he had to turn down an offer to join then on a summit attempt, Bonington and so had to go down again but the tent could be carried up next day to be left on the snow field above Camp VI. On 23 May with insufficient rope and no tent for Camp VII, the lead climbers took a rest day.{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=212\u2013216,224}}\n\nIn terrible conditions on 24 May Bonington and Clough managed a carry to Camp VI but found Haston and Whillans had been forced back there so all four climbers had to spend the night together in the two-man tent. Bonington and Clough got back to Camp IV but once there the weather became impossible.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=202\u2013204}}\n\n===Summit===\nFor the next two days the entire mountain was snowbound and it seemed the monsoon had arrived but on 27 May 1970 at Camp VI there was an improvement in the weather. Leaving Camp VI about 07:00, without supplementary oxygen because they had none, Whillans and Haston reached the snow field at 11:00 from where they could see the summit through breaks in the cloud. They agreed to move the tent up to establish a camp at a higher location but they really had a more ambitious goal for the day. Indeed, any camp would be entirely lacking food or sleeping bags. They were faced with an ice plateau leading to a snow ridge and then an {{convert|800|ft|adj=on}} cliff of mixed ice and rock rising up to the top of the mountain. They abandoned the tent at the foot of the ridge and climbed on without [[belay]]s. Neither climber had any difficulty with breathing.{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=216\u2013219}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=202\u2013204}}\n\nThe last fifty feet of the ice cliff was vertical though there were good holds and as they reached the northern side of the mountain the wind dropped. They could see traces of army boot footprints but the flag that had been left a week earlier by the army expedition had blown away. Haston took a cin\u00e9 film of Whillans reaching the summit and then they swapped places. From the top, which they reached at 14:30 and stayed for about 10 minutes, they could see the other two Annapurna summits but nothing more. With no feeling of exhilaration, which they knew would come later. They had {{convert|150|ft}} of rope which, after they had abseiled down, was all there was left on the summit. By 17:00 they had managed the difficult descent to Camp VI.{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=216\u2013219}}{{sfnp|Day|2010|p=188}}{{sfnp|Frost|1971|p=232}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=427}}\n\nLower down the mountain everyone had been completely stormbound but Bonington, having been confined to Camp IV, put in his routine 17:00 radio call asking Haston if they had been able to get out of their camp. Due to static on the radio he did not hear the reply \"Aye, we've just climbed Annapurna\" but this was heard load and clear at Base Camp and the news spread rapidly up the mountain.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=204}}{{sfnp|Haston|1971|p=219}}\n\n===Leaving the mountain===\nBurke and Frost wanted to make their own attempt on the summit and, contrary to his better judgement, Bonington agreed subject to the clearing of the camps proceeding at the same time. So on 28 May, Burke and Frost while Whillans and Haston descended, reaching Camp III at midday. Everyone was very excited but were held back by their British formality. Only by evening did Frost and Burke reach Camp VI. On 29 May they made their attempt but Burke had to turn back and Frost, having reached the snowfield, stayed there almost three hours but then, because it was the Lord's will, turned back in ferocious wind.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=220\u2013224}}\n\nOn 30 May the mountain was being cleared apace with most of the party reaching Base Camp when Thompson rushed down, calling out in despair. He and Clough had been passing under the place of the \"Sword of Damocles\" when a [[serac]] fell creating an avalanche which had killed Clough.{{refn|group=note|The overhanging wall of ice they called the \"Sword of Damocles\" had collapsed on 23 May so they thought the location had become less dangerous. However, there were ice towers higher up and it was one of these that fell.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=111225\u2013226}}}} His body was carried down to base camp and he was buruied near there at the foot of a face where Clough had taught the Sherpas and television to use jumars and to abseil. Returning down the valley they found the earlier snow had melted and flowers were blooming.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=224\u2013229}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe expedition proved to be Britain's most important mountaineering achievement since the [[1953 Everest expedition|1953 British Mount Everest expedition]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Douglas |first1=Ed |title=Don Whillans: the vertical beatnik |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/mar/06/features.sportmonthly1 |work=The Observer |date=6 March 2005 |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912235700/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/mar/06/features.sportmonthly1 |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIt was a huge success because not only was the summit reached but it had been, for its time, the most difficult technical climb to the summit of a major world peak.{{sfnp|Unsworth|2000|p=434}} In mountaineering circles the expedition was recognised as a paradigm shift in [[Alpine style|alpine-style]] climbing. The expedition was at the beginning of a trend away from taking the easiest route on a high Himalayan peak towards choosing a more direct and difficult route.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Derek |title=Behind the Shot: Dougal Haston at Annapurna Basecamp |journal=Adventure Journal |date=3 August 2016 |url=https://www.adventure-journal.com/2016/08/behind-the-shot-dougal-haston-at-annapurna-basecamp/ |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111013011/http://www.adventure-journal.com/2016/08/behind-the-shot-dougal-haston-at-annapurna-basecamp/ |archive-date=11 November 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nFor the first time in Britain a television audience had been able to watch the climb as it progressed. At least once a week interviews with the climbers and film of the climb itself were shown on ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' and it was possible to show film from the summit only five days after it had been taken \u2013 the film was carried back to base camp, taken by runner to Pokhara and then from there to London by air. Afterwards a one-hour documentary was shown on [[Thames Television]].{{sfnp|Burke|1971|pp=282\u2013285}}{{sfnp|Edwards|1971}}\n\nBonington went on to lead further Himalayan expeditions \u2013 the [[1975 British Mount Everest Southwest Face expedition|Everest Southwest Face expedition of 1975]] was a direct successor with Boysen and Thompson participating and where Haston was one of those reaching the summit. On this occasion Burke died when attempting the summit by himself.<ref>{{cite news |title=1975: First Britons conquer Everest |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/24/newsid_2538000/2538093.stm |accessdate=17 January 2020 |work=BBC On this day |date=2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307132259/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/24/newsid_2538000/2538093.stm |archive-date=7 March 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Whillans was invited on no more Bonington expeditions. Haston died skiing off piste in Estcourt was killed in 1972 on K2 on another Bonington exoedition.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McCarthy |first1=Guy |title=Cowboys on K2 |journal=Climbing Magazine |date=19 December 2015 |url=https://www.climbing.com/news/cowboys-on-k2/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124105658/https://www.climbing.com/news/cowboys-on-k2/|archivedate=24 November 211|url-status=live}}</ref>  By 1884 Pasang Kami owned the most lavish hotel in Kathmandu, built up from a yak shelter. It had a penthouse restaurant and was  even equipped with electric lighting.{{sfnp|Bonington|1986|pp=207,209}}\n\nOn 8\u20139 October 2013, [[Ueli Steck]] climbed the South Face, solo and without rope or a support team, to reach Annapurna's summit, taking 28 hours in total over the climb from base camp and the descent.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kiester |first1=Shey |title=Ueli Steck's Annapurna South Face Solo |website=www.alpinist.com |date=14 October 2013 |url=http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web13f/newswire-ueli-steck-south-face-annapurna |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707151936/http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web13f/newswire-ueli-steck-south-face-annapurna |archive-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Horrell |first1=Mark |title=What Ueli Steck meant to ordinary people like me \u2013 Mark Horrell |url=https://www.markhorrell.com/blog/2017/what-ueli-steck-meant-to-ordinary-people-like-me/ |website=Footsteps on the Mountain |publisher=Mark Horrell |date=3 May 2017 |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331055353/https://www.markhorrell.com/blog/2017/what-ueli-steck-meant-to-ordinary-people-like-me/ |archive-date=31 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{cite book|last1=Bonington|first1=Chris|author1-link=Chris Bonington|title=Annapurna South Face|date=1971|publisher=Book Club Associates|ref={{sfnref|Bonington|1971a}}}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Bonington |first1=Christian |author1-link=Chris Bonington|title=Annapurna South face |journal=[[Alpine Journal]] |date=1971 |pages=18\u201333 |url=https://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1971_files/AJ%201971%2018-33%20Bonington%20Annapurna.pdf|ref={{sfnref|Bonington|1971b}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bonington|first1=Chris|author1-link=Chris Bonington|title=The Everest Years: a climber's life|date=1986|publisher=[[Hodder & Stoughton]]|location=London|isbn=0340366907}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bonington |first1=Chris |authorlink1=Chris Bonington |title=Boundless horizons : the autobiography of Chris Bonington|date=1999 |publisher=The Mountaineers |location=Seattle |isbn=0-89886-755-X|url=https://archive.org/details/boundlesshorizon00boni|url-access=registration|via=[[Open Library]]|pages=177\u2013436}} This book is a compendium of three earlier Bonington volumes. The volume cited here is {{cite book |last1=Bonington |first1=Chris |authorlink1=Chris Bonington |title=The Next Horizon |date=1973 |publisher=Gollancz|isbn= 9780575016392}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bonington |first1=Chris |author1-link=Chris Bonington|title=Ascent |date=2017 |publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]] |isbn=978-1-4711-5754-7}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Mick| author1-link=Mick Burke (mountaineer)|editor-first1=Chris|editor-last1=Bonington|editor1-link=Chris Bonington|chapter=Appendix F, Cine Photography|title=Annapurna South Face|publisher=Book Club Associates|year=1971|pages=282\u2013285}} This book is a compendium of three previous Bonington books. The volume discussing Annapurna South Face is {{cite book |last1=Bonington |first1=Chris |title=The Next Horizon |date=1973 |publisher=Victor Gollancz}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Day |first1=Henry |author-link1=Henry Day (colonel)|title=Annapurna-North face route |journal=[[Alpine Journal]] |date=1971 |pages=88\u201398 |url=https://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1971_files/AJ%201971%2088-98%20Day%20Annapurna.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Day|first1=Henry|author-link1=Henry Day (colonel)|title=Annapurna Anniversaries|journal=[[Alpine Journal]]|date=2010|pages=181\u2013189|url=https://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2010-11_files/AJ%202010-11%20179-189%20Day%20Annapurna.pdf}}\n* {{cite AV media |others= John Edwards (producer), Jeremy Isaacs (executive producer)|last1=Edwards|first1=John|title= Annapurna: Hardest Way Up |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uQE_65nk_p4 |access-date=30 December 2018|type=television production |publisher= [[Thames TV]]|date=16 March 1971}} \u2013 clip from full documentary ''The Hardest Way Up''\n* {{cite journal |last1=Frost |first1=Tom |authorlink1=Tom Frost |title=Annapurna South Face |journal=American Alpine Journal |date=1971 |url=http://publications.americanalpineclub.org/articles/12197122900 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Harlin III |first1=John |title=The Eiger obsession : facing the mountain that killed my father |date=2008 |publisher=Hutchinson |isbn=9780091925581|ref={{sfnref|Harlin|2008}}}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Haston |first1=Dougal| author1-link=Dougal Haston|editor-first1=Chris|editor-last1=Bonington|editor1-link=Chris Bonington|chapter=Chapter 17: The Final Push|title=Annapurna South Face|publisher=Book Club Associates|year=1971|pages=205\u2013219}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Herzog|first1=Maurice|author-link1=Maurice Herzog|title=Annapurna|journal=Alpine Journal|date=1951|volume=58|issue=282|pages=155\u2013168\n| url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1951_files/AJ58%201951%20155-168%20Herzog%20Annapurna.pdf|ref=harf}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Herzog|first1=Maurice|author-link1=Maurice Herzog|title=Annapurna|date=1954|publisher=Reprint Society\n| translator1-first=Nea|translator1-last=Morin|translator1-link=Nea Morin\n| translator2-first=Janet|translator2-last=Adam Smith|translator2-link=Janet Adam Smith\n}} Introduction by [[Eric Shipton|Shipton, Eric]].\n* {{cite book|last1=Isserman|first1=Maurice|author1-link=Maurice Isserman|last2=Weaver|first2=Stewart|title=Fallen Giants : A History of Himalayan Mountaineering from the Age of Empire to the Age of Extremes|date=2008|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=9780300115017|edition=1|chapter=The Golden Age Postponed}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Thompson|first1=Simon|title=Unjustifiable risk? : the story of British climbing|date=2010|chapter=Chapter 6. 1939\u20131970: Hard Men in an Affluent Society|publisher=Cicerone|location=Milnthorpe|isbn=9781852846275}}\n* {{cite book|last=Unsworth|first=Walt|title=Everest: The Mountaineering History|publisher=Mountaineers Books|date=2000|location=Seattle, WA, US|isbn=978-0898866704}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Ward|first1=M. P.|last2=Clark|first2=P. K.|title=Everest, 1951: Cartographic and Photographic Evidence of a New Route from Nepal|journal=The Geographical Journal|date=March 1992|volume=158|issue=1|pages=47\u201356|doi=10.2307/3060016|jstor=3060016}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last1=Messner|first1=Reinhold|title=Annapurna: 50 years of expeditions in the death zone|date=2000|publisher=Mountaineers Book|location=Seattle|isbn=9780898867381|ref=none}}\n\n{{coord|28|35|43|N|83|49|32|E|display=title|format=dms|type:mountain_region:NP}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Annapurna South Face expedition, 1970 British}}\n[[Category:Himalayas]]\n[[Category:Expeditions from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Asian expeditions|Anna]]\n[[Category:1970 in Nepal|Annapurna 1970]]\n[[Category:1970 in the United Kingdom|Anna]]\n[[Category:Mountaineering expeditions to the Himalayas|Anna]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|First ascent of Himalayan mountain face using rock climbing techniques}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Annapurna Base Camp Range 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Annapurna South Face from Base Camp (2013)]]\nThe '''1970 British Annapurna South Face expedition''' was a Himalayan climb that was the first to take a deliberately difficult route up the face of an [[Eight-thousander|8,000-metre mountain]]. On 27 May 1970 [[Don Whillans]] and [[Dougal Haston]] reached the summit of [[Annapurna I]] which at {{convert|26545|ft}} is the highest peak in the [[Annapurna Massif]] in [[Nepal]]. [[Chris Bonington]] led the expedition which approached up a glacier from the [[Annapurna Sanctuary]] and then used rock climbing techniques to put [[fixed rope]]s up the steep South Face. Although the plan had been to use supplementary oxygen, in the event it was not possible to carry any cylinders high enough for the lead climbers to use on their summit bid.\n\nLow down on the mountain, on 30 May as the expedition was about to leave, [[Ian Clough]] was killed by a falling [[serac]]. Several members of the expedition rose to fame in Britain, and as a whole the expedition received international recognition in mountaineering circles on account of its innovative and extremely difficult nature.\n\n== Background ==\n=== Annapurna ===\n{{see also|Mount Everest reconnaissance from Nepal}}\nThe [[Annapurna Massif|Annapurna massif]] is in the [[Eastern Himalaya]]a region of Nepal where for over one hundred years the ruling [[Rana dynasty]]  had not allowed explorers or mountaineers to enter the country.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=238\u2013241}}{{sfnp|Ward|Clark|1992}} In 1950 Nepal at last gave permission for the [[1950 French Annapurna expedition]], to attempt [[Dhaulagiri]] or [[Annapurna I Main|Annapurna I]], the two highest peaks in the Annapurna region. The expedition, led by [[Maurice Herzog]], mounted a successful summit attempt via the North Face. For most Himalayan mountains the easiest route to the summit is along a ridge route but for Annapurna the North Face is not too steep (though it is very exposed to avalanches) and the route subsequently turned out to be the easiest.{{sfnp|Herzog|1954|pp=48,54,57,102\u2013103}}{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=242\u2013253,387}} Although it was the first climbed of the eight-thousanders, Annapurna is not often climbed and there is a high death rate among those attempting it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adam |first1=Voiland |title=The Eight-Thousanders |url=https://www.earthobservatory.nasa.gov/features/8000MeterPeaks |website=www.earthobservatory.nasa.gov |publisher=NASA |date=16 December 2013 |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503184334/https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/Features/8000MeterPeaks/ |archive-date=3 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Start of rock climbing in Himalaya ===\nAfter years of stagnation between the wars, British rock climbing underwent a renaissance, particularly with working-class climbing clubs starting up in the north of England and Scotland. The [[Rock and Ice Club]] in [[Manchester]], the Creagh Dhu Mountaineering Club in [[Glasgow]] and several university climbing clubs were amongst those that engendered a highly competitive climbing environment. At [[Clogwyn Du'r Arddu]] in Wales numerous routes of a very high standard were achieved using strictly [[free climbing]] techniques. [[Hamish MacInnes]] and [[Dougal Haston]], although not members, climbed with Creagh Dhu and MacInnes had mentored [[Chris Bonington]]'s youthful climbing as early as 1953.{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|pp=189\u2013260}}\n\nIn 1960, Bonington, as a member of a joint British\u2013Indian\u2013Nepalese army team led by [[J. O. M. Roberts|Jimmy Roberts]], reached the summit of the {{convert|26039|ft|adj=on}} [[Annapurna II]], {{convert|20|mi}} east of the range's main summit, Annapurna I. The route did not involve rock climbing.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=347,387}}\n\n[[Mount Everest]] was ascended in 1963 by an American team along [[Timeline of Mount Everest expeditions#1963|a deliberately difficult route along its West Ridge]].{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|p=387}}  Two years later, when planning with the American [[John Harlin]] for Harlin's ''direttissima'' attempt on the [[Eigerwand|North Face of the Eiger]], Harlin introduced Bonington to the American [[Big wall climbing|big wall]] technique of directly ascending a [[fixed rope]] using [[Jumar]]s.{{sfnp|Harlin|2008|pp=109\u2013111}} Harlin fell to his death and Haston's success on the route were reported on by Bonington and [[Mick Burke (mountaineer)|Mick Burke]] who were on the North Face as climbing journalist and cameraman.{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|p=246}} The publicity led to the televising of a climb of the [[Old Man of Hoy]] in Scotland, this time featuring Bonington and Haston.{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|p=231}} From this start, commercial sponsorship became a possibility for rock climbing and more elaborate and ambitious expeditions could be planned. With all fourteen [[Eight-thousander|8000-metre peaks]] climbed by 1964, Himalayan expeditions using rock climbing routes became an opportunity Bonington wanted to seize.{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|pp=189\u2013260}}\n\nEncouraged by Roberts, Bonington conceived of the idea of climbing [[Annapurna]] by its South Face which he realised was going to require not just rock climbing but also [[Expedition style|siege climbing tactics]] because the ascent would take many weeks. No one had tried rock climbing at high altitude before. The face itself was almost twice as high as the {{convert|6000|ft}} [[Eigerwand]] and even above the rock band there was another {{convert|3000|ft}} to the summit.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971b|p=18\u201333}}{{sfnp|Bonington|2017|p=155}}{{sfnp|Thompson|2010|pp=189\u2013260}}  The topography near the summit could be assessed from photographs Bonington had taken on the Annapurna II expedition of ten years earlier.{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=411}}\n\n===Planning===\n{{external media|topic=Clip from TV programme|Annapurna|title=Annapurna South Face|headerimage=|caption=\n|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uQE_65nk_p4 Annapurna: The Hardest Way Up]{{sfnp|Edwards|1971}}}}\nWith financial support for the expedition from the [[Mount Everest Foundation]], Bonington assembled a team from amongst his friends: [[Nick Estcourt]], [[Martin Boysen]], [[Ian Clough]], Mike Thompson, Burke and Haston. Advised to include an American to boost sales of the book he was planning, Bonington appointed [[Tom Frost]] who had considerable [[big wall]] experience in [[Yosemite]] as well as \u2013 secretly at the time \u2013 [[Nanda Devi]] on a [[Nanda Devi#CIA mission|CIA mission]] to install a nuclear-powered listening device for monitoring [[China and weapons of mass destruction|Chinese missiles]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=2\u201313,238\u2013239}} Frost was known to and respected by Haston and [[Don Whillans]]. Whillans was to be deputy leader for, although by then he was an overweight heavy drinker and smoker who disliked Bonington, he had more Himalayan experience than any other British mountaineer still active.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=389\u2013390}} Indeed, only he, Bonington and Clough had been to Himalaya at all.{{sfnp|Bonington|1986|p=16}} Also included as climbers were [[Kelvin Kent (mountaineer)|Kelvin Kent]], base camp manager, and David Lambert, the doctor. A four-man television team from [[ITN]] and [[Thames Television]] was to be accompanying them.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=2\u201313,238\u2013239}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=414}}\n\n===Departure===\nThey took {{convert|18000|ft}} of rope for fixing (they did not use their climbing rope), 40 cylinders of Oxygen and six breathing sets.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=246,257}} The baggage was sent from London by sea with Whillans and Lambert flying to [[Bombay]]{{refn|group=note|[[Mumbai]] is the present name.}} to see to its unloading and transport to [[Pokhara]] by lorry. However, the ship was then delayed by about three weeks so Bonington arranged for Whillans and Lambert to travel to [[Kathmandu]] to reconnoitre the approach route instead of waiting at Bombay, and Clough would go to Bombay to deal with the baggage.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=29\u201331,39}} They took oxygen cylinders intending to use supplementary oxygen above about {{convert|22500|ft}} but it was very little used for climbing and not at all above Camp VI. It was used, however, for people who had become ill.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=257\u2013259}}\n\n==Expedition==\n===March-in and Base Camp===\n[[File:1970 Annapurna south face expedition approach route.svg|thumb|Approach route from [[Pokhara]] to Annapurna Base Camp]]\nIn March 1970 the expedition flew to Kathmandu and then on to [[Pokhara]] from where the trek to the southern vicinity of Annapurna was along an easy route. Unlike twenty years earlier when [[Maurice Herzog|Herzog]] had no satisfactory map and had to pioneer a route, by 1970 the track was well known even to [[hippie]] wanderers.{{refn|group=note|The eight-day trek route from Pokhara went up beside the [[Seti Gandaki River|Seti Khola]] river and then the Modi Khola (a tributary of the [[Gandaki river]]). Bonington notes passing through [[Naudanda]], [[Lumle]], Chondracot (now Chandrakot), Ghandrung (now [[Ghandruk]]), Chomro (now Chhomrong), Thomo and Hinko Cave.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=47\u201350,54,79}}}} Another change was that the Sherpas were no longer unsophisticated peasants \u2013 they were smart in appearance, spoke good English and had a Western attitude. [[Pasang Kami]], the sirdar, treated the sahibs as equals and this was reciprocated. The other Sherpas were Pemba Tharkay, Ang Pema, Mingma Tsering, Nima Tsering and Kancha. As it turned out, a group from the British Army Mountaineering Association, led by [[Henry Day (colonel)|Henry Day]], was setting off at the same time for an ascent on Herzog's north face route and they had greatly helped Bonington by flying out {{convert|1500|lb}} of baggage to supply him until his main baggage arrived.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|pp=390\u2013391}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=29,39,43,238}}{{sfnp|Day|1971|p=89}}\n\nOn 16 March Whillans, Thompson and two Sherpas went ahead of the main parties to reconnoitre the route and to find a suitable place for the base camp.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=38\u201339}} A temporary location was found to be at the entrance to the [[Annapurna Sanctuary]] at the location of a previous base camp: that of the 1957 expedition to [[Machapuchare]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=18,51}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=416}}\nThe slower-moving baggage train of 140 porters set off from Pokhara on 22 March and Clough with his 240 porters was able to leave Bombay with the delayed baggage on 24 March.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=42,53,81}}\n\nBonington and Whillans met up on 27 March and Whillans said he thought he and his Sherpas had seen a [[yeti]] and had photographed the footprints. More significantly, he had been able to identify a climbing route up the mountain's south face.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=56\u201362,68, ill 10}} After the whole party has gathered at the temporary base camp on 29 March an advance party including Whillans, Haston and Burke established a final base camp at {{convert|14000|ft}} three miles from the foot of the face.{{sfnp|Isserman|Weaver|2008|p=391}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=42}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=417}} Estcourt used a theodolite to make accurate altitude measurements of various points on the face because foreshortening makes estimation inaccurate. The porters returned to Pokhara from where many of them would help move up to Base Camp the main baggage being carried from Bombay by the party led by Clough, Thompson and Kent. Meanwhile, the lead climbers and Sherpas were left to ferry the advance baggage up to the final Base Camp.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=62\u201366}} The monsoon was due at bbout the end of May.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=166,195}}\n\n===Climbing route===\n[[File:1970 Annapurna south face expedition climbing route.png|thumb|Climbing route up South Face]]\nBetween Camp III at {{convert|20100|ft}} and the top of the Rock Band at {{convert|24750|ft}} the average slope is 55\u00b0.{{refn|group=note|Bonington compares this with 44\u00b0 on the [[Aiguille de la Brenva|Brenva face]] of [[Mont Blanc]] and 61\u00b0 on the Walker Spur of the [[Grandes Jorasses]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=237}}}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=236\u2013237}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | Locations of camps on mountain\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Camp\n! colspan=\"2\" | Altitude\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Occupied{{refn|group=note|Dates of occupation{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=233}} unless noted otherwise.}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Description\n|-\n!  feet{{refn|group=note|Altitudes{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=237}} unless noted otherwise.}} !! metres{{refn|group=note|Altitudes in metres calculated from referenced figures in feet.}}\n|-\n| Temporary Base || 12,000{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|loc=plate 12}} || {{convert|12000|ft|disp=number}} || 28&nbsp;March<br />{{refn|group=note|Date of occupation by main party;  for advance party \u2013 21 March.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=51}}}} || sited at Base Camp of 1957 Machapuchare expedition{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=18,60}}\n|-\n| Base || 14,000 || {{convert|14000|ft|disp=number}} || 31 March{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=66}} || side of Annapurna glacier{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=60}}\n|-\n| Camp I || 16,000 || {{convert|16000|ft|disp=number}} || 2 April || on [[Nunatak|\"rognon\"]] (island of rock in glacier){{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=64}}\n|-\n| Camp II || 17,500 || {{convert|17500|ft|disp=number}} || 6 April || under rock overhang{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=76}}\n|-\n| Camp III || 20,100 || {{convert|20100|ft|disp=number}} || 13 April || large, flat area at Col{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=85}}\n|-\n| Camp IV || 21,300 || {{convert|21300|ft|disp=number}} || 23 April || sloping 30\u00b0  on Ice Ridge{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=109,111}}\n|-\n| dump || 21,650{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=154,236}} || {{convert|21650|ft|disp=number}} || 11 May || col at top of Ice Ridge{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=139\u2013140,154,236}}\n|-\n| temporary<br /> Camp&nbsp;V || 22,500<br />{{refn|group=note|8,500 feet above Base Camp at 14,000 feet.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=147,237}}}} || {{convert|22500|ft|disp=number}} || 6 May{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=141}} || foot of Ice Wall, vulnerable to snow sliding from above{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=141}}\n|-\n| Camp V || 22,750 || {{convert|22750|ft|disp=number}} || 9 May || [[bergschrund]] at foot of Rock Band{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=149,152}}\n|-\n| Camp VI || 24,000 || {{convert|24000|ft|disp=number}} || 19 May || tiny platform carved in snow at top of Flat Iron{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=194}}\n|-\n| Summit || 26,545 || {{convert|26545|ft|disp=number}} || 27 May ||\n|}\n\n===To Camp III and abortive start up Ice Ridge===\nWhillans and Haston had found a difficult route across the glacier and up to a [[Nunatak|rognon]] \u2013 an island of rock on a glacier \u2013 where Camp I was planned to be and then reached the flattish top of the rognon where Camp I would be just far enough away from the face \u2013 about a mile away \u2013 to avoid avalanche danger. Bonington and Burke relocated the lower part of the route hoping to make it suitable for porters.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=64\u201372}}\n\nThe ridge they were to use at the start of the climb was straightforwardly approached across the glacier but steep cliff barred the way onto the ridge itself so they skirted these on the right to reach a site for Camp II, lower than hoped for but with nowhere suitable immediately higher. For a short distance the route was seriously threatened by an ice overhang which they called the \"Sword of Damocles\" but they decided to reduce the risk by moving under it as quickly as possible.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=73\u201377}}\n\nWhen he arrived with the main baggage Clough was supposed to stop at Hinko Cave overnight on 7 April but, due to confusing instructions, with his entourage of 240 porters he continued on in a snowstorm to temporary base camp some miles further on. Some porters had refused to go beyond Hinko Cave and the rest, overloaded and without adequate clothes and shoes in the bad weather, variously got into states of anger and collapse. However, now the main gear had arrived, it was possible to sort out shelter under cover for the night and provide medical help when necessary.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=79\u201381}} On this same day Whillans and Haston had reached the Ice Ridge at a col where Camp III was to be established. They had to climb through deep snow in bad weather. In ten days the expedition had got from the Sanctuary to half height on the face, although with the difficult climbing all to be done further ahead. They [[abseil]]ed down to Camp II from where, next day, they started placing fixed ropes towards the col.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=81\u201383}}\n\nOn 11 March Boysen and Estcourt established Camp III on the col, where there were to be two Whillans Box tents at a spacious location, free from risk of avalanches or falling rocks.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=85,98}} The version used on Annapurna, designed by Whillans, was [[cuboid]] in shape, {{convert|6.5|x|4.0|x|4|ft}}, made of socketed aluminium tubes covered in nylon top and bottom and cotton-[[terylene]] at the sides. It was strengthened with nylon webbing straps and at one end was a nylon-zipped entrance. An inner nylon tent was available but not always used. It weighed {{convert|30|lb}}{{refn|group=note|In comparison the nylon tents of a hooped design, Bonington calls them RAFMA tents, weighed only {{convert|10|lb}}.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=251}}}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=66\u201367,249\u2013250}}\n\nOn 12 April, after Bonington had organised the logistics of getting Base Camp fully set up and equipped, he and Frost set from there so that on 14 April they could start to prospect a route up the Ice Ridge above Camp III. After investigating a snow shelf leading to a gully on the west of the ridge, Bonington decided avalanches posed too great a threat so he joined Frost who was ascending along the actual crest of the ridge. However, this turned out to be much more difficult than they had expected with snow too soft and loose for firm [[piton]] placements and there would be a need to set [[fixed rope]]s all the way up the ridge. Also, they had not formed a plan for placing fixed ropes \u2013 should the lead climber fix his rope or should he climb normally leaving the second climber to pay out a rope from his rucksack, fixing it as he climbed? To begin with the latter method seemed more successful but progress was dreadfully slow with Bonington never having previously encountered such appalling snow.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=86\u201391}} Later in the expedition the technique changed and they climbed using their {{convert|9|mm|adj=on}} fixed rope which they then secured with pitons and [[karabiner]]s, not using their {{convert|11|mm|adj=on}} climbing rope at all.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=247}}\n\nThat night at Camp III they discussed their religious beliefs \u2013 Bonington was a sceptic and Frost a [[Morman]]. Bonington wrote to his wife \"He is a convinced and fervent Mormon, never rams it down your throat, yet his faith has given him a code of conduct that puts him way out in front of most of us\". Next day it was straightforward to re-climb their fixed rope but again onward climbing was extremely difficult. On the previous day and this one Whillans and Haston had been ferrying supplies from Camp II up to Camp III and following their second climb they starting exploring the shelf which Bonington had investigated previously beside the ridge. Here they made such good progress that the pair on the ridge needed little persuasion to abandon  entirely their efforts on the lowest part of the ridge.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=91\u201395}}\n\nNext day all four climbers set off along the shelf with Haston breaking trail and never surrendering the lead. The avalanche risk was considerable even though they kept their distance from the ridge and matters got worse as they reached the gully threatened by avalanches from ice cliffs thousands of feet above and by [[Snow cornice|cornices]] on the ridge itself. They decided to avoid the gully by climbing a minor [[ar\u00eate]] which led from the foot of the gully up to a high point on the main ridge but they had to leave a [[deadman anchor]] when deteriorating weather forced them to retreat to camp. Next day Bonington and Frost got within {{convert|50|ft}} of the crest of the Ice Ridge but again bad weather forced a retreat.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=95\u201399}}\n\nBy 18 April only {{convert|1000|ft}} had been gained since the Col had been reached eleven days earlier and from Base Camp and on 19 April Haston again ascended the minor ar\u00eate where the way to the main ridge was blocked by huge cornices but he found he could slip through gaps in the rotten snow between the wall of the ridge and one of the cornices. However, after reaching the crest of main ridge and fixing a rope he was forced back by the weather. At last, two days later, he was able to reach the Ice Ridge and find an ideal place for Camp IV.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=102\u2013109}}\n\nThe expedition was unexpectedly enhanced when four trekkers \u2013 the Sherpas called them the \"London Sherpas\" \u2013 turned up at Base Camp completely unexpectedly.{{refn|group=note|The trekkers had left [[Essex]] in England in 1969 in a [[Land Rover]], planning to climb in the [[Hindu Kush]]. Delayed in Austria they had spent the winter in Afghanistan and then had driven to Kathmandu, flown to Pokhara, trekked over to the foothills of [[Dhaulagiri]] and crossed to Chomro via the Deroli Pass intending to reach the [[Annapurna Sanctuary]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=109}} The Deroli Pass, now more usually referred to as the [[Deurali Pass]], is on the [[Annapurna Circuit]] trail, near [[Ghorepani]] and [[Poon Hill]].}} In return for \"board and lodging\" the two men helped carry loads even as high as Camp IV and the women helped at Base Camp where Bonington thought their presence engendered a more a civilised and relaxed air. Other trekkers also turned up to get a grandstand view of the climb and to help carrying loads.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=109\u2013110}}\n\n===Camp IV to Camp V on the Rock Band===\nBoysen, Estcourt, Haston and Whillans worked together establishing Camp IV but the situation at Camp III became critical after several attempts to supply it from Camp II had failed because of deep snow and avalanches. Eventually an overnight carry was successful and in general it seemed the snow conditions improved the higher one got up the mountain.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=110\u2013114}}\n\nBoysen and Estcourt tackled the upper part of the Ice Ridge above Camp IV which was very narrow with cornices to the left but solid rock on the right. At one point Boysen's progress was blocked except for a {{convert|20|ft|adj=on}} tunnel which he could clamber through, without his rucksack, as if potholing. The tunnel led not further up the ridge but out onto an ice cliff with a {{convert|2000|ft|adj=on}} drop to the glacier. However, he managed to climb onto and up the cliff despite the drag of his climbing rope passing along a highly contorted route behind him. When he reached safety he had let out {{convert|150|ft}} of rope in ascending only {{convert|50|ft}}. It was the most difficult ice climb Boysen had ever done. There was no direct way for Estcourt to ascend to Boysen's stance so he had to repeat the circuitous climb. Boysen's next lead again went on to a traverse, which was later called the \"Terrible Traverse\", which he was not able to complete before descending to Camp IV for the night. They had spent all day climbing {{convert|300|ft}}.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=115\u2013119,125}} Next day it again proved impossible to keep to the crest of the ridge but a descent on the right to solid rock gave access to an ice-covered rock wall leading upwards. This climb had to be without the rope being secured with pitons because the rope would have jammed along its contorted route. They regained the ridge again only some {{convert|50|ft}} higher than they had reached the previous day. The following day they extended their route slightly further. After that they had to go down to recover from exhaustion but the fixed ropes they had left allowed everyone following to take a direct line though one that was neither safe nor easy.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=119\u2013121,125}}\n\nBonington and Clough took over the work of extending the route, reaching Camp IV on 27 April. Sometimes they advanced only {{convert|10|ft}} in an hour.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=123\u2013128}} At Whillans' suggestion, they arranged for Sherpas to carry all the climbers'supplies up to Camp III so that when climbers went down to rest they only needed to go to Camp III rather than Base Camp.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=128}} After a few very difficult days, and without being able to regain the crest of the Ice Ridge at a higher point, Clough went down to be replaced by Haston. On 3 May Whillans, Frost and Burke carried a box tent up to Camp IV while Bonington and Haston with very difficult ice climbing reached a col at {{convert|21650|ft}} where the Ice Ridge terminates to be replaced by a snow slope leading up to the Ice Wall.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=124\u2013141}} Next day they carried a load of ropes to the col and Haston ran out {{convert|500|ft}} of rope towards the Ice Wall. At {{convert|22350|ft}} the slope suddenly changes from 45\u00b0 to vertical and this point was planned to become Camp V{{refn|group=note|The site turned out to be very poor so the camp here was only temporary.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=149}}}} where a {{convert|18|lb|adj=on}} hooped tent was set up, capable of sleeping three. Supplying as high as here was a logistical problem because it took at least five days for anything to arrive from base camp.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=141,251}}\n\nSupported by Frost and Burke, Whillans and Haston established Camp V but that night spindrift  inundated the site and the tent so they decided to find a better camp location. Next day they explored the Ice Wall finding a \"gangway\" leading to the top of the Ice Wall and the foot of the Rock Band. At this point the overhang of the [[bergschrund]], although threatening, provided excellent shelter so they proposed moving Camp V to this point. On 9 May Frost and Burke established the camp at the new, higher location.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=141\u2013153}} The climb from Camp IV to V was very long and difficult so two intermediate dumps{{refn|group=note|The lower of the dumps was at the top of the Ice Ridge and the other was at the original site for Camp V at the bottom of the Ice Wall.}} for supplies were used with carrying being done in shorter sections from above and below.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=149\u2013150,154,178}}\n\n===Above Camp V===\n[[File:Tom Frost - South Face of Annapurna - 1970.jpg|thumb|Photograph by Frost: Boysen descending to Camp IV after carrying supplies up to Camp V.]]\nFrost and Burke started on the Rock Band which sloped at about 50\u00b0{{refn|group=note|Bonington likens this to the Second Ice Field on the [[Nordwand|North face of the Eiger]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=160}}}} Instead of taking the most direct line up a groove leading straight upwards, they cut over to the left aiming for the \"Flat Iron\", named after the similar-looking feature on the Eiger, with Burke doing the lead climbing. The good weather helped with the climbing but because of the thaw they were bombarded  from above by falling rocks. The climbers Further down the mountain were having to rest through illness or exhaustion so shortages of rope, oxygen, tents, food and fuel built up towards Camp V. On 12 May Burke and Frost made more progress but only through taking serious risks with inadequate piton placements but when they turned back for the day a storm hit them and their tent was almost buried. Fortunately by that time fresh supplies had arrived from lower camps.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=154\u2013172}}\n\nBonington's general plan had been to pair off the leading climbers and to share the work of the pairs equitably by having periods of rest, carrying supplies to higher camps and extending the route. The Sherpas were carrying higher up the mountain than expected and other trekkers with climbing experience had turned up by chance and helped out. However at the higher camps things were not going so well and so on 13 May Bonington decided that when Frost and Burke came down to be rested they would be replaced by Whillans and Haston. In fact it was the turn of Estcourt and Boysen to force the route upwards but they had been working hard doing carrying while Whillans and Haston were rested. Over the radio between various camps some of the adversely affected climbers complained but were accepting it after Bonington agreed for Whillans and Haston to do a single carry before rotating into the lead. Whillans then started criticising Burke and Frost for making very slow progress on the Rock Band and so, to curtail the increasing bitterness, the radio call was ended leaving each pair to plan the detail of their newly assigned roles.{{refn|group=note|Bonington did not think Whillans' criticisms were at all fair. Indeed Burke and Frost has worked hard and made good progress.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=182}}}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=173\u2013180}}\n\nOn their last day in the lead Burke and Frost, possibly goaded by the criticism, managed to fix ropes up all the way to the Flat Iron. Burke had been on the face for 28 days, and Frost only slightly less \u2013 Bonington thought Burke's climb had been on the most exacting rock of the entire expedition. When Frost met Bonington down at Camp II he firmly told him he thought the stab in the back of Estcourt and Boysen had wrecked the morale of the expedition \u2013 all the same he maintained his close relationship with Bonington.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=180\u2013184}}\n\nOn 17 May Boysen, Whillans and Haston carried equipment to the top of the Flat Iron to a suitable site for Camp VI but on the way Boysen had to return to camp to recover. Whillans and Haston found a site for Camp VI but that night at Camp V the ridge tent was crushed with an avalanche of snow so Estcourt and Haston went down to the upper dump to collect the one intended for Camp VII and to get more food. Climbing back to Camp VI on 19 May, Haston's rucksack, containing his personal gear and food for Camp VI, fell down the mountain. So, that night, Whillans was alone at Camp VII with no food after the others had descended. Estcourt was alone at Camp V and so Bonington went up there to help him support the lead team. The climb from there to Camp VI was even more tiring and Bonington scarcely managed the {convert|200|ft|adj=on}} [[jumar]] climb near the top. However, he managed and even took the time on his way down to relocate the dangling rope and place further [[piton]]s on this [[Pitch (ascent/descent)|pitch]] of the climb. As for oxygen, there were only three bottles at Camp V and another three at the upper dump. There was hardly any food or rope at Camp VI.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=154,185\u2013195}}{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=205\u2013209}}\n\nOn 20 May Haston returned to Camp VI where Whillans had been without food for over twenty-four hours. Bonington carried up there more food and a radio but had to dump the rope slightly below the camp. Camp VI was a terrible place \u2013 the tent was too large to fit on the ledge so Whillans and Haston had to sleep lying across the width of the tent. Also, the wind was severe and it was only held by two tent pegs, a rope over the top, and the weight of the climbers.{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=209\u2013209}} The same day Estcourt carried the oxygen bottles up to Camp V from the upper dump and the lead climbers climbed {{convert|400|ft}} up from Camp VI but they were then out of food and rope and had no tent to pitch for Camp VII which they intended to place at the top of the Rock Band. They heard news that the army team on the other side of the mountain had reached the summit using a similar route to that of the [[1950 French Annapurna expedition|French expedition in 1950]].{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=196\u2013200}}\n\nOn 22 May Bonington and Estcourt headed up with supplies and oxygen cylinders towards Camp VI but Estcourt had to retreat back and Bonington, who was using supplementary oxygen, had to abandon the tent and oxygen ''en route''. Haston and Whillans had reached the top of the \"mini rock band\" at the top of the Rock Band but, with no rope left, they had needed to climb without protection, leaving only about {{convert|1500|ft}} to the summit, they estimated.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=200\u2013202}} They had reached the {{convert|25000|ft|adj=on}} snowfield above the Rock Band but without a tent or food. Next day Bonington carried tent, cin\u00e9 camera and food up from V to VI but he had needed to abandon his personal gear so he had to turn down an offer to join then on a summit attempt, Bonington and so had to go down again but the tent could be carried up next day to be left on the snow field above Camp VI. On 23 May with insufficient rope and no tent for Camp VII, the lead climbers took a rest day.{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=212\u2013216,224}}\n\nIn terrible conditions on 24 May Bonington and Clough managed a carry to Camp VI but found Haston and Whillans had been forced back there so all four climbers had to spend the night together in the two-man tent. Bonington and Clough got back to Camp IV but once there the weather became impossible.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=202\u2013204}}\n\n===Summit===\nFor the next two days the entire mountain was snowbound and it seemed the monsoon had arrived but on 27 May 1970 at Camp VI there was an improvement in the weather. Leaving Camp VI about 07:00, without supplementary oxygen because they had none, Whillans and Haston reached the snow field at 11:00 from where they could see the summit through breaks in the cloud. They agreed to move the tent up to establish a camp at a higher location but they really had a more ambitious goal for the day. Indeed, any camp would be entirely lacking food or sleeping bags. They were faced with an ice plateau leading to a snow ridge and then an {{convert|800|ft|adj=on}} cliff of mixed ice and rock rising up to the top of the mountain. They abandoned the tent at the foot of the ridge and climbed on without [[belay]]s. Neither climber had any difficulty with breathing.{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=216\u2013219}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=202\u2013204}}\n\nThe last fifty feet of the ice cliff was vertical though there were good holds and as they reached the northern side of the mountain the wind dropped. They could see traces of army boot footprints but the flag that had been left a week earlier by the army expedition had blown away. Haston took a cin\u00e9 film of Whillans reaching the summit and then they swapped places. From the top, which they reached at 14:30 and stayed for about 10 minutes, they could see the other two Annapurna summits but nothing more. With no feeling of exhilaration, which they knew would come later. They had {{convert|150|ft}} of rope which, after they had abseiled down, was all there was left on the summit. By 17:00 they had managed the difficult descent to Camp VI.{{sfnp|Haston|1971|pp=216\u2013219}}{{sfnp|Day|2010|p=188}}{{sfnp|Frost|1971|p=232}}{{sfnp|Bonington|1999|p=427}}\n\nLower down the mountain everyone had been completely stormbound but Bonington, having been confined to Camp IV, put in his routine 17:00 radio call asking Haston if they had been able to get out of their camp. Due to static on the radio he did not hear the reply \"Aye, we've just climbed Annapurna\" but this was heard load and clear at Base Camp and the news spread rapidly up the mountain.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|p=204}}{{sfnp|Haston|1971|p=219}}\n\n===Leaving the mountain===\nBurke and Frost wanted to make their own attempt on the summit and, contrary to his better judgement, Bonington agreed subject to the clearing of the camps proceeding at the same time. So on 28 May, Burke and Frost while Whillans and Haston descended, reaching Camp III at midday. Everyone was very excited but were held back by their British formality. Only by evening did Frost and Burke reach Camp VI. On 29 May they made their attempt but Burke had to turn back and Frost, having reached the snowfield, stayed there almost three hours but then, because it was the Lord's will, turned back in ferocious wind.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=220\u2013224}}\n\nOn 30 May the mountain was being cleared apace with most of the party reaching Base Camp when Thompson rushed down, calling out in despair. He and Clough had been passing under the place of the \"Sword of Damocles\" when a [[serac]] fell creating an avalanche which had killed Clough.{{refn|group=note|The overhanging wall of ice they called the \"Sword of Damocles\" had collapsed on 23 May so they thought the location had become less dangerous. However, there were ice towers higher up and it was one of these that fell.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=111225\u2013226}}}} His body was carried down to base camp and he was buruied near there at the foot of a face where Clough had taught the Sherpas and television to use jumars and to abseil. Returning down the valley they found the earlier snow had melted and flowers were blooming.{{sfnp|Bonington|1971a|pp=224\u2013229}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe expedition proved to be Britain's most important mountaineering achievement since the [[1953 Everest expedition|1953 British Mount Everest expedition]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Douglas |first1=Ed |title=Don Whillans: the vertical beatnik |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/mar/06/features.sportmonthly1 |work=The Observer |date=6 March 2005 |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912235700/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/mar/06/features.sportmonthly1 |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIt was a huge success because not only was the summit reached but it had been, for its time, the most difficult technical climb to the summit of a major world peak.{{sfnp|Unsworth|2000|p=434}} In mountaineering circles the expedition was recognised as a paradigm shift in [[Alpine style|alpine-style]] climbing. The expedition was at the beginning of a trend away from taking the easiest route on a high Himalayan peak towards choosing a more direct and difficult route.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Derek |title=Behind the Shot: Dougal Haston at Annapurna Basecamp |journal=Adventure Journal |date=3 August 2016 |url=https://www.adventure-journal.com/2016/08/behind-the-shot-dougal-haston-at-annapurna-basecamp/ |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111013011/http://www.adventure-journal.com/2016/08/behind-the-shot-dougal-haston-at-annapurna-basecamp/ |archive-date=11 November 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nFor the first time in Britain a television audience had been able to watch the climb as it progressed. At least once a week interviews with the climbers and film of the climb itself were shown on ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' and it was possible to show film from the summit only five days after it had been taken \u2013 the film was carried back to base camp, taken by runner to Pokhara and then from there to London by air. Afterwards a one-hour documentary was shown on [[Thames Television]].{{sfnp|Burke|1971|pp=282\u2013285}}{{sfnp|Edwards|1971}}\n\nBonington went on to lead further Himalayan expeditions \u2013 the [[1975 British Mount Everest Southwest Face expedition|Everest Southwest Face expedition of 1975]] was a direct successor with Boysen and Thompson participating and where Haston was one of those reaching the summit. On this occasion Burke died when attempting the summit by himself.<ref>{{cite news |title=1975: First Britons conquer Everest |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/24/newsid_2538000/2538093.stm |accessdate=17 January 2020 |work=BBC On this day |date=2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307132259/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/24/newsid_2538000/2538093.stm |archive-date=7 March 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Whillans was invited on no more Bonington expeditions. Haston died skiing off piste in Estcourt was killed in 1972 on K2 on another Bonington exoedition.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McCarthy |first1=Guy |title=Cowboys on K2 |journal=Climbing Magazine |date=19 December 2015 |url=https://www.climbing.com/news/cowboys-on-k2/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124105658/https://www.climbing.com/news/cowboys-on-k2/|archivedate=24 November 211|url-status=live}}</ref>  By 1884 Pasang Kami owned the most lavish hotel in Kathmandu, built up from a yak shelter. It had a penthouse restaurant and was  even equipped with electric lighting.{{sfnp|Bonington|1986|pp=207,209}}\n\nOn 8\u20139 October 2013, [[Ueli Steck]] climbed the South Face, solo and without rope or a support team, to reach Annapurna's summit, taking 28 hours in total over the climb from base camp and the descent.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kiester |first1=Shey |title=Ueli Steck's Annapurna South Face Solo |website=www.alpinist.com |date=14 October 2013 |url=http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web13f/newswire-ueli-steck-south-face-annapurna |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707151936/http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web13f/newswire-ueli-steck-south-face-annapurna |archive-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Horrell |first1=Mark |title=What Ueli Steck meant to ordinary people like me \u2013 Mark Horrell |url=https://www.markhorrell.com/blog/2017/what-ueli-steck-meant-to-ordinary-people-like-me/ |website=Footsteps on the Mountain |publisher=Mark Horrell |date=3 May 2017 |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331055353/https://www.markhorrell.com/blog/2017/what-ueli-steck-meant-to-ordinary-people-like-me/ |archive-date=31 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{cite book|last1=Bonington|first1=Chris|author1-link=Chris Bonington|title=Annapurna South Face|date=1971|publisher=Book Club Associates|ref={{sfnref|Bonington|1971a}}}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Bonington |first1=Christian |author1-link=Chris Bonington|title=Annapurna South face |journal=[[Alpine Journal]] |date=1971 |pages=18\u201333 |url=https://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1971_files/AJ%201971%2018-33%20Bonington%20Annapurna.pdf|ref={{sfnref|Bonington|1971b}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bonington|first1=Chris|author1-link=Chris Bonington|title=The Everest Years: a climber's life|date=1986|publisher=[[Hodder & Stoughton]]|location=London|isbn=0340366907|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bonington |first1=Chris |authorlink1=Chris Bonington |title=Boundless horizons : the autobiography of Chris Bonington|date=1999 |publisher=The Mountaineers |location=Seattle |isbn=0-89886-755-X|url=https://archive.org/details/boundlesshorizon00boni|url-access=registration|via=[[Open Library]]|pages=177\u2013436|ref=harv}} This book is a compendium of three earlier Bonington volumes. The volume cited here is {{cite book |last1=Bonington |first1=Chris |authorlink1=Chris Bonington |title=The Next Horizon |date=1973 |publisher=Gollancz|isbn= 9780575016392}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bonington |first1=Chris |author1-link=Chris Bonington|title=Ascent |date=2017 |publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]] |isbn=978-1-4711-5754-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Mick| author1-link=Mick Burke (mountaineer)|editor-first1=Chris|editor-last1=Bonington|editor1-link=Chris Bonington|chapter=Appendix F, Cine Photography|title=Annapurna South Face|date=1971|publisher=Book Club Associates|year=1971|pages=282\u2013285|ref=harv}} This book is a compendium of three previous Bonington books. The volume discussing Annapurna South Face is {{cite book |last1=Bonington |first1=Chris |title=The Next Horizon |date=1973 |publisher=Victor Gollancz}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Day |first1=Henry |author-link1=Henry Day (colonel)|title=Annapurna-North face route |journal=[[Alpine Journal]] |date=1971 |pages=88\u201398 |url=https://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1971_files/AJ%201971%2088-98%20Day%20Annapurna.pdf|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Day|first1=Henry|author-link1=Henry Day (colonel)|title=Annapurna Anniversaries|journal=[[Alpine Journal]]|date=2010|pages=181\u2013189|url=https://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2010-11_files/AJ%202010-11%20179-189%20Day%20Annapurna.pdf|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite AV media |others= John Edwards (producer), Jeremy Isaacs (executive producer)|last1=Edwards|first1=John|title= Annapurna: Hardest Way Up |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uQE_65nk_p4 |access-date=30 December 2018|type=television production |publisher= [[Thames TV]]|date=16 March 1971|ref=harv}} \u2013 clip from full documentary ''The Hardest Way Up''\n* {{cite journal |last1=Frost |first1=Tom |authorlink1=Tom Frost |title=Annapurna South Face |journal=American Alpine Journal |date=1971 |url=http://publications.americanalpineclub.org/articles/12197122900 |accessdate=16 January 2020|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Harlin III |first1=John |title=The Eiger obsession : facing the mountain that killed my father |date=2008 |publisher=Hutchinson |isbn=9780091925581|ref={{sfnref|Harlin|2008}}}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Haston |first1=Dougal| author1-link=Dougal Haston|editor-first1=Chris|editor-last1=Bonington|editor1-link=Chris Bonington|chapter=Chapter 17: The Final Push|title=Annapurna South Face|date=1971|publisher=Book Club Associates|year=1971|pages=205\u2013219|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Herzog|first1=Maurice|author-link1=Maurice Herzog|title=Annapurna|journal=Alpine Journal|date=1951|volume=58|issue=282|pages=155\u2013168\n| url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1951_files/AJ58%201951%20155-168%20Herzog%20Annapurna.pdf|ref=harf}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Herzog|first1=Maurice|author-link1=Maurice Herzog|title=Annapurna|date=1954|publisher=Reprint Society\n| translator1-first=Nea|translator1-last=Morin|translator1-link=Nea Morin\n| translator2-first=Janet|translator2-last=Adam Smith|translator2-link=Janet Adam Smith\n| ref=harv}} Introduction by [[Eric Shipton|Shipton, Eric]].\n* {{cite book|last1=Isserman|first1=Maurice|author1-link=Maurice Isserman|last2=Weaver|first2=Stewart|title=Fallen Giants : A History of Himalayan Mountaineering from the Age of Empire to the Age of Extremes|date=2008|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=9780300115017|edition=1|ref=harv|chapter=The Golden Age Postponed}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Thompson|first1=Simon|title=Unjustifiable risk? : the story of British climbing|date=2010|chapter=Chapter 6. 1939\u20131970: Hard Men in an Affluent Society|publisher=Cicerone|location=Milnthorpe|isbn=9781852846275|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Unsworth|first=Walt|title=Everest: The Mountaineering History|publisher=Mountaineers Books|date=2000|location=Seattle, WA, US|isbn=978-0898866704|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Ward|first1=M. P.|last2=Clark|first2=P. K.|title=Everest, 1951: Cartographic and Photographic Evidence of a New Route from Nepal|journal=The Geographical Journal|date=March 1992|volume=158|issue=1|pages=47\u201356|doi=10.2307/3060016|ref=harv|jstor=3060016}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last1=Messner|first1=Reinhold|title=Annapurna: 50 years of expeditions in the death zone|date=2000|publisher=Mountaineers Book|location=Seattle|isbn=9780898867381|ref=none}}\n\n{{coord|28|35|43|N|83|49|32|E|display=title|format=dms|type:mountain_region:NP}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Annapurna South Face expedition, 1970 British}}\n\n[[Category:Himalayas]]\n[[Category:Expeditions from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Asian expeditions|Anna]]\n[[Category:1970 in Nepal|Annapurna 1970]]\n[[Category:1970 in the United Kingdom|Anna]]\n[[Category:Mountaineering expeditions to the Himalayas|Anna]]\n", "name_user": "Headbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, removed: |ref=harv (14)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1970_British_Annapurna_South_Face_expedition"}
{"title_page": "Nita Martan", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Nita Martan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date   = July 4, 1898 \n| birth_place  = [[Colorado]], [[United States]]\n| death_date   = June 1, 1986 \n| death_place  = [[Riverside, California]], United States\n| othername   = Manilla Martan \n| occupation  = Actress\n| yearsactive = 1920\u20131931 (film)\n}}\n'''Nita Martan''' (1898\u20131986) was an American [[stage actor|stage]] and [[film actress]], active in the [[silent era|silent]] and early [[sound era]]s.<ref>Munden p.193</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[The Son of Tarzan (film)|The Son of Tarzan]]'' (1920) (credited as Manilla Martan)\n* ''[[Lost at the Front]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Dog Justice]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Lady Be Good (1928 film)|Lady Be Good]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Twin Beds (1929 film)|Twin Beds]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Borrowed Wives]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[Chasing Rainbows (1930 film)|Chasing Rainbows]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[The Third Alarm]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[Two Gun Man]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Anybody's Blonde]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Caught Cheating]]'' (1931)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Munden, Kenneth White. ''The American Film Institute Catalog of Motion Pictures Produced in the United States, Part 1''. University of California Press, 1997.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0551424}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martan, Nita}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Colorado]]\n\n\n{{US-film-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Nita Martan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date   = July 4, 1898 \n| birth_place  = [[Colorado]], [[United States]]\n| death_date   = June 1, 1986 \n| death_place  = [[ Riverside, California]], United States\n| othername   = Manilla Martan \n| occupation  = Actress\n| yearsactive = 1920\u20131931 (film)\n}}\n'''Nita Martan''' (1898\u20131986) was an American [[stage actor|stage]] and [[film actress]], active in the [[silent era|silent]] and early [[sound era]]s.<ref>Munden p.193</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[The Son of Tarzan (film)|The Son of Tarzan]]'' (1920) (credited as Manilla Martan)\n* ''[[Lost at the Front]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Dog Justice]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Lady Be Good (1928 film)|Lady Be Good]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Twin Beds (1929 film)|Twin Beds]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Borrowed Wives]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[Chasing Rainbows (1930 film)|Chasing Rainbows]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[The Third Alarm]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[Two Gun Man]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Anybody's Blonde]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Caught Cheating]]'' (1931)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Munden, Kenneth White. ''The American Film Institute Catalog of Motion Pictures Produced in the United States, Part 1''. University of California Press, 1997.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0551424}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martan, Nita}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Colorado]]\n\n\n{{US-film-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nita_Martan"}
{"title_page": "Vinod Gupta", "text_new": "{{for|the Indian cricketer|Vinod Gupta (cricketer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Vinod Gupta\n| image        = Vinod Gupta with President Bill Clinton.jpg\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = Gupta and former U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]], 2014\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1946|7|4}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/14/us/politics/14gupta.html|title=Clinton's Backers Ties to Powerful Cut Both Ways|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Rampur Maniharan]], near [[Saharanpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  = \n| residence    = \n| nationality  = \n| education    = \n| occupation   = Businessman\n| salary       = \n| title        = \n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| party = [[Democratic party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| boards       = \n| spouse       = Laurel Gupta\n| children     = 3\n| parents      = \n| website      =\n| restingplace = \n| religion     = \n| ethnicity    = \n| alma mater   = [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]]<br> [[University of Nebraska]] {{small|([[Master of Science|MS]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])}}\n| known for    = \n| networth     = \n| relations    = \n}}\n\n'''Vinod Gupta''' (born July 4, 1946) is an Indian-born American businessman, investor, and philanthropist.  He is the former chief executive officer (CEO) and chairman of infoGROUP (previously known as infoUSA).<ref>[https://archive.is/20120708003616/http://biz.yahoo.com/bw/080428/20080428005870.html?.v=1 ]</ref>  Gupta served as CEO of infoGROUP from the time of its incorporation in 1972 until September 1997, and again from August 1998 to August 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ostroy |first=Andy |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/08/21/business/NA-US-InfoGroup-Shake-up.php |title=The New York Times - Breaking News, World News & Multimedia |newspaper=[[International Herald Tribune]] |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>  Gupta has donated over $50 million to numerous philanthropic endeavors in the United States and India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://vingupta.com/|title=Welcome to World Education Foundation|work=World Education Foundation|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBorrowing $100 from a bank to get started, Gupta grew infoGroup from a one-man operation to a global employer of over 5,000 with annual revenues of over $750 million.<ref name=\"stonetemple.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stonetemple.com/infousas-pankaj-mathur-interviewed-by-eric-enge/|title=InfoUSA's Pankaj Mathur Interviewed by Eric Enge {{!}} Stone Temple|website=www.stonetemple.com|language=English|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>  Under Gupta's leadership, infoGROUP acquired over 45 companies.  InfoGroup was sold in July 2010 for $680 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/washingtonlife/docs/may2012/90|title=Washington Life Magazine - May 2012|work=issuu|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Gupta founded DatabaseUSA.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.databaseusa.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=22 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224000257/http://databaseusa.com/ |archivedate=24 February 2013 }}</ref>  Gupta later founded and/or acquired a number of businesses, including A to Z Databases, Express-Copy, [[Infofree|InfoFree]], JangoMail, LocatePlus, and LP Police, which are owned by the Everest Group, Gupta's family office and investment corporation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.everestusa.net/acquisitions|title=Acquisitions {{!}} Everest Group LLC|work=Everest Group LLC|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFormer United States President [[Bill Clinton]] praised Gupta's and infoGroup's dedication to public service in Clinton's book ''Giving'', which described the company as one that \"has made a concerted effort to hire people who were on welfare, as well as people who are disabled or who have to support themselves after getting out of unsafe domestic situations.\"<ref name=\"businesswire.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20070919005949/en/infoUSAs-Participation-Welfare-Work-Programs-Mentioned-Bill|title=infoUSA's Participation in Welfare to Work Programs Mentioned in Bill Clinton's New Book, Giving|website=www.businesswire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta noted that he was \"deeply honored by President Clinton's recognition of infoUSA's hiring programs,\" and that he was \"proud of ''info''USA's commitment to providing opportunities to our fellow citizens, helping them achieve financial independence and vocational success whether they are working their way off welfare or overcoming a disability.\"<ref name=\"businesswire.com\"/>\n\nPresident Clinton appointed Gupta to serve as a trustee of the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/20/us/politics/20clinton.html|title=In Charity and Politics, Clinton Donors Overlap|last=Becker|first=Don Van Natta Jr , Jo|date=2007-12-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-21|last2=Mcintire|first2=Mike|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kennedy-center.org/pages/about/BoardOfTrustees|title=Board of Trustees {{!}} The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Art|website=www.kennedy-center.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta was nominated (and confirmed) to serve as the United States Consul General to [[Bermuda]], as well as the United States ambassador to [[Fiji]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/finance/mktguideapps/personinfo/FromMktGuideIdPersonTearsheet.jhtml?passedMktGuideId%3D8704 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060428082352/http://www.forbes.com/finance/mktguideapps/personinfo/FromMktGuideIdPersonTearsheet.jhtml?passedMktGuideId=8704 |archivedate=28 April 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGupta was born in [[Rampur Maniharan]], a small town (village) near [[Saharanpur]] ([[Uttar Pradesh]]) located {{convert|100|mi|km}} north of [[New Delhi]] to the family of Dr. Giri Lal Gupta.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta \"'grew up with no electricity, no roads, no toilets, no TVs, no cars. I didn't know much of what was outside.'\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  After graduating from high school, Gupta applied to the [[Indian Institutes of Technology]] (IIT), and was [[List of Indian Institute of Technology, Kharagpur alumni|admitted]] to the [[IIT Kharagpur]] campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  He majored in agricultural engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, Gupta moved to the United States to pursue a master's degree.  He \"won a scholarship to the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska at Lincoln]], where he earned master's degrees in agricultural engineering and [[Master of Business Administration|business]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nGupta was awarded three honorary doctorate degrees from the Monterey Institute, the University of Nebraska, and IIT Kharagpur.  Gupta delivered the commencement address at IIT Kharagpur in 2006.\n\n==Early career==\nGupta [[List of University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln people|graduated]] from the University of Nebraska in 1971.  He was subsequently hired as a marketing research analyst with Commodore Corporation, a manufacturer of mobile homes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Commodore asked Gupta to gather a list of every mobile home dealer in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  After Gupta realized that most of the available sources were either outdated or incomplete, he ordered all available 4,800 Yellow Pages phone directories and set out to compile the list himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> \n \nWith the help of another employee, Gupta sorted the books by state.  Commodore told Gupta that he and the second employee could work on the project on their own time, and once they had completed it, the company would consider buying the list.  After Gupta completed the list, he gave Commodore two options: pay $9,000 for exclusive rights to the list, or receive it free of charge and allow Gupta and his partner to sell it to Commodore's competitors.  Balking at the $9,000 cost, Commodore chose the latter option.\n\n==InfoGroup==\nBorrowing $100 from a local Nebraska bank, Gupta invested the money in mailers he sent out to other mobile home manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB875059169319215500|title=ABI's Founder Gupta Hands Reins to Adviser|last=Journal|first=Jeffrey A. Tannenbaum Staff Reporter of The Wall Street|work=WSJ|access-date=2017-04-21|language=English}}</ref>  Within three weeks, Gupta received checks for $22,000 and orders for another $13,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta founded American Business Information (ABI) in 1972.<ref name=\"Tannenbaum\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB875059169319215500|title=ABI's Founder Gupta Hands Reins to Adviser|last=Tannenbaum|first=Jeffrey A.|date=1997-09-24|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2017-04-21|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nBy 1986, \"ABI had the entire Yellow Pages in its databases, ready to be accessed in any form that customers wanted.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBy 1994, the company had revenues of $75 million and was publicly traded on the NASDAQ exchange.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta had already amassed \"six million shares\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> and was \"worth over $100 million.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBy 1997, the company had 1,500 employees and revenues of $108 million.<ref name=\"Tannenbaum\"/>  ABI was valued at approximately $650 million, of which Gupta, who \"decided to step down as chief executive of the fast-growing company because he thinks it needs more professional management,\" owned 38% (or approximately $250 million).<ref name=\"Tannenbaum\"/>\n\nIn 1998, Gupta resumed his role as chief executive of ABI, and renamed the company infoUSA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://newsbreaks.infotoday.com/NewsBreaks/American-Business-Information-Has-a-New-Name-infoUSA-and-a-New-Web-Site-17920.asp|title=American Business Information Has a New Name infoUSA and a New Web Site|last=Hane|first=Paula J.|date=1998-08-17|access-date=2017-04-21|language=English}}</ref>\n\nOver the next 10 years, Gupta acquired over 45 companies and built infoUSA into a \"data-collection industry titan\"<ref name=\"Clintons' InfoUSA Ties Scrutinized\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=18958566|title=Clintons' InfoUSA Ties Scrutinized|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref> with annual revenues of over $750 million.<ref name=\"stonetemple.com\"/>  In 2008, Gupta renamed \"[d]atabase giant infoUSA . . . infoGroup to better reflect its global expansion . . . [and] offices and operations in the U.S., Australia, Canada, China, India, Singapore and the U.K.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://adage.com/article/btob/infousa-infogroup/271103/|title=InfoUSA changes name to infoGroup|access-date=2017-04-21|language=en}}</ref>  The company was sold in 2010 for $680 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/washingtonlife/docs/may2012/90|title=Washington Life Magazine - May 2012|work=issuu|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Charitable foundation==\nGupta has pledged to donate all of his wealth to charity,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_IN66TjlScsC&pg=PT30&lpg=PT30&dq=vinod+gupta+charity&source=bl&ots=ruBqgKm9Ap&sig=A--lFi9Pudpbw9NWR_j2wmJoVCA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjos-WNk7bTAhUK_IMKHTpLBKg4HhDoAQgiMAA#v=onepage&q=vinod%20gupta%20charity&f=false|title=The Game Changers: 20 extraordinary success stories of entrepreneurs from IIT Kharagpur|last=Modi|first=Yuvnesh|last2=Kumar|first2=Rahul|last3=Kothari|first3=Alok|date=2012-01-13|publisher=Random House India|isbn=9788184002843|language=en}}</ref> and has made access to quality education a primary focus of his charitable contributions.  \"Through his charitable foundation, Gupta has helped advance education across fields including: business, science, information technology, communications, intellectual property law and wildlife preservation.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://list.infousa.com/VinGuptaCharitable.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521003847/http://list.infousa.com/VinGuptaCharitable.htm |archivedate=21 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nGupta donated $1 million to establish the [[Rampur Maniharan|Ram Rati Gupta Polytechnic]], a women's polytechnic in his native town of [[Rampur Maniharan]], a small town near [[Saharanpur]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]] state.  The Polytechnic was inaugurated by former United States President [[Bill Clinton]].  The former President met with students from the polytechnic when he visited India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2014/07/18/photo-essay-bill-clinton-visits-india/|title=Photo Essay: Bill Clinton Visits India|last=Bhattacharya|first=Suryatapa|date=2014-07-18|website=WSJ|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>\n\nGupta donated $2 million to his alma mater, the Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur, to create the [[Vinod Gupta School of Management]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Basu |first=Somdatta |date=25 January 2008 |title=Alumnus donates $1 mn to IIT |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-01-25/kolkata/27751165_1_iit-kgp-iit-kharagpur-vinod-gupta-school |newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>  The institute now offers an [[MBA]] program to engineering graduates with 0 to 5 years of work experience.  After Gupta's contributions, IIT received an additional $2 million from other IIT alumni.\n\nGupta has also donated money for a new science block at his former village school, and provided buses for his village's girls' school.\n\nGupta most recently founded a law school under the IIT umbrella: the [[Rajiv Gandhi School of Intellectual Property Law]], which is ranked the second-best law school in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.careers360.com/colleges/ranking/2017|title=Top Law colleges in India 2017|last=www.careers360.com|website=www.law.careers360.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n \nIn the United States, Gupta has donated $2 million to establish a curriculum for small business management at the [[University of Nebraska]] at Lincoln.  He has also donated an additional $500,000 to set up a scholarship fund for minority students who want to enter its science or engineering schools.\n\nIn 2013, Gupta partnered with the [[United States Department of State]]'s Office of the Global Partnership Initiative and the [[George Washington University School of Business]] to establish the Benjamin Kane Gupta Fellows Program.<ref name=\"mediarelations.gwu.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://mediarelations.gwu.edu/entrepreneur-and-philanthropist-vinod-gupta-establishes-gw-fellowship-program-us-department-state|title=Entrepreneur and Philanthropist Vinod Gupta Establishes GW Fellowship Program at the U.S. Department of State in Memory of His Son {{!}} Office of Media Relations {{!}} The George Washington University|website=mediarelations.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>  The program is an \"elite national internship program for M.B.A. graduate students . . . located within the Department of State,\" which \"offer[s] fellows . . . the opportunity to learn how to build public-private partnership to enhance and strengthen U.S. foreign policy and development efforts.\"<ref name=\"mediarelations.gwu.edu\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Gupta donated $1 million to the [[George Washington University Law School]] to establish the Ben Gupta Endowed Fund for International Legal Education.<ref name=\"gwlawmagazine.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gwlawmagazine.com/archives/2014/fall/alumni-philanthropy-gratitude.html|title=Alumni & Philanthropy: With Gratitude {{!}} GW Law|website=www.gwlawmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>  The scholarship \"support[s] students from developing countries seeking JD or LLM degrees, and those pursuing educational opportunities at the Law School on a non-degree basis.\"<ref name=\"gwlawmagazine.com\"/>\n\n==Securities and Exchange Commission charges==\nIn 2010, Gupta was charged along with two other employees of InfoGroup for \"their roles in a scheme in which the CEO funneled illegal compensation to himself in the form of perks worth millions of dollars.\"  The SEC claimed Gupta used $9.5 million in corporate funds for personal gain and his \"lavish lifestyle.\"<ref name=\"SEC charges\">\n{{cite press release\n|url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press/2010/2010-39.htm\n|title=SEC Charges Former Executives in Illegal Scheme to Enrich CEO With Perks\n|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]\n|date=15 March 2010\n|accessdate=23 March 2013\n}}</ref> The three later settled with the SEC without admitting wrongdoing.  According to the SEC, Gupta paid $7.4 million in fines and penalties, and agreed to be barred from serving as an officer or director of a public company.<ref name=\"SEC charges\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footnoted.com/my-big-fat-deal/the-perks-that-ate-infogroup/ |title=Title unknown |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701085725/http://www.footnoted.com/my-big-fat-deal/the-perks-that-ate-infogroup/ |archivedate=1 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, InfoGroup sued Gupta for improperly recruiting its employees and accessing its computer secrets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/02/us-based-infogroup-sues-its-founder-and-ex-ceo-vinod-gupta/|title=US based Infogroup sues its Founder and Ex-CEO Vinod Gupta|date=20 February 2014|work=Bihar Prabha|agency=Indo-Asian News Service (IANS)|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Relationship with the Clintons ==\nGupta is \"a close ally of both Clintons,\"<ref name=\"Clintons' InfoUSA Ties Scrutinized\"/> and a \"major Democratic fundraiser\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/washingtonlife/docs/may2012/90|title=Washington Life Magazine - May 2012|work=issuu|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref> and \"[[Rainmaker (business)|rainmaker]].\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/14/us/politics/14gupta.html|title=Clinton Backer's Ties to Powerful Cut Both Ways|last=Mcintire|first=Mike|date=2007-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-21|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  He \"has a long history of giving and raising campaign money for the Clintons, and gave $1 million for the 2000 Millennium Celebration, a New Year's Party thrown by the Clintons.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Overby |first=Peter |date=13 February 2008 |title=Clintons' InfoUSA Ties scrutinized |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=18958566 |work=National Public Radio}}</ref>  Gupta later \"hired Bill Clinton as a consultant . . . one of two continuing business relationships [Clinton] has had since leaving office . . . worth $3.3 million,\"<ref name=\"Clintons' InfoUSA Ties Scrutinized\"/> through infoGroup, the company formerly \"owned by Vinod Gupta, a billionaire who has raised hundreds of thousands of dollars for the Clintons' campaigns and contributed $1 million to the Clinton Foundation.\"<ref name=\"Newsweek\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/bill-clintons-business-ties-face-scrutiny-87355|title=Bill Clinton's Business Ties Face Scrutiny|date=2008-01-26|work=Newsweek|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Bob Kerrey]], a former Senator from Nebraska, \"'Vin is shockingly social,' . . . 'One of his gifts is he can strike up a conversation with anybody, and does. I can see why he and President Clinton got along so well, because they're both sort of that way.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/14/us/politics/14gupta.html|title=Clinton Backer's Ties to Powerful Cut Both Ways|last=Mcintire|first=Mike|date=2007-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-20|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, Gupta praised Clinton's work for the company.  \"'He helps us meet some of the right people,' he told the ''Omaha World-Herald''.  'In many speeches, he has mentioned InfoUSA by name.'\"<ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\nBy spending money, Gupta networked into the power elites of Washington, New York and the Bay Area.  He brought in hundreds of millions of dollars in revenue through his contacts at Google, Microsoft, AOL, Cisco, the Democratic Party, eBay, and HP.  He has one of the largest rolodexes in the industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hillaryproject.com/index.php?%2Fen%2Fstory-details%2Fbill_clintons_business_ties_face_scrutiny%2F |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117002034/http://www.hillaryproject.com/index.php?%2Fen%2Fstory-details%2Fbill_clintons_business_ties_face_scrutiny%2F |archivedate=17 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGupta is married to Laurel Gupta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gwtoday.gwu.edu/memoriam-benjamin-gupta |title=In Memoriam: Benjamin Gupta &#124; GW Today &#124; The George Washington University |publisher=Gwtoday.gwu.edu |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>  He has three sons: Jess, Benjamin, and Alexander, with his first wife, Bonnie Gupta, and one stepson from his marriage to Laurel Gupta.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ferris |first=Sarah |url=http://blogs.gwhatchet.com/newsroom/tag/vinod-gupta/ |title=Vinod Gupta - Newsroom |website=Blogs.gwhatchet.com |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mediarelations.gwu.edu/entrepreneur-and-philanthropist-vinod-gupta-establishes-gw-fellowship-program-us-department-state |title=Entrepreneur and Philanthropist Vinod Gupta Establishes GW Fellowship Program at the U.S. Department of State in Memory of His Son &#124; Office of Media Relations &#124; The George Washington University |website=Mediarelations.gwu.edu |date=18 June 2013 |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://bengupta.org/tributes/view/general_colin_l._powell_letter/ |title=General Colin L. Powell Letter &#124; News &#124; Ben Gupta Living Memorial |website=Bengupta.org |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 2000s, Gupta's son Benjamin Kane Gupta was hired by the [[State Department]] as an intern during Hillary Clinton's term as Secretary of State.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanlibertyreport.com/articles/who-is-vinod-gupta/ |title=Who Is Vinod Gupta? &#124; |website=Americanlibertyreport.com |date=20 June 2014 |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>  Benjamin Gupta was 28 years old when he died due to complications resulting from an accidental \"acute mixed drug intoxication\" consisting of [[oxycodone]] and alcohol.<ref name=\"gwhatchetmix\">{{cite web|last=Anand |first=Priya |url=http://www.gwhatchet.com/2012/02/09/mix-of-drug-alcohol-led-to-death-of-law-student/ |title=Mix of drug, alcohol led to death of law student |publisher=The GW Hatchet |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>  At a memorial service attended by both Hillary and Bill Clinton, Hillary Clinton noted that Ben \"really showed us what a life well-lived would look like,\"<ref name=\"gwhatchetmix\"/> while Bill stated that \"some people live four times as long and don't do as much good.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bengupta.com/legacy |title=Legacy &#124; Ben Gupta Living Memorial |website=Bengupta.com |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gupta, Vinod}}\n[[Category:1940s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American businessmen of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:University of Nebraska alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Saharanpur district]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Indian cricketer|Vinod Gupta (cricketer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Vinod Gupta\n| image        = Vinod Gupta with President Bill Clinton.jpg\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = Gupta and former U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]], 2014\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1946|7|4}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/14/us/politics/14gupta.html|title=Clinton's Backers Ties to Powerful Cut Both Ways|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Rampur Maniharan]], near [[Saharanpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  = \n| residence    = \n| nationality  = \n| education    = \n| occupation   = Businessman\n| salary       = \n| title        = \n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| party = [[Democratic party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| boards       = \n| spouse       = Laurel Gupta\n| children     = 3\n| parents      = \n| website      =\n| restingplace = \n| religion     = \n| ethnicity    = \n| alma mater   = [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]]<br> [[University of Nebraska]] {{small|([[Master of Science|MS]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])}}\n| known for    = \n| networth     = \n| relations    = \n}}\n\n'''Vinod Gupta''' (born July 4, 1946) is an Indian-born American businessman, investor, and philanthropist.  He is the former chief executive officer (CEO) and chairman of infoGROUP (previously known as infoUSA).<ref>[https://archive.is/20120708003616/http://biz.yahoo.com/bw/080428/20080428005870.html?.v=1 ]</ref>  Gupta served as CEO of infoGROUP from the time of its incorporation in 1972 until September 1997, and again from August 1998 to August 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ostroy |first=Andy |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/08/21/business/NA-US-InfoGroup-Shake-up.php |title=The New York Times - Breaking News, World News & Multimedia |newspaper=[[International Herald Tribune]] |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>  Gupta has donated over $50 million to numerous philanthropic endeavors in the United States and India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://vingupta.com/|title=Welcome to World Education Foundation|work=World Education Foundation|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBorrowing $100 from a bank to get started, Gupta grew infoGroup from a one-man operation to a global employer of over 5,000 with annual revenues of over $750 million.<ref name=\"stonetemple.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stonetemple.com/infousas-pankaj-mathur-interviewed-by-eric-enge/|title=InfoUSA's Pankaj Mathur Interviewed by Eric Enge {{!}} Stone Temple|website=www.stonetemple.com|language=English|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>  Under Gupta's leadership, infoGROUP acquired over 45 companies.  InfoGroup was sold in July 2010 for $680 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/washingtonlife/docs/may2012/90|title=Washington Life Magazine - May 2012|work=issuu|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Gupta founded DatabaseUSA.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.databaseusa.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=22 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224000257/http://databaseusa.com/ |archivedate=24 February 2013 }}</ref>  Gupta later founded and/or acquired a number of businesses, including A to Z Databases, Express-Copy, [[Infofree|InfoFree]], JangoMail, LocatePlus, and LP Police, which are owned by the Everest Group, Gupta's family office and investment corporation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.everestusa.net/acquisitions|title=Acquisitions {{!}} Everest Group LLC|work=Everest Group LLC|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFormer United States President [[Bill Clinton]] praised Gupta's and infoGroup's dedication to public service in Clinton's book ''Giving'', which described the company as one that \"has made a concerted effort to hire people who were on welfare, as well as people who are disabled or who have to support themselves after getting out of unsafe domestic situations.\"<ref name=\"businesswire.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20070919005949/en/infoUSAs-Participation-Welfare-Work-Programs-Mentioned-Bill|title=infoUSA's Participation in Welfare to Work Programs Mentioned in Bill Clinton's New Book, Giving|website=www.businesswire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta noted that he was \"deeply honored by President Clinton's recognition of infoUSA's hiring programs,\" and that he was \"proud of ''info''USA's commitment to providing opportunities to our fellow citizens, helping them achieve financial independence and vocational success whether they are working their way off welfare or overcoming a disability.\"<ref name=\"businesswire.com\"/>\n\nPresident Clinton appointed Gupta to serve as a trustee of the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/20/us/politics/20clinton.html|title=In Charity and Politics, Clinton Donors Overlap|last=Becker|first=Don Van Natta Jr , Jo|date=2007-12-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-21|last2=Mcintire|first2=Mike|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kennedy-center.org/pages/about/BoardOfTrustees|title=Board of Trustees {{!}} The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Art|website=www.kennedy-center.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta was nominated (and confirmed) to serve as the United States Consul General to [[Bermuda]], as well as the United States ambassador to [[Fiji]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/finance/mktguideapps/personinfo/FromMktGuideIdPersonTearsheet.jhtml?passedMktGuideId%3D8704 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060428082352/http://www.forbes.com/finance/mktguideapps/personinfo/FromMktGuideIdPersonTearsheet.jhtml?passedMktGuideId=8704 |archivedate=28 April 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGupta was born in [[Rampur Maniharan]], a small town (village) near [[Saharanpur]] ([[Uttar Pradesh]]) located {{convert|100|mi|km}} north of [[New Delhi]] to the family of Dr. Giri Lal Gupta.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta \"'grew up with no electricity, no roads, no toilets, no TVs, no cars. I didn't know much of what was outside.'\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  After graduating from high school, Gupta applied to the [[Indian Institutes of Technology]] (IIT), and was [[List of Indian Institute of Technology, Kharagpur alumni|admitted]] to the [[IIT Kharagpur]] campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  He majored in agricultural engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, Gupta moved to the United States to pursue a master's degree.  He \"won a scholarship to the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska at Lincoln]], where he earned master's degrees in agricultural engineering and [[Master of Business Administration|business]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nGupta was awarded three honorary doctorate degrees from the Monterey Institute, the University of Nebraska, and IIT Kharagpur.  Gupta delivered the commencement address at IIT Kharagpur in 2006.\n\n==Early career==\nGupta [[List of University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln people|graduated]] from the University of Nebraska in 1971.  He was subsequently hired as a marketing research analyst with Commodore Corporation, a manufacturer of mobile homes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Commodore asked Gupta to gather a list of every mobile home dealer in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  After Gupta realized that most of the available sources were either outdated or incomplete, he ordered all available 4,800 Yellow Pages phone directories and set out to compile the list himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> \n \nWith the help of another employee, Gupta sorted the books by state.  Commodore told Gupta that he and the second employee could work on the project on their own time, and once they had completed it, the company would consider buying the list.  After Gupta completed the list, he gave Commodore two options: pay $9,000 for exclusive rights to the list, or receive it free of charge and allow Gupta and his partner to sell it to Commodore's competitors.  Balking at the $9,000 cost, Commodore chose the latter option.\n\n==InfoGroup==\nBorrowing $100 from a local Nebraska bank, Gupta invested the money in mailers he sent out to other mobile home manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB875059169319215500|title=ABI's Founder Gupta Hands Reins to Adviser|last=Journal|first=Jeffrey A. Tannenbaum Staff Reporter of The Wall Street|work=WSJ|access-date=2017-04-21|language=English}}</ref>  Within three weeks, Gupta received checks for $22,000 and orders for another $13,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta founded American Business Information (ABI) in 1972.<ref name=\"Tannenbaum\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB875059169319215500|title=ABI's Founder Gupta Hands Reins to Adviser|last=Tannenbaum|first=Jeffrey A.|date=1997-09-24|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2017-04-21|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nBy 1986, \"ABI had the entire Yellow Pages in its databases, ready to be accessed in any form that customers wanted.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBy 1994, the company had revenues of $75 million and was publicly traded on the NASDAQ exchange.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>  Gupta had already amassed \"six million shares\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> and was \"worth over $100 million.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1995/02/06/201835/index.htm|title=BUILDING A FORTUNE ON FREE DATA VINOD GUPTA IS A MULTIMILLIONAIRE BECAUSE HE SELLS THE INFORMATION THAT OTHER ENTREPRENEURS NEED TO STAY IN BUSINESS. - February 6, 1995|website=archive.fortune.com|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBy 1997, the company had 1,500 employees and revenues of $108 million.<ref name=\"Tannenbaum\"/>  ABI was valued at approximately $650 million, of which Gupta, who \"decided to step down as chief executive of the fast-growing company because he thinks it needs more professional management,\" owned 38% (or approximately $250 million).<ref name=\"Tannenbaum\"/>\n\nIn 1998, Gupta resumed his role as chief executive of ABI, and renamed the company infoUSA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://newsbreaks.infotoday.com/NewsBreaks/American-Business-Information-Has-a-New-Name-infoUSA-and-a-New-Web-Site-17920.asp|title=American Business Information Has a New Name infoUSA and a New Web Site|last=Hane|first=Paula J.|date=1998-08-17|access-date=2017-04-21|language=English}}</ref>\n\nOver the next 10 years, Gupta acquired over 45 companies and built infoUSA into a \"data-collection industry titan\"<ref name=\"Clintons' InfoUSA Ties Scrutinized\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=18958566|title=Clintons' InfoUSA Ties Scrutinized|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref> with annual revenues of over $750 million.<ref name=\"stonetemple.com\"/>  In 2008, Gupta renamed \"[d]atabase giant infoUSA . . . infoGroup to better reflect its global expansion . . . [and] offices and operations in the U.S., Australia, Canada, China, India, Singapore and the U.K.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://adage.com/article/btob/infousa-infogroup/271103/|title=InfoUSA changes name to infoGroup|access-date=2017-04-21|language=en}}</ref>  The company was sold in 2010 for $680 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/washingtonlife/docs/may2012/90|title=Washington Life Magazine - May 2012|work=issuu|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Charitable foundation==\nGupta has pledged to donate all of his wealth to charity,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_IN66TjlScsC&pg=PT30&lpg=PT30&dq=vinod+gupta+charity&source=bl&ots=ruBqgKm9Ap&sig=A--lFi9Pudpbw9NWR_j2wmJoVCA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjos-WNk7bTAhUK_IMKHTpLBKg4HhDoAQgiMAA#v=onepage&q=vinod%20gupta%20charity&f=false|title=The Game Changers: 20 extraordinary success stories of entrepreneurs from IIT Kharagpur|last=Modi|first=Yuvnesh|last2=Kumar|first2=Rahul|last3=Kothari|first3=Alok|date=2012-01-13|publisher=Random House India|isbn=9788184002843|language=en}}</ref> and has made access to quality education a primary focus of his charitable contributions.  \"Through his charitable foundation, Gupta has helped advance education across fields including: business, science, information technology, communications, intellectual property law and wildlife preservation.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://list.infousa.com/VinGuptaCharitable.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521003847/http://list.infousa.com/VinGuptaCharitable.htm |archivedate=21 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nGupta donated $1 million to establish the [[Rampur Maniharan|Ram Rati Gupta Polytechnic]], a women's polytechnic in his native town of [[Rampur Maniharan]], a small town near [[Saharanpur]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]] state.  The Polytechnic was inaugurated by former United States President [[Bill Clinton]].  The former President met with students from the polytechnic when he visited India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2014/07/18/photo-essay-bill-clinton-visits-india/|title=Photo Essay: Bill Clinton Visits India|last=Bhattacharya|first=Suryatapa|date=2014-07-18|website=WSJ|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>\n\nGupta donated $2 million to his alma mater, the Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur, to create the [[Vinod Gupta School of Management]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Basu |first=Somdatta |date=25 January 2008 |title=Alumnus donates $1 mn to IIT |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-01-25/kolkata/27751165_1_iit-kgp-iit-kharagpur-vinod-gupta-school |newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>  The institute now offers an [[MBA]] program to engineering graduates with 0 to 5 years of work experience.  After Gupta's contributions, IIT received an additional $2 million from other IIT alumni.\n\nGupta has also donated money for a new science block at his former village school, and provided buses for his village's girls' school.\n\nGupta most recently founded a law school under the IIT umbrella: the [[Rajiv Gandhi School of Intellectual Property Law]], which is ranked the second-best law school in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.careers360.com/colleges/ranking/2017|title=Top Law colleges in India 2017|last=www.careers360.com|website=www.law.careers360.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>\n \nIn the United States, Gupta has donated $2 million to establish a curriculum for small business management at the [[University of Nebraska]] at Lincoln.  He has also donated an additional $500,000 to set up a scholarship fund for minority students who want to enter its science or engineering schools.\n\nIn 2013, Gupta partnered with the [[United States Department of State]]'s Office of the Global Partnership Initiative and the [[George Washington University School of Business]] to establish the Benjamin Kane Gupta Fellows Program.<ref name=\"mediarelations.gwu.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://mediarelations.gwu.edu/entrepreneur-and-philanthropist-vinod-gupta-establishes-gw-fellowship-program-us-department-state|title=Entrepreneur and Philanthropist Vinod Gupta Establishes GW Fellowship Program at the U.S. Department of State in Memory of His Son {{!}} Office of Media Relations {{!}} The George Washington University|website=mediarelations.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>  The program is an \"elite national internship program for M.B.A. graduate students . . . located within the Department of State,\" which \"offer[s] fellows . . . the opportunity to learn how to build public-private partnership to enhance and strengthen U.S. foreign policy and development efforts.\"<ref name=\"mediarelations.gwu.edu\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Gupta donated $1 million to the [[George Washington University Law School]] to establish the Ben Gupta Endowed Fund for International Legal Education.<ref name=\"gwlawmagazine.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gwlawmagazine.com/archives/2014/fall/alumni-philanthropy-gratitude.html|title=Alumni & Philanthropy: With Gratitude {{!}} GW Law|website=www.gwlawmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref>  The scholarship \"support[s] students from developing countries seeking JD or LLM degrees, and those pursuing educational opportunities at the Law School on a non-degree basis.\"<ref name=\"gwlawmagazine.com\"/>\n\n==Securities and Exchange Commission charges==\nIn 2010, Gupta was charged along with two other employees of InfoGroup for \"their roles in a scheme in which the CEO funneled illegal compensation to himself in the form of perks worth millions of dollars.\"  The SEC claimed Gupta used $9.5 million in corporate funds for personal gain and his \"lavish lifestyle.\"<ref name=\"SEC charges\">\n{{cite press release\n|url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press/2010/2010-39.htm\n|title=SEC Charges Former Executives in Illegal Scheme to Enrich CEO With Perks\n|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]\n|date=15 March 2010\n|accessdate=23 March 2013\n}}</ref> The three later settled with the SEC without admitting wrongdoing.  According to the SEC, Gupta paid $7.4 million in fines and penalties, and agreed to be barred from serving as an officer or director of a public company.<ref name=\"SEC charges\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footnoted.com/my-big-fat-deal/the-perks-that-ate-infogroup/ |title=Title unknown |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701085725/http://www.footnoted.com/my-big-fat-deal/the-perks-that-ate-infogroup/ |archivedate=1 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, InfoGroup sued Gupta for improperly recruiting its employees and accessing its computer secrets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/02/us-based-infogroup-sues-its-founder-and-ex-ceo-vinod-gupta/|title=US based Infogroup sues its Founder and Ex-CEO Vinod Gupta|date=20 February 2014|work=Bihar Prabha|agency=Indo-Asian News Service (IANS)|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Relationship with the Clintons ==\nGupta is \"a close ally of both Clintons,\"<ref name=\"Clintons' InfoUSA Ties Scrutinized\"/> and a \"major Democratic fundraiser\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/washingtonlife/docs/may2012/90|title=Washington Life Magazine - May 2012|work=issuu|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref> and \"[[Rainmaker (business)|rainmaker]].\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/14/us/politics/14gupta.html|title=Clinton Backer's Ties to Powerful Cut Both Ways|last=Mcintire|first=Mike|date=2007-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-21|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  He \"has a long history of giving and raising campaign money for the Clintons, and gave $1 million for the 2000 Millennium Celebration, a New Year's Party thrown by the Clintons.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Overby |first=Peter |date=13 February 2008 |title=Clintons' InfoUSA Ties scrutinized |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=18958566 |work=National Public Radio}}</ref>  Gupta later \"hired Bill Clinton as a consultant . . . one of two continuing business relationships [Clinton] has had since leaving office . . . worth $3.3 million,\"<ref name=\"Clintons' InfoUSA Ties Scrutinized\"/> through infoGroup, the company formerly \"owned by Vinod Gupta, a billionaire who has raised hundreds of thousands of dollars for the Clintons' campaigns and contributed $1 million to the Clinton Foundation.\"<ref name=\"Newsweek\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/bill-clintons-business-ties-face-scrutiny-87355|title=Bill Clinton's Business Ties Face Scrutiny|date=2008-01-26|work=Newsweek|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Bob Kerrey]], a former Senator from Nebraska, \"'Vin is shockingly social,' . . . 'One of his gifts is he can strike up a conversation with anybody, and does. I can see why he and President Clinton got along so well, because they're both sort of that way.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/14/us/politics/14gupta.html|title=Clinton Backer's Ties to Powerful Cut Both Ways|last=Mcintire|first=Mike|date=2007-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-20|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, Gupta praised Clinton's work for the company.  \"'He helps us meet some of the right people,' he told the ''Omaha World-Herald''.  'In many speeches, he has mentioned InfoUSA by name.'\"<ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\nBy spending money, Gupta networked into the power elites of Washington, New York and the Bay Area.  He brought in hundreds of millions of dollars in revenue through his contacts at Google, Microsoft, AOL, Cisco, the Democratic Party, eBay, and HP.  He has one of the largest rolodexes in the industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hillaryproject.com/index.php?%2Fen%2Fstory-details%2Fbill_clintons_business_ties_face_scrutiny%2F |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117002034/http://www.hillaryproject.com/index.php?%2Fen%2Fstory-details%2Fbill_clintons_business_ties_face_scrutiny%2F |archivedate=17 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGupta is married to Laurel Gupta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gwtoday.gwu.edu/memoriam-benjamin-gupta |title=In Memoriam: Benjamin Gupta &#124; GW Today &#124; The George Washington University |publisher=Gwtoday.gwu.edu |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>  He has three sons: Jess, Benjamin, and Alexander, with his first wife, Bonnie Gupta, and one stepson from his marriage to Laurel Gupta.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ferris |first=Sarah |url=http://blogs.gwhatchet.com/newsroom/tag/vinod-gupta/ |title=Vinod Gupta - Newsroom |website=Blogs.gwhatchet.com |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mediarelations.gwu.edu/entrepreneur-and-philanthropist-vinod-gupta-establishes-gw-fellowship-program-us-department-state |title=Entrepreneur and Philanthropist Vinod Gupta Establishes GW Fellowship Program at the U.S. Department of State in Memory of His Son &#124; Office of Media Relations &#124; The George Washington University |website=Mediarelations.gwu.edu |date=18 June 2013 |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://bengupta.org/tributes/view/general_colin_l._powell_letter/ |title=General Colin L. Powell Letter &#124; News &#124; Ben Gupta Living Memorial |website=Bengupta.org |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 2000s, Gupta's son Benjamin Kane Gupta was hired by the [[State Department]] as an intern during Hillary Clinton's term as Secretary of State.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanlibertyreport.com/articles/who-is-vinod-gupta/ |title=Who Is Vinod Gupta? &#124; |website=Americanlibertyreport.com |date=20 June 2014 |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>  Benjamin Gupta was 28 years old when he died due to complications resulting from an accidental \"acute mixed drug intoxication\" consisting of [[oxycodone]] and alcohol.<ref name=\"gwhatchetmix\">{{cite web|last=Anand |first=Priya |url=http://www.gwhatchet.com/2012/02/09/mix-of-drug-alcohol-led-to-death-of-law-student/ |title=Mix of drug, alcohol led to death of law student |publisher=The GW Hatchet |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>  At a memorial service attended by both Hillary and Bill Clinton, Hillary Clinton noted that Ben \"really showed us what a life well-lived would look like,\"<ref name=\"gwhatchetmix\"/> while Bill stated that \"some people live four times as long and don't do as much good.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bengupta.com/legacy |title=Legacy &#124; Ben Gupta Living Memorial |website=Bengupta.com |date= |accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Wikiquote]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gupta, Vinod}}\n[[Category:1940s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American businessmen of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:University of Nebraska alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Saharanpur district]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Vilho-Veli", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vinod_Gupta"}
{"title_page": "Dean (given name)", "text_new": "'''Dean''' is an English masculine given name and middle name with several origins:\n* Derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] word \"\u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2\" (\"dekanos\"), which means \"monk or dignitary in charge of ten others\", see also [[Dean (Christianity)]]\n* Derived from the English surname [[Dean (surname)|Dean]], from an [[Old English|Anglo-Saxon]] word meaning \"valley\"\n* An Anglicization of the [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] noun [[Din (Hebrew)|\u05d3\u05d9\u05df]], meaning Law or Justice.\n\n==People==\n* [[Dean Acheson]] (1893\u20131971), American statesman and lawyer\n* [[Dean Cain]] (born 1966), American actor\n* [[Dean Caliguire]] (born 1967), American football player\n* [[Dean Callaway]], Australian rugby league footballer\n* [[Dean Cameron]], (born 1962) American actor, musician, and comedian\n* [[Deen Castronovo]], (born 1964) American rock drummer\n* [[Dean Chance]], American baseball player\n* [[Dean Cokinos]], American football coach\n* [[Dean Delannoit]], Belgian pop singer\n* [[Dean Deleo]] (born 1961), American rock musician\n* [[Dean Fertita]], American rock musician\n* [[Dean Fisher]] (born 1956), American politician\n* [[Dean Fujioka]], Japanese actor, musician, and model\n* [[Dean Fuleihan]], American civil servant\n* [[Dean Furman]] (born 1988), South African footballer \n* [[Dean Geyer]], Australian singer/actor\n* [[Dean Griffiths]], Jamaican hurdler\n* [[Dean Hart]] (1954\u20131990), Canadian wrestler\n* [[Dean Heller]], American politician\n* [[Dean Henderson]] (born 1997), English footballer \n* [[Dean Kamen]], inventor of Segway PT and founder of FIRST\n* [[Dean Kashiwagi]], professor and creator of the Kashiwagi Solution Model  \n* [[Dean Koontz]], American author\n* [[Dean Kremer]] (born 1996), Israeli-American baseball player\n* [[Dean Lewis]] (born 1989), Australian singer-songwriter\n* [[Dean Lukin]], Australian weightlifter\n*[[Dean Macpherson]] (born 1985), South African politician\n* [[Dean Malenko]] (born 1960), ring name of American wrestler Dean Simon\n* [[Dean Martin]] (1917\u20131995), American entertainer\n* [[Dean McAdams]] (1917\u20131996), American football player\n* [[Dean McDermott]], Canadian actor\n* [[Dean Northover]] (born 1991), Canadian football player\n* [[Dean O'Gorman]], New Zealand actor\n* [[Dean Obeidallah]], American comedian\n* [[Dean Palmer]], American baseball player\n* [[Dean Pelman]], American-Israeli baseball player\n* [[Dean Philpott]] (born 1935), American football player\n* [[Dean Reed]] (1938-1986), American singer in East Germany\n* [[Dean Rusk]] (1909\u20131994), U.S. Secretary of State\n* [[Dean Schofield]] (born 1979), English rugby player\n* [[Dean Smith]] (1931-2015), American basketball coach\n* [[Dean Stoecker]] (born 1956/1957), American billionaire, co-founder of Alteryx\n* Dean Torrence (born 1940), American musician, half of rock n' roll duo [[Jan and Dean]]\n* [[Dean Wade]] (born 1996), American basketball player\n* [[Dean Wareham]], New Zealand-American musician\n* [[Dean Ween]], American guitarist, Ween\n* [[Dean Whare]] (born 1990), New Zealand rugby player\n* [[Dean Winters]] (born 1964), American actor\n* [[Dean Calvin York]] (born 1954), American Speedway Motorcycle and Motocross Racer \n* [[Dean Zelinsky]], American guitar luthier\n\n===People with it as a middle name===\n* [[Richard Dean Anderson]], American actor\n* [[James Dean Bradfield]], lead singer of the Manic Street Preachers\n* [[Alan Dean Foster]], science fiction writer\n* [[William Dean Howells]], American writer\n* [[Jeffrey Dean Morgan]], an American actor\n* [[Greg Dean Schmitz]], film journalist\n* [[Harry Dean Stanton]], American actor\n\n===People with it as a stage names===\n* [[Dean Ambrose]] (born 1985), ring name of American professional wrestler Jonathan Good\n* [[Dean (South Korean singer)|Dean]], stage name of South Korean R&B singer-songwriter, rapper and record producer Kwon Hyuk ( Korean : \uad8c\ud601)\n\n==Fictional characters==\n* [[Dean Moriarty]], character in Jack Kerouac's [[On the Road]]\n* [[Dean Winchester]], character on the show ''Supernatural''\n* [[Dean Walton]], a fictional character in ''Degrassi: The Next Generation''\n* [[Dean Venture]], character on the show ''The Venture Bros.''\n* [[Dean Thomas (Harry Potter)|Dean Thomas]], a fictional character in the ''Harry Potter'' series\n* [[Dean Forester]], character on the show ''Gilmore Girls''\n* Dean Domino, a character in the 2010 game [[Fallout: New Vegas#Dead Money|Fallout: New Vegas: Dead Money]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dean (surname)]]\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:Given names originating from a surname]]\n", "text_old": "'''Dean''' is an English masculine given name and middle name with several origins:\n* Derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] word \"\u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2\" (\"dekanos\"), which means \"monk or dignitary in charge of ten others\", see also [[Dean (Christianity)]]\n* Derived from the English surname [[Dean (surname)|Dean]], from an [[Old English|Anglo-Saxon]] word meaning \"valley\"\n* An Anglicization of the [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] noun [[Din (Hebrew)|\u05d3\u05d9\u05df]], meaning Law or Justice.\n\n==People==\n* [[Dean Acheson]] (1893\u20131971), American statesman and lawyer\n* [[Dean Cain]] (born 1966), American actor\n* [[Dean Caliguire]] (born 1967), American football player\n* [[Dean Callaway]], Australian rugby league footballer\n* [[Dean Cameron]], (born 1962) American actor, musician, and comedian\n* [[Deen Castronovo]], (born 1964) American rock drummer\n* [[Dean Chance]], American baseball player\n* [[Dean Cokinos]], American football coach\n* [[Dean Delannoit]], Belgian pop singer\n* [[Dean Fertita]], American rock musician\n* [[Dean Fisher]] (born 1956), American politician\n* [[Dean Fujioka]], Japanese actor, musician, and model\n* [[Dean Fuleihan]], American civil servant\n* [[Dean Furman]] (born 1988), South Afric