 as a middle name===\n* [[Richard Dean Anderson]], American actor\n* [[James Dean Bradfield]], lead singer of the Manic Street Preachers\n* [[Alan Dean Foster]], science fiction writer\n* [[William Dean Howells]], American writer\n* [[Jeffrey Dean Morgan]], an American actor\n* [[Greg Dean Schmitz]], film journalist\n* [[Harry Dean Stanton]], American actor\n\n===People with it as a stage names===\n* [[Dean Ambrose]] (born 1985), ring name of American professional wrestler Jonathan Good\n* [[Dean (South Korean singer)|Dean]], stage name of South Korean R&B singer-songwriter, rapper and record producer Kwon Hyuk ( Korean : \uad8c\ud601)\n\n==Fictional characters==\n* [[Dean Moriarty]], character in Jack Kerouac's [[On the Road]]\n* [[Dean Winchester]], character on the show ''Supernatural''\n* [[Dean Walton]], a fictional character in ''Degrassi: The Next Generation''\n* [[Dean Venture]], character on the show ''The Venture Bros.''\n* [[Dean Thomas (Harry Potter)|Dean Thomas]], a fictional character in the ''Harry Potter'' series\n* [[Dean Forester]], character on the show ''Gilmore Girls''\n* Dean Domino, a character in the 2010 game [[Fallout: New Vegas#Dead Money|Fallout: New Vegas: Dead Money]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dean (surname)]]\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:Given names originating from a surname]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8805:cc00:9e:2d87:cb78:cb10:fe2d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePeople)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dean_(given_name)"}
{"title_page": "China\u2013North Korea border", "text_new": "{{Infobox\n| title  = China\u2013North Korea border\n| image  = [[File:Border stone china-corea.jpg|frameless]]\n| caption = Inscription stone marking the border of China and North Korea in [[Jilin]]\n| data1  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n| order = st\n| s      = \u4e2d\u671d\u8fb9\u5883\n| t      = \u4e2d\u671d\u908a\u5883\n| p      = Zh\u014dng\u2013Ch\u00e1o Bi\u0101nj\u00ecng}}\n| data2  = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes|context=north\n| hangul = \uc870\uc120\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc8fc\uc758\uc778\ubbfc\uacf5\ud654\uad6d-\uc911\ud654\uc778\ubbfc\uacf5\ud654\uad6d \uad6d\uacbd\n| hanja  = \u671d\u9bae\u6c11\u4e3b\u4e3b\u7fa9\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u00b7\u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b \u570b\u5883\n| mr     = Chos\u014fn Minjuju\u016di Inmin Konghwaguk\u119e \u2013 Chunghwa Inmin Konghwaguk Kukky\u014fng\n| rr     = Joseon Minjujuui Inmin Gonghwaguk \u2013 Junghwa Inmin Gonghwaguk Gukgyeong}}\n}}\n\nThe '''China\u2013North Korea border''' is the international border separating the People's Republic of [[China]] (PRC) and the [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]] (North Korea).\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:SinoKorea Friendship Bridge.jpg|thumb|[[Sino-Korean Friendship Bridge]] (right), linking [[Dandong]] with North Korea]]\nThe border is {{convert|880|mi|km|disp=flip}} long.<ref name=Onishi>Onishi, Norimitsu. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/22/weekinreview/22marsh.html?_r=0 Tension, Desperation: The China-North Korean Border].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. October 22, 2006. Retrieved on October 23, 2012.</ref> From west to east, the [[Yalu River]],<ref name=Kanto>Kanto, Dick K. and Mark E. Manyin. [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/R41043.pdf China-North Korea Relations], Congressional Research Service (December 28, 2010).</ref> [[Paektu Mountain]], and the [[Tumen River]] divides the two countries.\n\n[[Dandong]], in the [[Liaoning]] Province of China, on the [[Yalu River]] delta, is the largest city on the border.<ref>Rogers, Jenny. \"[http://www.goldcoast.com.au/article/2012/10/02/439048_gold-coast-business.html New group reaches out to China].\" ''[[Gold Coast Bulletin]]''. October 2, 2012. Retrieved on October 23, 2012.</ref> On the other side of the river is the city of [[Sinuiju]] in [[North Pyongan Province]], North Korea. The two cities are situated on the Amnok river delta at the western end of the border, near the [[Yellow Sea]]. Their waterfronts face each other and are connected by the [[Sino-Korean Friendship Bridge]].\n\nThere are 205 islands on the Amnok River. A 1962 border treaty between North Korea and China split the islands according to which ethnic group were living on each island. North Korea possesses 127 and China 78. Due to the division criteria, some islands such as [[Hwanggumpyong Island]] belong to North Korea even though they are on the Chinese side of the river. Both countries have navigation rights on the river, including in the delta.\n\nThe source of the Amnok River is [[Heaven Lake]] on [[Paektu Mountain]], which is considered the birthplace of the Korean and [[Manchu people]]s. This lake is also the source of the [[Tumen River]] which forms the eastern portion of the border.\n\nThere are a significant number of ethnic Koreans in Northeast China, particularly in the [[Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture]].\n\n==Trade and contact==\n[[File:Beijing to Pyongyang train.jpg| thumb|The Beijing\u2013Pyongyang passenger train passes Dandong]]\nIts border with China has been described as North Korea's \"lifeline to the outside world.\"<ref name=Onishi/> Much of the China-North Korea trade goes through the port of Dandong.<ref name=Kanto/>\n\nChinese cell phone service has been known to extend as far as {{convert|10|km|abbr=on|0}} into Korean territory, which has led to the development of a black market for Chinese cell phones in the border regions. International calls are strictly forbidden in North Korea, and violators put themselves at considerable peril to acquire such phones.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20445632 North Korea: On the net in world's most secretive nation (BBC)]</ref>\n\nTourists in Dandong can take speedboat rides along the North Korean side of the Amnok River and up its tributaries.<ref>{{cite new|title=A trip to the North Korea-China border, in photos|url=https://www.nknews.org/2015/05/a-trip-to-the-north-korea-china-border-in-photos/|publisher=NK News|date=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nA common wedding day event for many Chinese couples involve renting boats, putting [[Personal flotation device|life preserver]]s on over their wedding clothes, and going to the North Korean border to have wedding photos taken.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hessler|first=Peter|title=Oracle Bones|url=https://archive.org/details/oraclebonesjourn00hess_0|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=Harper Perennial|location=New York et al.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/oraclebonesjourn00hess_0/page/62 62]}}</ref>\n\nMemory cards and teddy bears are reportedly among the most popular items for North Koreans shopping in Dandong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/article/thanks-memory-cards-north-koreans-return-china/|title=Thanks for the memory cards; North Koreans return from China|last=Reuters|first=|date=4 December 2016|website=www.atimes.com|publisher=|access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Crossings==\n[[File:Jian friendship bridge 2011 07 24.jpg|thumb|The Ji'an Railway Bridge between [[Ji'an, Jilin|Ji'an]], [[Jilin]] Province and [[Manpo]], [[Chagang Province]] of North Korea.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=6| China-North Korea Border Crossings\n|-\n! Name\n! style=\"width: 20%| Bordering<br />Chinese town\n! style=\"width: 20%| Bordering<br />Korean town\n! Open to<br />[[third country national|third<br />country<br />nationals]]\n! style=\"width: 5%| Railway crossing\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Hwanggumpyong Island]]|| [[Tangchi, Dandong|Tangchi]],<br />[[Zhenxing District|Zhenxing]], [[Dandong]]|| [[Sindo County|Sindo]],<br /> [[North Pyongan Province]]|| No|| No|| Planned\n|-\n| [[New Yalu River Bridge]]|| Tangchi,<br />Zhenxing, Dandong|| [[Sinuiju]],<br />North Pyongan|| Yes|| No|| Under construction\n|-\n| [[Yalu River Broken Bridge]]|| Tangchi,<br />Zhenxing, Dandong|| Sinuiju,<br />North Pyongan|| No|| No|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Sino-Korean Friendship Bridge]]|| Tangchi,<br />Zhenxing, Dandong|| Sinuiju,<br />North Pyongan|| Yes|| Yes|| Opened{{efn|There are four weekly trains with hard and soft sleepers from Beijing to [[Pyongyang]] via the Sino\u2013Korean Friendship Bridge, as well as a weekly carriage attached to the Vladivostok train from Moscow, via Harbin, Shenyang, and Dandong.<ref name=TransSiberian>[https://archive.is/20140527173015/http://www.koreakonsult.com/transsiberian_eng.html \"Trans-Siberian Railway Tours\"] Accessed 2014-05-25</ref>}} \n|-\n| [[Yalu River Broken Wooden Pontoon]]|| [[Zhenzhu Subdistrict]],<br />[[Zhen'an District|Zhen'an]], Dandong|| Sinuiju,<br />North Pyongan|| No|| Yes|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Hekou Broken Bridge]]|| [[Changdian]],<br />[[Kuandian Manchu Autonomous County|Kuandian]], Dandong|| [[Sakchu County]],<br />North Pyongan|| No|| No|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Upper Hekou Railway Bridge]]|| Changdian,<br />Kuandian, Dandong|| Sakju,<br />North Pyongan|| No|| Yes|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Ji'an Yalu River Border Railway Bridge|Ji'an Railway Bridge]]|| [[Ji'an, Jilin|Ji'an City]],<br />[[Tonghua]]|| [[Manpo]],<br />[[Chagang Province|Chagang]]|| No|| Yes|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Ji'an Yalu River Road Bridge|Ji'an Road Bridge]]|| Ji'an City,<br />Tonghua|| Manpo,<br />Chagang|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Chagang Samgang Station|Chagang Samgang Railway Bridge]]|| [[Yunfeng Lake]],<br />Ji'an, Tonghua|| Manpo,<br />Chagang|| No|| Yes|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Kuunbong Station|Kuunbong Railway Bridge]]|| Yunfeng Lake,<br />Ji'an, Tonghua|| [[Chasong County|Chasong]],<br />Chagang|| No|| Yes|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Linjiang Yalu River Bridge]]|| [[Linjiang]] City,<br />[[Baishan]]|| [[Chunggang County|Chunggang]],<br />Chagang|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Changbai\u2013Hyesan International Bridge|Changbai-Hyesan Bridge]]|| [[Changbai Korean Autonomous County|Changbai]],<br />Baishan|| [[Hyesan]],<br />[[Ryanggang Province]]|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Karim Bridge]]|| [[Ershidaogou]],<br />Changbai, Baishan|| [[Pochon County|Pochon]],<br />Ryanggang|| No|| No|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Samjiyon crossing]]|| [[Erdaobaihe]],<br />[[Antu County|Antu]], [[Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture|Yanbian]]|| [[Samjiyon]],<br />Ryanggang|| No|| No|| Near [[Paektu Mountain]]\n|-\n| [[Guchengli Bridge]]|| [[Chongshan]],<br />[[Helong]], Yanbian|| [[Taehongdan County|Taehongdan]],<br />Ryanggang|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Nanping Bridge]]|| [[Nanping, Helong|Nanping]],<br />Helong, Yanbian|| [[Musan County|Musan]],<br />[[North Hamgyong Province|North Hamgyong]]|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Sanhe Bridge]]|| [[Sanhe, Longjing|Sanhe]],<br />[[Longjing, Jilin|Longjing]], Yanbian||[[Hoeryong]],<br />North Hamgyong|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Chaokai Railway|Chaokai Bridge]]|| [[Kaishantun]],<br />Longjing, Yanbian|| Sambong,<br />[[Onsong County|Onsong]], North Hamgyong|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Tumen Border Railway Bridge]]|| [[Tumen, Jilin|Tumen City]],<br />Yanbian|| [[Namyang Workers' District|Namyang]],<br />Onsong, North Hamgyong|| Yes|| Yes|| Opened\n|-\n| [[New Tumen Border Bridge]]|| Tumen City,<br />Yanbian|| Namyang,<br />Onsong, North Hamgyong|| Yes|| No|| Under Construction\n|-\n| [[Tumen Border Bridge|Tumen Border Road Bridge]]|| Tumen City,<br />Yanbian|| Namyang,<br />Onsong, North Hamgyong|| Yes|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Liangshui Broken Bridge]]|| [[Liangshui]],<br />Tumen, Yanbian|| Onsong,<br />North Hamgyong|| No|| No|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[East Manchuria Railway#Situation after the closure|Hunyung Railway Bridges]]|| [[Ying'an]],<br />[[Hunchun]], Yanbian|| Hunyung,<br />[[Kyongwon County|Kyongwon]], North Hamgyong|| No|| Yes|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Shatuozi Bridge]]|| [[Sanjiazi Manchu Ethnic Township|Sanjiazi]],<br />Hunchun, Yanbian|| Kyongwon,<br />North Hamgyong|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Tumen River Bridge|Quanhe-Yunting Bridge]]|| [[Jingxin]],<br />Hunchun, Yanbian|| Wonjong,<br />[[Rason]]|| Yes|| No|| \nOpened{{efn|Special entry permits are required to enter Rason instead of the standard DPRK visa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/visas-09262016154432.html| title=North Korea Fast-Tracks Entry Visas For Rason SEZ| date=2016-09-26| accessdate=2019-01-04}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| colspan=6| {{notelist}}\n|}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | total_width = 600\n\n | image1 = Txu-oclc-6654394-nj-51-5th-ed.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = Coastal border region ([[Korea Bay]]){{efn|name=\"a\"|from map: \"DELINEATION OF INTERNATIONAL BOUNDARIES MUST NOT BE CONSIDERED AUTHORITATIVE\"}}\n | image2 = Txu-oclc-6654394-nk-51-4th-ed.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = Southern/Western border region{{efn|from map: \"THE REPRESENTATION OF INTERNATIONAL BOUNDARIES ON THIS MAP IS NOT NECESSARILY AUTHORITATIVE.\"}}\n | image3 = Txu-oclc-6654394-nk-52-4th-ed.jpg\n | caption3 = Northern/Eastern border region{{efn|name=\"a\"}}\n | footer = Historical English-language maps of the China-Korea (PRC-DPRK) border from west to east (south to north) from the [[International Map of the World]] produced by the US Army's [[Army Map Service]] and the [[Defense Mapping Agency]], mid-20th century.\n }}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Border security==\n[[File:North Korean border at Dandong, China.jpg|thumb|The border at the Amnok River delta near Dandong in 2012]]\nThe 1,420&nbsp;km border between North Korea and China has been described as \"porous\".<ref name=Onishi/> Many [[North Korean defectors]] cross into China.\n\nThe Chinese government transferred responsibility for managing the border to the army from the police in 2003.<ref>Foley, James. \u201cChina Steps Up Security on North Korean Border\u201d, Jane's Intelligence Review, 1 November 2003.</ref> Chinese authorities began building wire fences \"on major defection routes along the Tumen River\" in 2003.<ref name=\"Guan\">Ng Gan Guan, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/16/AR2006101600289.html China Erects Fence Along N. Korea Border], Associated Press (October 16, 2006).</ref> Beginning in September 2006,<ref name=\"Guan\"/> China erected a {{convert|20|km}} fence on the border near Dandong, along stretches of the [[Yalu River]] delta with lower banks and narrower width.<ref name=Kanto/> The concrete and [[barbed wire]] fence ranged in height from {{convert|8|ft}} to {{convert|15|ft}}.<ref name=\"Guan\"/>\n\nIn 2007, a U.S. official stated that China was building more \"fences and installations at key border outposts\".<ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=4281 www.dailynk.com \"China Troops Increase at North Korean Border\"]</ref> In the same year, it was reported that North Korea had started building a fence along a {{convert|10|km}} stretch of its side of the [[Yalu River]], and had also built a road to guard the area.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071125105433/http://www.edmontonsun.com/News/World/2007/08/27/4449708-sun.html www.edmontonsun.com \"North Korea building fence on China border\"]</ref><ref>{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501203637/http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/front/5084232.html|archivedate=1 May 2011|url=http://chron.com/disp/story.mpl/front/5084232.html|title=Report: N. Korea building fence to keep people in|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=4 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, it was reported that China was building fences {{convert|4|m}} high near Dandong, and that {{convert|13|km}} of this new fencing had been built.  It was also reported that China was reinforcing patrols, and that new patrol posts were being built on higher ground to give wider visibility over the area. According to a resident of the area: \"It's the first time such strong border fences are being erected here. Looks like it is related to the unstable situation in North Korea.\" The resident also added that previously \"anybody could cross if they really wanted\" as the fence had only been {{convert|10|ft}} with no barbed wire.<ref>Foster, Peter and agencies, Beijing. \"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/8415490/China-builds-higher-fences-over-fears-of-instability-in-North-Korea.html China builds higher fences over fears of instability in North Korea].\" ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. March 30, 2011. Retrieved on October 26, 2012.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.chinapost.com.tw/china/national-news/2011/03/31/296806/China-boosts.htm China boosts North Korea border fence].\" ''[[The China Post]]''. Thursday March 31, 2011. Retrieved on October 26, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2014, journalist who visited [[Dandong]] reported a low level of security.<ref>[http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/09/18/comment-absurdities-faced-north-korean-refugees-china Comment: The absurdities faced by North Korean refugees in China]</ref> In 2015, fencing was reported as the exception rather than the rule.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2015/02/the-myth-of-a-sealed-china-n-korea-border/|title=The myth of a sealed China-N. Korea border|author=Rob York|work=NK News|date=25 February 2015}}</ref> In 2015, a photojournalist who traveled along the Chinese side of the border commented that fencing was rare and that it would be easy to cross the Amnok river when it was frozen. The same report noted friendly contact between people on opposite sides of the border.<ref>{{cite news|title=A trip to the North Korea-China border, in photos|url=https://www.nknews.org/2015/05/a-trip-to-the-north-korea-china-border-in-photos/|work=NK News|date=29 May 2015}}</ref> In 2018, a photojournalist drove along the border and described it as \"mile after mile of nothing, guarded by no-one\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/a-road-trip-on-the-edge-of-north-korea|title=A road trip on the edge of North Korea|first=Damir|last=Sagolj|work=Reuters|date=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a single rogue North Korean soldier killed four [[Koreans in China|ethnic Korean citizens of China]] who lived along the border of China with North Korea.<ref>https://www.yahoo.com/news/runaway-n-korean-soldier-kill-four-chinese-reports-060526414.html?bcmt=1420505551797-974622bd-2486-431b-8e29-2290873790fc&ref=gs https://www.yahoo.com/news/china-village-defenceless-against-north-korean-intruders-055043942.html?ref=gs</ref>\n\n[[File:\u5de1\u9053\u5de5\u51fa\u54c1 photo by Xundaogong \u56fe\u4eec\u6c5f\u94c1\u8def\u6865 - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|Railway bridge over the [[Tumen River]]]]\nRumours of Chinese troop mobilizations on the border frequently circulate in times of heightened tension on the Korean peninsula. According to scholar Adam Cathcart, these rumours are hard to substantiate and hard to interpret.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tigers in the Haze: Chinese Troops on the Border with North Korea in the 'April Crisis'|url=https://jamestown.org/program/tigers-haze-chinese-troops-border-north-korea-april-crisis/|first=Adam|last=Cathcart|publisher=China Brief, Jamestown University|date=20 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nA leaked [[China Mobile]] document that went viral on Chinese social media on 7 December 2017 allegedly revealed Chinese government plans to construct five \"refugee settlement points\" along the border to North Korea in [[Changbai Korean Autonomous County|Changbai county]] and [[Jilin]] province.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3afb2902-dbd9-11e7-a039-c64b1c09b482|title=US-North Korea tensions fuel fears on Chinese border|last=|first=|date=10 December 2017|website=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/11/world/asia/china-north-korea-border.html|title=Fearing the Worst, China Plans Refugee Camps on North Korean Border|last=Perlez|first=Jane|date=2017-12-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> This was apparently in preparation for a large influx of North Korean [[refugee]]s if the [[Kim Jong-un|Kim]] regime collapsed in a potential conflict with the [[United States]]. ''[[The Guardian]]'' quoted the document: \"Due to cross-border tensions \u2026 the [Communist] party committee and government of Changbai county has proposed setting up five refugee camps in the county.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/12/china-refugee-camps-border-north-korea|title=China building network of refugee camps along border with North Korea|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2017-12-12|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-13|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|China|North Korea|Politics}}\n*[[North Korean defectors]]\n*[[China\u2013North Korea relations]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|China-North Korea border}}\n*[http://sinonk.com/category/ttp/ The Tumen River Documentation Project] at Sino-NK\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8wRLQ8MVi0Q|title=An Inconvenient Border: Where China Meets North Korea|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=2016-09-26}}\n* [https://fall.law.fsu.edu/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS017.pdf China-Korea Boundary]\n{{China \u2013 North Korea border crossings}}\n{{Borders of China}}\n{{Borders of North Korea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:China-North Korea border}}\n[[Category:China\u2013North Korea border| ]]\n[[Category:Borders of China]]\n[[Category:Borders of North Korea]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox\n| title  = China\u2013North Korea border\n| image  = [[File:Border stone china-corea.jpg|frameless]]\n| caption = Inscription stone marking the border of China and North Korea in [[Jilin]]\n| data1  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n| s      = \u4e2d\u671d\u8fb9\u5883\n| t      = \u4e2d\u671d\u908a\u5883\n| p      = Zh\u014dng\u2013Ch\u00e1o Bi\u0101nj\u00ecng}}\n| data2  = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes|context=north\n| hangul = \uc870\uc120\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc8fc\uc758\uc778\ubbfc\uacf5\ud654\uad6d-\uc911\ud654\uc778\ubbfc\uacf5\ud654\uad6d \uad6d\uacbd\n| hanja  = \u671d\u9bae\u6c11\u4e3b\u4e3b\u7fa9\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u00b7\u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b \u570b\u5883\n| mr     = Chos\u014fn Minjuju\u016di Inmin Konghwaguk\u119e \u2013 Chunghwa Inmin Konghwaguk Kukky\u014fng\n| rr     = Joseon Minjujuui Inmin Gonghwaguk \u2013 Junghwa Inmin Gonghwaguk Gukgyeong}}\n}}\n\nThe '''China\u2013North Korea border''' is the international border separating the People's Republic of [[China]] (PRC) and the [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]] (North Korea).\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:SinoKorea Friendship Bridge.jpg|thumb|[[Sino-Korean Friendship Bridge]] (right), linking [[Dandong]] with North Korea]]\nThe border is {{convert|880|mi|km|disp=flip}} long.<ref name=Onishi>Onishi, Norimitsu. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/22/weekinreview/22marsh.html?_r=0 Tension, Desperation: The China-North Korean Border].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. October 22, 2006. Retrieved on October 23, 2012.</ref> From west to east, the [[Yalu River]],<ref name=Kanto>Kanto, Dick K. and Mark E. Manyin. [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/R41043.pdf China-North Korea Relations], Congressional Research Service (December 28, 2010).</ref> [[Paektu Mountain]], and the [[Tumen River]] divides the two countries.\n\n[[Dandong]], in the [[Liaoning]] Province of China, on the [[Yalu River]] delta, is the largest city on the border.<ref>Rogers, Jenny. \"[http://www.goldcoast.com.au/article/2012/10/02/439048_gold-coast-business.html New group reaches out to China].\" ''[[Gold Coast Bulletin]]''. October 2, 2012. Retrieved on October 23, 2012.</ref> On the other side of the river is the city of [[Sinuiju]] in [[North Pyongan Province]], North Korea. The two cities are situated on the Amnok river delta at the western end of the border, near the [[Yellow Sea]]. Their waterfronts face each other and are connected by the [[Sino-Korean Friendship Bridge]].\n\nThere are 205 islands on the Amnok River. A 1962 border treaty between North Korea and China split the islands according to which ethnic group were living on each island. North Korea possesses 127 and China 78. Due to the division criteria, some islands such as [[Hwanggumpyong Island]] belong to North Korea even though they are on the Chinese side of the river. Both countries have navigation rights on the river, including in the delta.\n\nThe source of the Amnok River is [[Heaven Lake]] on [[Paektu Mountain]], which is considered the birthplace of the Korean and [[Manchu people]]s. This lake is also the source of the [[Tumen River]] which forms the eastern portion of the border.\n\nThere are a significant number of ethnic Koreans in Northeast China, particularly in the [[Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture]].\n\n==Trade and contact==\n[[File:Beijing to Pyongyang train.jpg| thumb|The Beijing\u2013Pyongyang passenger train passes Dandong]]\nIts border with China has been described as North Korea's \"lifeline to the outside world.\"<ref name=Onishi/> Much of the China-North Korea trade goes through the port of Dandong.<ref name=Kanto/>\n\nChinese cell phone service has been known to extend as far as {{convert|10|km|abbr=on|0}} into Korean territory, which has led to the development of a black market for Chinese cell phones in the border regions. International calls are strictly forbidden in North Korea, and violators put themselves at considerable peril to acquire such phones.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20445632 North Korea: On the net in world's most secretive nation (BBC)]</ref>\n\nTourists in Dandong can take speedboat rides along the North Korean side of the Amnok River and up its tributaries.<ref>{{cite new|title=A trip to the North Korea-China border, in photos|url=https://www.nknews.org/2015/05/a-trip-to-the-north-korea-china-border-in-photos/|publisher=NK News|date=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nA common wedding day event for many Chinese couples involve renting boats, putting [[Personal flotation device|life preserver]]s on over their wedding clothes, and going to the North Korean border to have wedding photos taken.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hessler|first=Peter|title=Oracle Bones|url=https://archive.org/details/oraclebonesjourn00hess_0|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=Harper Perennial|location=New York et al.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/oraclebonesjourn00hess_0/page/62 62]}}</ref>\n\nMemory cards and teddy bears are reportedly among the most popular items for North Koreans shopping in Dandong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/article/thanks-memory-cards-north-koreans-return-china/|title=Thanks for the memory cards; North Koreans return from China|last=Reuters|first=|date=4 December 2016|website=www.atimes.com|publisher=|access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Crossings==\n[[File:Jian friendship bridge 2011 07 24.jpg|thumb|The Ji'an Railway Bridge between [[Ji'an, Jilin|Ji'an]], [[Jilin]] Province and [[Manpo]], [[Chagang Province]] of North Korea.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=6| China-North Korea Border Crossings\n|-\n! Name\n! style=\"width: 20%| Bordering<br />Chinese town\n! style=\"width: 20%| Bordering<br />Korean town\n! Open to<br />[[third country national|third<br />country<br />nationals]]\n! style=\"width: 5%| Railway crossing\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Hwanggumpyong Island]]|| [[Tangchi, Dandong|Tangchi]],<br />[[Zhenxing District|Zhenxing]], [[Dandong]]|| [[Sindo County|Sindo]],<br /> [[North Pyongan Province]]|| No|| No|| Planned\n|-\n| [[New Yalu River Bridge]]|| Tangchi,<br />Zhenxing, Dandong|| [[Sinuiju]],<br />North Pyongan|| Yes|| No|| Under construction\n|-\n| [[Yalu River Broken Bridge]]|| Tangchi,<br />Zhenxing, Dandong|| Sinuiju,<br />North Pyongan|| No|| No|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Sino-Korean Friendship Bridge]]|| Tangchi,<br />Zhenxing, Dandong|| Sinuiju,<br />North Pyongan|| Yes|| Yes|| Opened{{efn|There are four weekly trains with hard and soft sleepers from Beijing to [[Pyongyang]] via the Sino\u2013Korean Friendship Bridge, as well as a weekly carriage attached to the Vladivostok train from Moscow, via Harbin, Shenyang, and Dandong.<ref name=TransSiberian>[https://archive.is/20140527173015/http://www.koreakonsult.com/transsiberian_eng.html \"Trans-Siberian Railway Tours\"] Accessed 2014-05-25</ref>}} \n|-\n| [[Yalu River Broken Wooden Pontoon]]|| [[Zhenzhu Subdistrict]],<br />[[Zhen'an District|Zhen'an]], Dandong|| Sinuiju,<br />North Pyongan|| No|| Yes|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Hekou Broken Bridge]]|| [[Changdian]],<br />[[Kuandian Manchu Autonomous County|Kuandian]], Dandong|| [[Sakchu County]],<br />North Pyongan|| No|| No|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Upper Hekou Railway Bridge]]|| Changdian,<br />Kuandian, Dandong|| Sakju,<br />North Pyongan|| No|| Yes|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Ji'an Yalu River Border Railway Bridge|Ji'an Railway Bridge]]|| [[Ji'an, Jilin|Ji'an City]],<br />[[Tonghua]]|| [[Manpo]],<br />[[Chagang Province|Chagang]]|| No|| Yes|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Ji'an Yalu River Road Bridge|Ji'an Road Bridge]]|| Ji'an City,<br />Tonghua|| Manpo,<br />Chagang|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Chagang Samgang Station|Chagang Samgang Railway Bridge]]|| [[Yunfeng Lake]],<br />Ji'an, Tonghua|| Manpo,<br />Chagang|| No|| Yes|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Kuunbong Station|Kuunbong Railway Bridge]]|| Yunfeng Lake,<br />Ji'an, Tonghua|| [[Chasong County|Chasong]],<br />Chagang|| No|| Yes|| Defunct\n|-\n| [[Linjiang Yalu River Bridge]]|| [[Linjiang]] City,<br />[[Baishan]]|| [[Chunggang County|Chunggang]],<br />Chagang|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Changbai\u2013Hyesan International Bridge|Changbai-Hyesan Bridge]]|| [[Changbai Korean Autonomous County|Changbai]],<br />Baishan|| [[Hyesan]],<br />[[Ryanggang Province]]|| No|| No|| Opened\n|-\n| [[Karim Bridge]]|| 