mits are required to enter Rason instead of the standard DPRK visa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/visas-09262016154432.html| title=North Korea Fast-Tracks Entry Visas For Rason SEZ| date=2016-09-26| accessdate=2019-01-04}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| colspan=6| {{notelist}}\n|}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | total_width = 600\n\n | image1 = Txu-oclc-6654394-nj-51-5th-ed.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = Coastal border region ([[Korea Bay]]){{efn|name=\"a\"|from map: \"DELINEATION OF INTERNATIONAL BOUNDARIES MUST NOT BE CONSIDERED AUTHORITATIVE\"}}\n | image2 = Txu-oclc-6654394-nk-51-4th-ed.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = Southern/Western border region{{efn|from map: \"THE REPRESENTATION OF INTERNATIONAL BOUNDARIES ON THIS MAP IS NOT NECESSARILY AUTHORITATIVE.\"}}\n | image3 = Txu-oclc-6654394-nk-52-4th-ed.jpg\n | caption3 = Northern/Eastern border region{{efn|name=\"a\"}}\n | footer = Historical English-language maps of the China-Korea (PRC-DPRK) border from west to east (south to north) from the [[International Map of the World]] produced by the US Army's [[Army Map Service]] and the [[Defense Mapping Agency]], mid-20th century.\n }}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Border security==\n[[File:North Korean border at Dandong, China.jpg|thumb|The border at the Amnok River delta near Dandong in 2012]]\nThe 1,420&nbsp;km border between North Korea and China has been described as \"porous\".<ref name=Onishi/> Many [[North Korean defectors]] cross into China.\n\nThe Chinese government transferred responsibility for managing the border to the army from the police in 2003.<ref>Foley, James. \u201cChina Steps Up Security on North Korean Border\u201d, Jane's Intelligence Review, 1 November 2003.</ref> Chinese authorities began building wire fences \"on major defection routes along the Tumen River\" in 2003.<ref name=\"Guan\">Ng Gan Guan, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/16/AR2006101600289.html China Erects Fence Along N. Korea Border], Associated Press (October 16, 2006).</ref> Beginning in September 2006,<ref name=\"Guan\"/> China erected a {{convert|20|km}} fence on the border near Dandong, along stretches of the [[Yalu River]] delta with lower banks and narrower width.<ref name=Kanto/> The concrete and [[barbed wire]] fence ranged in height from {{convert|8|ft}} to {{convert|15|ft}}.<ref name=\"Guan\"/>\n\nIn 2007, a U.S. official stated that China was building more \"fences and installations at key border outposts\".<ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=4281 www.dailynk.com \"China Troops Increase at North Korean Border\"]</ref> In the same year, it was reported that North Korea had started building a fence along a {{convert|10|km}} stretch of its side of the [[Yalu River]], and had also built a road to guard the area.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071125105433/http://www.edmontonsun.com/News/World/2007/08/27/4449708-sun.html www.edmontonsun.com \"North Korea building fence on China border\"]</ref><ref>{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501203637/http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/front/5084232.html|archivedate=1 May 2011|url=http://chron.com/disp/story.mpl/front/5084232.html|title=Report: N. Korea building fence to keep people in|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=4 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, it was reported that China was building fences {{convert|4|m}} high near Dandong, and that {{convert|13|km}} of this new fencing had been built.  It was also reported that China was reinforcing patrols, and that new patrol posts were being built on higher ground to give wider visibility over the area. According to a resident of the area: \"It's the first time such strong border fences are being erected here. Looks like it is related to the unstable situation in North Korea.\" The resident also added that previously \"anybody could cross if they really wanted\" as the fence had only been {{convert|10|ft}} with no barbed wire.<ref>Foster, Peter and agencies, Beijing. \"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/8415490/China-builds-higher-fences-over-fears-of-instability-in-North-Korea.html China builds higher fences over fears of instability in North Korea].\" ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. March 30, 2011. Retrieved on October 26, 2012.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.chinapost.com.tw/china/national-news/2011/03/31/296806/China-boosts.htm China boosts North Korea border fence].\" ''[[The China Post]]''. Thursday March 31, 2011. Retrieved on October 26, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2014, journalist who visited [[Dandong]] reported a low level of security.<ref>[http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/09/18/comment-absurdities-faced-north-korean-refugees-china Comment: The absurdities faced by North Korean refugees in China]</ref> In 2015, fencing was reported as the exception rather than the rule.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2015/02/the-myth-of-a-sealed-china-n-korea-border/|title=The myth of a sealed China-N. Korea border|author=Rob York|work=NK News|date=25 February 2015}}</ref> In 2015, a photojournalist who traveled along the Chinese side of the border commented that fencing was rare and that it would be easy to cross the Amnok river when it was frozen. The same report noted friendly contact between people on opposite sides of the border.<ref>{{cite news|title=A trip to the North Korea-China border, in photos|url=https://www.nknews.org/2015/05/a-trip-to-the-north-korea-china-border-in-photos/|work=NK News|date=29 May 2015}}</ref> In 2018, a photojournalist drove along the border and described it as \"mile after mile of nothing, guarded by no-one\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/a-road-trip-on-the-edge-of-north-korea|title=A road trip on the edge of North Korea|first=Damir|last=Sagolj|work=Reuters|date=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a single rogue North Korean soldier killed four [[Koreans in China|ethnic Korean citizens of China]] who lived along the border of China with North Korea.<ref>https://www.yahoo.com/news/runaway-n-korean-soldier-kill-four-chinese-reports-060526414.html?bcmt=1420505551797-974622bd-2486-431b-8e29-2290873790fc&ref=gs https://www.yahoo.com/news/china-village-defenceless-against-north-korean-intruders-055043942.html?ref=gs</ref>\n\n[[File:\u5de1\u9053\u5de5\u51fa\u54c1 photo by Xundaogong \u56fe\u4eec\u6c5f\u94c1\u8def\u6865 - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|Railway bridge over the [[Tumen River]]]]\nRumours of Chinese troop mobilizations on the border frequently circulate in times of heightened tension on the Korean peninsula. According to scholar Adam Cathcart, these rumours are hard to substantiate and hard to interpret.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tigers in the Haze: Chinese Troops on the Border with North Korea in the 'April Crisis'|url=https://jamestown.org/program/tigers-haze-chinese-troops-border-north-korea-april-crisis/|first=Adam|last=Cathcart|publisher=China Brief, Jamestown University|date=20 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nA leaked [[China Mobile]] document that went viral on Chinese social media on 7 December 2017 allegedly revealed Chinese government plans to construct five \"refugee settlement points\" along the border to North Korea in [[Changbai Korean Autonomous County|Changbai county]] and [[Jilin]] province.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3afb2902-dbd9-11e7-a039-c64b1c09b482|title=US-North Korea tensions fuel fears on Chinese border|last=|first=|date=10 December 2017|website=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/11/world/asia/china-north-korea-border.html|title=Fearing the Worst, China Plans Refugee Camps on North Korean Border|last=Perlez|first=Jane|date=2017-12-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> This was apparently in preparation for a large influx of North Korean [[refugee]]s if the [[Kim Jong-un|Kim]] regime collapsed in a potential conflict with the [[United States]]. ''[[The Guardian]]'' quoted the document: \"Due to cross-border tensions \u2026 the [Communist] party committee and government of Changbai county has proposed setting up five refugee camps in the county.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/12/china-refugee-camps-border-north-korea|title=China building network of refugee camps along border with North Korea|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2017-12-12|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-13|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|China|North Korea|Politics}}\n*[[North Korean defectors]]\n*[[China\u2013North Korea relations]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|China-North Korea border}}\n*[http://sinonk.com/category/ttp/ The Tumen River Documentation Project] at Sino-NK\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8wRLQ8MVi0Q|title=An Inconvenient Border: Where China Meets North Korea|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=2016-09-26}}\n* [https://fall.law.fsu.edu/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS017.pdf China-Korea Boundary]\n{{China \u2013 North Korea border crossings}}\n{{Borders of China}}\n{{Borders of North Korea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:China-North Korea border}}\n[[Category:China\u2013North Korea border| ]]\n[[Category:Borders of China]]\n[[Category:Borders of North Korea]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "name_user": "WhisperToMe", "label": "safe", "comment": "Simplified first", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/China%E2%80%93North_Korea_border"}
{"title_page": "Patricia Bethune", "text_new": "{{short description|American film and television actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Patricia Bethune\n| image        =  \n|caption= \n|birth_name = Patricia Anne Bethune\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|7|27}}\n| birth_place  = U.S.\n| education    =  \n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1995\u2013present\n}}\n'''Patricia Bethune''' (born  July 27, 1956) is an American television actress. In 2019, she received [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Guest Performer in a Drama Series]] at the [[46th Daytime Emmy Awards]] for her recurring performance as evil Nurse Mary Pat on the ABC daytime soap opera, ''[[General Hospital]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soapoperanetwork.com/2019/05/introducing-daytime-emmy-award-winner-patricia-bethune|title=Introducing Daytime Emmy Award Winner Patricia Bethune|first=Errol|last=Lewis|date=May 10, 2019|website=Soap Opera Network}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/entertainment/review-patricia-bethune-wins-2019-emmy-award-for-general-hospital/article/549200|title=Review: Patricia Bethune wins 2019 Emmy Award for 'General Hospital' (Includes first-hand account)|date=May 6, 2019|website=www.digitaljournal.com}}</ref>\n\nBethune has appeared in a more than 50 television shows, include ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', ''[[Mad Men]]'' and ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''. From 2008 to 2014, she had a recurring role as Jane Bodehouse in the HBO horror drama series, ''[[True Blood]]''.<ref>https://www.trueblood-online.com/the-vault-exclusive-patricia-bethune-is-a-perfect-fit-for-jane-bodehouse/</ref> She also had recurring roles on ''[[The Norm Show]]'', ''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]'' and ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''.\n\nBethune also appeared in a number of films, include ''[[The Lost World: Jurassic Park]]'' (1997), ''[[Beyond the Reach]]'' (2014) and ''[[The Open House]]'' (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_open_house_2018|title=The Open House (2018)|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0404656}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Special Guest Performer}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film and television actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Patricia Bethune\n| image        =  \n|caption= \n|birth_name = Patricia Anne Bethune\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|7|27}}\n| birth_place  = U.S.\n| education    =  \n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1995\u2013present\n}}\n'''Patricia Bethune''' (born  July 27, 1956) is an American television actress. In 2019, she received [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Guest Performer in a Drama Series]] at the [[46th Daytime Emmy Awards]] for her recurring performance as evil Nurse Mary Pat on the ABC daytime soap opera, ''[[General Hospital]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soapoperanetwork.com/2019/05/introducing-daytime-emmy-award-winner-patricia-bethune|title=Introducing Daytime Emmy Award Winner Patricia Bethune|first=Errol|last=Lewis|date=May 10, 2019|website=Soap Opera Network}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/entertainment/review-patricia-bethune-wins-2019-emmy-award-for-general-hospital/article/549200|title=Review: Patricia Bethune wins 2019 Emmy Award for 'General Hospital' (Includes first-hand account)|date=May 6, 2019|website=www.digitaljournal.com}}</ref>\n\nBethune has appeared in a more than 50 television shows, include ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', ''[[Mad Men]]'' and ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''. From 2008 to 2014, she had a recurring role as Jane Bodehouse in the HBO horror drama series, ''[[True Blood]]''.<ref>https://www.trueblood-online.com/the-vault-exclusive-patricia-bethune-is-a-perfect-fit-for-jane-bodehouse/</ref> She also had recurring roles on ''[[The Norm Show]]'', ''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]'' and ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''.\n\nBethune also appeared in a number of films, include ''[[The Lost World: Jurassic Park]]'' (1997), ''[[Beyond the Reach]]'' (2014) and ''[[The Open House]]'' (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_open_house_2018|title=The Open House (2018)|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0404656}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Special Guest Performer}}\n\n{{US-actor-stub}}\n\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patricia_Bethune"}
